{"title_page": "Penalty shoot-out (association football)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n\nA '''penalty shoot-out''' (officially '''kicks from the penalty mark''')<ref name=\"Laws\">{{cite web|title=Laws of the Game 2016/2017|url=http://static-3eb8.kxcdn.com/documents/60/Laws%20of%20the%20Game_16-17_Digital_Eng.pdf|author=IFAB|authorlink=International Football Association Board|publisher=[[IFAB]]|location=[[Zurich]]|accessdate=27 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911032912/http://static-3eb8.kxcdn.com/documents/60/Laws%20of%20the%20Game_16-17_Digital_Eng.pdf|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a method of determining which team is awarded victory in an [[association football]] match that cannot end in a [[tie (draw)|draw]], when the score is tied after the regulation playing time as well as [[overtime (sports)|extra time]] (if used) have expired. In a penalty shoot-out, each team takes turns shooting at goal from the penalty mark, with the goal only defended by the opposing team's goalkeeper. Each team has five shots which must be taken by different kickers; the team that makes more successful kicks is declared the victor. Shoot-outs finish as soon as one team has an insurmountable lead. If scores are level after five pairs of shots, the shootout progresses into additional \"sudden-death\" rounds.<ref name=\"Laws\" /> Balls successfully kicked into the goal during a shoot-out do not count as goals for the individual kickers or the team, and are tallied separately from the goals scored during normal play (including extra time, if any). Although the procedure for each individual kick in the shoot-out resembles that of a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], there are some differences. Most notably, neither the kicker nor any player other than the [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] may play the ball again once it has been kicked.\n\nThe penalty shoot-out is one of the three methods of breaking a draw that are currently approved by the [[Laws of the Game (association football)|Laws of the Game]]; the others are extra time and, for [[two-legged tie]]s, the [[away goals rule]].<ref name=\"Laws\" /> A shoot-out is usually used only after one or more of the other methods fail to produce a winner. The method of breaking a draw for a specific match is determined beforehand by the match organizing body. In most professional level competitions, two 15-minute extra time periods are played if the score is tied at the end of regulation time, and a shoot-out is held if the score is still tied after the extra time periods.\n\nAlthough widely employed in football since the 1970s, penalty shoot-outs have been widely criticized by many followers of the game, due primarily to their perceived reliance on [[luck]] rather than skill and their dependence on individual duels between opposing players, which is arguably not in keeping with football as a [[team sport]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Wilson, M|author2=Wood, G|author3=Jordet, G.|title=The BASES Expert Statement on the Psychological Preparation for Football Penalty Shootouts|url=http://www.bases.org.uk/write/545_Expert_statement_on_Psychological_preparation_for_Football_penalty_shootouts.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106200749/http://www.bases.org.uk/write/545_Expert_statement_on_Psychological_preparation_for_Football_penalty_shootouts.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 January 2016|publisher=British Association of Sports and Exercise Sciences|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> Conversely, some believe the pressure and unpredictability involved makes it one of the most thrilling finales to any sport.<ref>{{Cite web |title=World Cup shootouts are great and here is how other sports can adopt the thrilling finale |quote=But all those things combine to make it dramatic and compulsive viewing, the ultimate element of instant unpredictability, a quick fix for both the \u201cshort attention span\u201d generation and all the ones before it, too. Shootouts provide all the things we like about sports. Heroes stepping into the spotlight with a single moment of brilliant or fortune. Sympathetic figures who your heart bleeds for. |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/columnist/martin-rogers/2018/07/01/world-cup-how-nfl-nba-mlb-get-soccer-shootout/749658002/ |work=USA Today |date=1 July 2018 |accessdate=2018-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Goalmouth Scramble: 10 'important' thoughts on the World Cup |quote=Nothing beats penalty shootouts for drama. And how great was the camera pivot to capture Manchester United legend Peter Schmeichel's reactions every time his son Kasper saved a penalty for Denmark? Truly gripping theatre. |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12081702 |work=New Zealand Herald |date=2 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nDuring a shoot-out, players other than the kicker and the goalkeepers must remain in the centre circle.<ref name=\"Laws\" /> The kicking team's goalkeeper stands at the intersection of the goal line and the line marking the penalty area ({{convert|16.5|m|yd|0|abbr=in|disp=x|/}}) near one of the assistant referees. Goals scored during the shoot-out are not commonly added to the goalscoring records of the players involved.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nA draw is a common result in football. Shoot-outs are only used in competitions that require a match-winner at the end of the game<ref name=\"Laws\" /> \u2013 this is predominantly in [[single-elimination tournament|knockout \"cup\" ties]], as opposed to [[round-robin tournament|round-robin \"leagues\"]]; they decide which team progresses to the next round of a tournament, or win it. Usually [[extra time]] has been played first, but this is not necessary;<ref name=\"Laws\" /> exceptions include the [[Copa Libertadores]], [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] (quarter-finals, semi-finals, and third-place game), [[FA Community Shield]] and the [[Football League Trophy]], all of which use shoot-outs straight after the end of normal time.\n\nThe rules of some competitions provide that a shoot-out may be used to decide placings in a round-robin group, in the unusual event that two teams who have faced each other in a final-day match finish the group with identical statistics, and no other teams has the same record. This was invoked in Group A of the [[2003 UEFA Women's Under-19 Championship]], in which Italy and Sweden held a shootout immediately after their drawn match.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eur-women-u19-03.html\n |title=European Women U-19 Championship 2002\u201303\n |last=Duret\n |first=S\u00e9bastien\n |author2=David Matishen\n |author3=Herv\u00e9 Morard\n |author4=Lars Aarhus\n |author5=Erik Garin\n |author6=Sturmius Burkert\n |date=14 February 2004\n |website=[[RSSSF]]\n |accessdate=2009-10-14\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121021024/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eur-women-u19-03.html\n |archivedate=21 January 2010\n |df=dmy\n }}\n</ref> This rule is a recent innovation, and for example did not apply in [[1990 FIFA World Cup#Group F|Group F of the 1990 World Cup]], where the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] were separated by drawing of lots immediately after drawing their final-day match.<ref>{{cite book |author=FIFA Technical Study Group |title=FIFA World Cup Italia'90: Official Report |publisher=FIFA |year=1990 |page=59 |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/techdevp/fwc_italy_1990_a_part2_277.pdf |quote=So the last two matches in Group F would decide whether teams could proceed forward by their own efforts, or make FIFA resort to drawing lots in Rome. [..] Ireland and Holland fought yet another 1\u20131 result and the draw in Rome placed Ireland in second place and Holland third. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924153727/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/techdevp/fwc_italy_1990_a_part2_277.pdf |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nSeveral leagues, such as the [[J.League]],<ref>{{cite book|author1=Hirata, T.|author2=Szymanski, S.|editor1-last=Lee|editor1-first=YH|editor2-last=Fort|editor2-first=R|title=The Sports Business in The Pacific Rim|publisher=Sports Economics, Management and Policy|chapter=The J. League and the World Cup}}</ref> have experimented with penalty shoot-outs immediately following a drawn league match, with the winner being awarded an extra [[points (association football)|point]]. In the United States and Canada, [[Major League Soccer]] initially also had a shoot-out immediately following the end of full-time, even during league matches, although these shoot-outs differed from standard penalty shoot-outs (see below).\n\nA team that loses a penalty shoot-out is eliminated from the tournament but it does not count as a defeat, while the winning team in the shoot-out advances or is crowned champion but does not get a match victory. For instance, the Netherlands are considered to have concluded the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] undefeated, despite being eliminated at the semi-final stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=7/news=van-gaal-we-can-still-make-history-2403702.html|title=Van Gaal: We can still make history|last=FIFA.com|date=11 July 2014|website=fifa.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129004925/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=7/news=van-gaal-we-can-still-make-history-2403702.html|archivedate=29 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Procedure==\n[[File:Hearts vs. Gretna Scottish Cup final.jpg|thumb|[[Steven Pressley]] scores for [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] against [[Gretna FC|Gretna]] in the [[2006 Scottish Cup Final]] shoot-out]]\n[[File:Penalty kick Lahm Cech Champions League Final 2012.jpg|thumb|[[Philipp Lahm]] is about to score in the [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final]]]]\n[[File:Didier Drogba Manuel Neuer last penalty kick Champions League Final 2012.jpg|thumb|Deciding penalty kick of [[Didier Drogba]] in the [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final]]]]\n\nThe following is a summary of the procedure for kicks from the penalty mark. The procedure is specified in Law 10 (\"Determining the Outcome of a Match\") of the IFAB's ''Laws of the Game'' document (p.&nbsp;71).<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n\n# The referee tosses a coin to decide the goal at which the kicks will be taken.  The choice of goal by the coin toss winner may only be changed by the referee for safety reasons or if the goal or playing surface becomes unusable.<ref name=\"Laws\"/>\n# The referee tosses the coin a second time to determine which team will take the first kick.\n# All players other than the kicker and the goalkeepers must remain in the [[Association football pitch|pitch]]'s centre circle (see above).\n# Each kick will be taken in the general manner of a penalty kick. Each kick will be taken from the [[Penalty area|penalty mark]], which is {{convert|11|m|yd|abbr=in}} from the goal line and equidistant from each touch line, with the goal defended only by the opposing goalkeeper. The goalkeeper must remain between the goal posts on his goal line until the ball has been kicked, although he can jump in place, wave his arms, move side to side along the goal line or otherwise try to distract the shooter.\n# Each team is responsible for selecting from the eligible players the order in which they will take the kicks.\n# Each kicker can kick the ball only once. Once kicked, the kicker may not play the ball again. The decision on a re-kick is solely at the referee's discretion.\n# No other player on either team, other than the designated kicker and goalkeeper, may touch the ball.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# A kick is successful if, having been touched once by the kicker, the ball crosses the goal line between the goal posts and under the crossbar, without touching any player, official, or outside agent other than the defending goalkeeper. The ball may touch the goalkeeper, goal posts, or crossbar any number of times before going into the goal as long as the referee believes the ball's motion is the result of the initial kick. This was clarified after an incident in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]] shoot-out between [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[France national football team|France]]. [[Bruno Bellone]]'s kick rebounded out off the post, hit goalkeeper [[Carlos Roberto Gallo|Carlos]]'s back, and subsequently bounced into the goal. Referee [[Ioan Igna]] gave the goal to France, and Brazil captain [[Edino Nazareth Filho|Edinho]] was booked for protesting that the kick should have been considered a miss as soon as it rebounded off the post. In 1987, the [[International Football Association Board]] clarified Law&nbsp;14, covering penalty kicks, to support Igna's decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.corshamref.org.uk/newsletter/news06jul.htm |date=July 2006 |title=The Corsham Referee Newsletter |first=Julian |last=Carosi |accessdate=2008-06-20 |number=31 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006164438/http://corshamref.org.uk/newsletter/news06jul.htm |archivedate=6 October 2008 }} and {{cite book |chapter-url=http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1987/1987app.pdf |title=Minutes of the AGM |author=IFAB |publisher=Soccer South Bay Referee Association |location=Llandudno |date=13 June 1987 |accessdate=29 November 2009 |pages=18\u201322 |chapter=III.8(a) Proposal by the Scottish Football Association: Law XIV\u2014Penalty Kick |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430130743/http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1987/1987app.pdf |archivedate=30 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n# Teams take turns to kick from the penalty mark until each has taken five kicks. However, if one side has scored more successful kicks than the other could possibly reach with all of its remaining kicks, the shoot-out immediately ends, regardless of the number of kicks remaining; this basis is called \"best-of-five kicks\". An example of this is the 2006 World Cup final, the shootout ended after Italy's [[Fabio Grosso]] had scored his team's fifth, despite the fact that France (on 3) still had one more to go.\n# If after five rounds of kicks the teams have an equal number of successful kicks, additional rounds of one kick each will be used until one team scores and the other misses. This is known as [[sudden death (sport)|sudden death]].\n# The team that scores the most successful kicks at the end of the shoot-out will be the winner of the match.\n# Only players who were on the pitch at the end of play or temporarily absent (injured, adjusting equipment etc.) will be allowed to participate in the shoot-out.<ref name=\"Laws\" /> If at the end of the match and before or during the kicks one side has more players on the pitch than the other, whether as a result of injury or red cards, then the side with more players must reduce its numbers to match the opponents; this is known as 'reduce to equate'. For example, if Team&nbsp;A has 11&nbsp;players but Team&nbsp;B only has 10, then Team&nbsp;A will choose one player who will not take part. Players excluded this way normally take no further part in the procedure, except that they can be used to replace an injured goalkeeper. The rule was introduced by the International Football Association Board in February 2000 because previously an eleventh kick would be taken by the eleventh (i.e. weakest) player of a full-strength team and the first (i.e. strongest) player of a sub-strength team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/developing/refereeing/news/newsid=74400.html |title=The Laws change and the game gets better |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=1 August 2000 |accessdate=2008-06-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514104336/http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/developing/refereeing/news/newsid%3D74400.html |archivedate=14 May 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> A rule change in 2016 eliminated the possibility of a team gaining such an advantage if a player is injured or sent off ''during'' the shoot-out.<ref name=\"changes2016\">{{cite web|last1=Hinch|first1=Will|title=Football Law Changes 2016/17|url=https://www.pitchero.com/blog/football-law-changes-201617|website=Pitchero|accessdate=14 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807040806/https://www.pitchero.com/blog/football-law-changes-201617|archivedate=7 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n# A team may replace a goalkeeper who becomes injured during the shoot-out with a substitute (provided the team has not already used the maximum number of substitutes allowed by the competition) or by a player previously excluded under the 'reduce to equate' provision.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# If a goalkeeper is sent off during the shoot-out, another player who finished the game must act as goalkeeper.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# If a player, other than the goalkeeper, becomes injured or is sent off during the shoot-out, then the shoot-out will continue with no substitution allowed. The opposing team must reduce its numbers accordingly.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# Any player remaining on the pitch may act as the goalkeeper, and it is ''not'' required for the same player to have acted as a goalkeeper during the game.\n# No player will be allowed to take a second kick until all other eligible players on their team have taken a first kick, including the goalkeeper.\n# If it becomes necessary for players to take another kick (because the score has remained equal after all eligible players have taken their first kick), players are not required to kick in the same order.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# Kicks from the penalty mark must not be delayed for a player who leaves the field of play. The player\u2019s kick will be forfeited (not scored) if the player does not return in time to take a kick.\n# The referee must not abandon the match if, during the kicks, a team is reduced to fewer than seven players.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n\n==Tactics==\n{{main|Penalty kick (association football)#Tactics}}\nDefending against a penalty kick is one of the most difficult tasks a goalkeeper can face. Some decide which way they will dive beforehand, giving themselves time to reach the side of the goalmouth.  A 2011 study published in the journal ''Psychological Science'' found goalkeepers dived to the right 71% of the time when their team was losing, but only 48% when ahead and 49% when tied, a phenomenon believed to be related to certain right-preferring behaviour in social mammals.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/08/02/138922339/under-pressure-soccer-goalies-tend-to-dive-right|title=Under Pressure, Soccer Goalies Tend To Dive Right|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=2011-09-03|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803010726/http://www.npr.org/2011/08/02/138922339/under-pressure-soccer-goalies-tend-to-dive-right|archivedate=3 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Others try to read the kicker's motion pattern. Kickers may attempt to feint, or delay their shot to see which way the keeper dives. Shooting high and centre, in the space that the keeper will evacuate, carries the highest risk of shooting above the bar.<ref>How to actually, seriously play soccer 2007/2008, p.130: \"Don't shoot right down the pipe\"</ref>  If a keeper blocks a penalty kick during a match, there is a danger the kicker or a teammate may score from the rebound; this is not relevant in the case of a shoot-out.\n\nSince the entire shoot-out is conducted at the same goal, the crowd behind the goal may favour one team and try to distract the other team's shooters. To forestall any potential advantage, in 2016 the Laws of the Game were modified to add a coin toss between the two teams prior to the shoot-out: the winner of the coin toss has the right to decide which goal is used for the shoot-out (previously, the decision was at the referee's discretion). The referee may change the goal only for safety reasons or if the selected goal or pitch are unusable.<ref name=\"Laws\"/>\n\nA goalkeeper may not use distracting gamesmanship such as cleaning his boots or asking the referee to see if the ball is placed properly; this risks a [[Misconduct (association football)#Cautionable offences (yellow card)|caution]] for [[unsporting conduct]]. [[Bruce Grobbelaar]]'s \"wobbly legs\" clowning distracted [[Francesco Graziani]] in the [[1984 European Cup Final]] shootout.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/football/view/258133/Euro-2012-Joe-Hart-ready-to-line-dance-for-England/|title=Euro 2012: Joe Hart will do a Bruce Grobbelaar|date=22 June 2012|work=[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]|accessdate=29 June 2012|location=London}}</ref>  The keeper is forbidden from moving off the goal line to narrow the shooter's angle; the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final]] shootout caused controversy as replays showed that both keepers got away with this, as did [[Jerzy Dudek]] in the [[2005 Champions League Final]].\n\n==History==\n===Origins===\nBefore the introduction of shoot-outs, knock-out matches level after extra time would be decided by a replay or a coin toss.\nHowever, variants of the modern shoot-out were used before then in several domestic competitions and minor tournaments.  Domestic examples include the [[Yugoslav Cup]] from 1952,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joegcupdetail.html#52 |title=Cup of Yugoslavia 1952 |first=Dinant |last=Abbink |date=6 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-07-15 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303174325/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joegcupdetail.html#52 |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> the [[Coppa Italia]] from 1958\u201359,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italcup59.html |title=Coppa Italia 1958/59 |first=Erik |last=Garin |date=28 March 2007 |accessdate=2008-07-15 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515085211/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italcup59.html |archivedate=15 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> and the Swiss inter-regional Youth Cup from 1959\u201360.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit-jugendcup.html#60 |title=Switzerland \u2013 Youth Cup 1959/60 |first=Dinant |last=Abbink |date=8 June 2000 |accessdate=2008-07-15 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915064925/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit-jugendcup.html#60 |archivedate=15 September 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>  International examples include the 1962 [[Uhrencup]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/uhren.html#62 |title=Coupe Horlog\u00e8re \u2013 Uhren Cup (Switzerland) 1962\u20132009: 1962 |first=Erik |last=Garin |date=6 November 2009 |accessdate=2011-07-14 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727042125/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/uhren.html#62 |archivedate=27 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (at the suggestion of its founder Kurt Weissbrodt),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grenchnertagblatt.ch/solothurn/grenchen/der-beweis-fuer-die-deutsche-frechheit-110695400 |title=Der Beweis f\u00fcr die deutsche Frechheit |first=Marco |last=Sansoni |language=German |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=2011-07-14 |publisher=Grenchner Tagblatt |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327160559/http://www.grenchnertagblatt.ch/solothurn/grenchen/der-beweis-fuer-die-deutsche-frechheit-110695400 |archivedate=27 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nthe final of the 1962 [[Ram\u00f3n de Carranza Trophy]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/carranza.html#62 |title=Trofeo Ram\u00f3n de Carranza (C\u00e1diz-Spain) 1955\u20132007: 1962 |first=Ra\u00fal |last=Torre |date=16 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-11 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610065753/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/carranza.html#62 |archivedate=10 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> (at the suggestion of journalist Rafael Ballester),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.as.com/opinion/articulo/don-rafael-ballester-innovador/dasftb/20060818dasdaiopi_1/Tes |title=A don Rafael Ballester, innovador |first=Alfredo |last=Rela\u00f1o |date=18 August 2006 |accessdate=2008-07-16 |language=Spanish |publisher=AS.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080630033033/http://www.as.com/opinion/articulo/don-rafael-ballester-innovador/dasftb/20060818dasdaiopi_1/Tes |archivedate=30 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> and [[Football at the Bolivarian Games#V Games|a silver medal playoff match]] between amateur teams representing [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] and [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] in the [[1965 Bolivarian Games]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bolivarianos.html\n |title=Bolivarian Games: Soccer Tournaments\n |first=Jos\u00e9 Luis\n |last=Pierrend\n |author2=Alfonzo Cornejo\n |date=3 September 2005\n |accessdate=2008-06-11\n |website=[[RSSSF]]\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425031108/http://rsssf.com/tablesb/bolivarianos.html\n |archivedate=25 April 2013\n |df=dmy\n }}\n</ref>\n\nIn major competitions, when a [[replay (sports)|replay]] or [[One-game playoff|playoff]] was not possible, ties were previously broken by drawing of lots. Examples include [[Italy national football team|Italy]]'s win over the [[USSR national football team|USSR]] in the semi-final of the [[UEFA Euro 1968|1968 European Championship]] (the final, also drawn, went to a replay).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/68e.html |title=European Championship 1968 |first=Karel |last=Stokkermans |author2=Mart\u00edn Tabeira |date=7 February 2007 |accessdate=2008-06-19 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622211438/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/68e.html |archivedate=22 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\n[[Israel]]i Yosef Dagan is credited with originating the modern shoot-out,<ref>{{cite web |title=Israeli Behind the Goal |url=http://www.infolive.tv/en/infolive.tv-10153-israelnews-israeli-behind-goal |format=[[Adobe Flash]] |publisher=infolive.tv |accessdate=2008-06-19 |language=Hebrew, English |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422055325/http://www.infolive.tv/en/infolive.tv-10153-israelnews-israeli-behind-goal |archivedate=22 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> after watching the [[Israel national football team|Israeli team]] lose a [[Football at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Olympic quarterfinal game]] against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] by drawing of lots in [[Mexico]]. Michael Almog, later president of the [[Israel FA]], described Dagan's proposal in a letter published in ''FIFA News'' in August 1969.<ref name=\"miller\">{{cite book |title=He Always Puts It To The Right: A History Of The Penalty Kick |isbn=978-0-7528-2728-5 |first=Clark |last=Miller |publisher=Orion |year=1996 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/healwaysputsitto0000mill }}\n</ref>  Koe Ewe Teik, the [[Malaysian FA]]'s member of the [[referee (association football)|referee]]'s committee, led the move for its adoption by FIFA.<ref name=\"miller\" />  FIFA's proposal was discussed on 20 February 1970 by a working party of the [[International Football Association Board]] (IFAB), which recommended its acceptance, although \"not entirely satisfied\" with it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1970/1970wpag.pdf |title=Minutes of the Working Party |author=IFAB |publisher=Soccer South Bay Referee Association |location=London |date=20 February 1970 |accessdate=29 November 2009 |page=4, \u00a712 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430131015/http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1970/1970wpag.pdf |archivedate=30 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> It was adopted by the IFAB's annual general meeting on 27 June 1970.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1970/1970min.pdf |title=Minutes of the AGM |author=IFAB |publisher=Soccer South Bay Referee Association |location=Inverness |date=27 June 1970 |accessdate=29 November 2009 |page=\u00a75(g) |nopp=y|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430093219/http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1970/1970min.pdf |archivedate=30 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> In 2006, [[Deutsche Presse-Agentur]] reported a claim by former referee [[Karl Wald]] (b. 1916), from [[Frankfurt am Main]], that he had first proposed the shoot-out in 1970 to the [[Bavaria]]n FA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stern.de/sport/wm2006/news/karl-wald-der-vater-des-elfmeterschiessens-564500.html|title=Karl Wald: Der Vater des Elfmeterschie\u00dfens|last=Hollmann|first=Christian|date=30 June 2006|work=[[Stern (magazine)|Stern]]|language=German|accessdate=13 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427085811/http://www.stern.de/sport/wm2006/news/karl-wald-der-vater-des-elfmeterschiessens-564500.html|archivedate=27 April 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Development===\nIn England, the first penalty shoot-out in a professional match took place in 1970 at [[Boothferry Park]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], between [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] during the semi-final of the [[Watney Cup]], and was won by Manchester United. The first player to take a kick was [[George Best]], and the first to miss was [[Denis Law]]. [[Ian McKechnie]], who saved Law's kick, was also the first goalkeeper to take a kick; his shot hit the crossbar and deflected over, putting Hull City out of the Cup.\n\nPenalty shoot-outs were used to decide matches in UEFA's [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] and [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] in the 1970\u201371 season. On 30 September 1970, after a 4\u20134 aggregate draw in [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1970-71#First round|the first round of the Cup Winners' Cup]], [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Honv\u00e9d]] won the first shoot-out 5\u20134 against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.linguasport.com/futbol/internacional/clubes/c2/C2_71.htm |title=Cup Winners' Cup 1970\u201371 |publisher=linguasport.com |language=English |accessdate=22 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930021314/http://www.linguasport.com/futbol/internacional/clubes/c2/C2_71.htm |archivedate=30 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> when [[Jim Forrest (footballer born 1944)|Jim Forrest]]'s shot hit the bar. Five weeks later, on 4 November 1970,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197071det.html#cc |title=European Champions' Cup and Fairs' Cup 1970\u201371 \u2013 Details |authors=Antonio Zea, Marcel Haisma |date=9 January 2008 |website=RSSSF |language=English |accessdate=22 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426213400/http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197071det.html#cc |archivedate=26 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the first ever European Cup shoot out took place between [[Everton F.C.]] and [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]], with the side from England this time being the winners 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.linguasport.com/futbol/internacional/clubes/c1/C1_71.htm |title=European Cup 1970\u201371 |publisher=linguasport.com |language=English |accessdate=22 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930021454/http://www.linguasport.com/futbol/internacional/clubes/c1/C1_71.htm |archivedate=30 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the first round of the [[European Cup 1972\u201373]], the referee prematurely ended a shoot-out between [[PFC CSKA Sofia|CSKA Sofia]] and [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]], with CSKA leading 3\u20132 but Panathinaikos having taken only four kicks. Panathinaikos complained to UEFA and the match was annulled and replayed the following month,<ref>{{cite news |title=UEFA annul Cup result  |author=[[Reuters]] |date=9 Oct 1972 |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=ProQuest |page=7 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Derby could silence their critics|last=Barham |first=Albert |date=25 Oct 1972|work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=ProQuest |page=27 }}\n</ref> with CSKA winning without the need for a shoot-out.\n\nThe final of the 1973 [[Campeonato Paulista]] ended in similar circumstances. [[Santos F.C.|Santos]] were leading [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos|Portuguesa]] 2\u20130 with each team having taken three shoot-out kicks, when referee Armando Marques mistakenly (as each team still had two shots to take, and therefore Portuguesa still had a chance of leveling the scoreline) declared Santos the winners. Portuguesa manager [[Otto Gl\u00f3ria]] quickly led his team out of the stadium; this was allegedly to ensure the shoot-out could not resume once the mistake was discovered, and that instead the match would be replayed, giving Portuguesa a better chance of victory. When Santos counter-objected to a replay, Paulista&nbsp;FA president Osvaldo Teixeira Duarte annulled the original match and declared both teams joint champions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cartaovermelho.com.br/index.php?name=News&file=article&sid=35&theme=Printer |title=Decis\u00e3o do Campeonato Paulista de 1973 |author=Reportagem CV |date=26 August 2003 |publisher=cartaovermelho.com.br |language=Portuguese |accessdate=26 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706151624/http://www.cartaovermelho.com.br/index.php?name=News&file=article&sid=35&theme=Printer |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Pel\u00e9 |author=Pel\u00e9 |author2=Orlando Duarte |author3=Alex Bellos |author4=Daniel Hahn  |title=Pel\u00e9: the autobiography |publisher=Simon & Schuster|year=2006 |isbn=978-0-7432-7583-5}}\n</ref>\n\nThe first major international tournament to be decided by a penalty shoot-out was the [[1976 European Football Championship|1976 European Championship]] final between [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[Germany national football team|West Germany]].  UEFA had made provision for a final replay two days later,<ref>{{cite news|title=Side Lines: Thomas the send-off |last=Road |first=Alan |date=20 June 1976 |work=The Observer |page=20 |publisher=ProQuest |quote=Clive Thomas ... has been asked by the European Football Federation to stay in the country to referee a possible replay of tonight's European championship between the West Germany and the Czechs in Belgrade. }}\n</ref> but the teams decided to use a shoot-out instead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Czechs owe championship to Viktor |last=Lacey |first=David |date=21 June 1976 |work=The Guardian |publisher=ProQuest |page=17 |quote=Extra time brought no more goals and so, the countries having decided against a replay on Tuesday, the tournament had to be decided on penalties.}}\n</ref> Czechoslovakia won 5\u20133, and the deciding kick was converted by [[Anton\u00edn Panenka]] with a \"[[Panenka (penalty kick)|chip]]\" after [[Uli Hoene\u00df]] had put the previous kick over the crossbar.\n\nThe first penalty shoot-out in the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] was on 9 January 1977, in [[1978 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)#First round|the first round of African qualifying]], when [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] beat [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/fifaworldcuppreliminaryhistory_byyear__13876.pdf |author=Communications Division |title=History of the FIFA World Cup Preliminary Competition (by year) |date=27 July 2007 |work=Good to Know |publisher=[[FIFA]] |page=22 |accessdate=2009-05-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615220946/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/fifaworldcuppreliminaryhistory_byyear__13876.pdf |archivedate=15 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> The first shoot-out in the finals tournament was in [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]], when [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] beat [[France national football team|France]] in the semifinal.  If [[1982 FIFA World Cup Final|the 1982 final]] had been drawn, penalties would not have applied unless the replay was also drawn;<ref>{{cite news|title=World Cup facts and figures|date=6 June 1982|work=Chicago Tribune|page=C2}}</ref><ref name=\"Norman1986\" /> from [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]], penalties were scheduled after the final as for the earlier knockout rounds.<ref name=\"Norman1986\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y0ojAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Mc8FAAAAIBAJ&dq=final%20penalties%20world-cup&pg=3134%2C4177671|title=Soccer purists blast penalty shoootouts|last=Chad|first=Norman|date=25 June 1986|work=The Palm Beach Post|page=5C|accessdate=27 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Famous incidents==\n===National team===\nThe finals of six major [[FIFA]] competitions, including two World Cups, have gone to penalty shoot-outs:\n* The [[1991 FIFA World Youth Championship]] final between [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal]] and [[Brazil national under-20 football team|Brazil]] in [[Lisbon]] was decided on a penalty shoot-out which the Portuguese won 4\u20132, with the last shot coming from [[Rui Costa]].\n*In the [[1994 FIFA World Cup Final]] at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], California, Brazil and [[Italy national football team|Italy]] ended extra time scoreless. Brazil went on to win the shoot-out 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/pwc/mr_3104.html|title=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) - FIFA.com|last=FIFA.com|website=www.fifa.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302011553/http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/pwc/mr_3104.html|archivedate=2 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*The [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup Final]] between the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]] and [[China women's national football team|China]], also at the Rose Bowl, was scoreless after extra time. The United States team won the shoot-out 5\u20134.\n*The [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final]] also went to a penalty shoot-out (after a 1\u20131 draw followed by a scoreless 30-mins. extra time) and was won by [[Italy national football team|Italy]] 5\u20133 against [[France national football team|France]] in [[Berlin]]'s [[Olympic Stadium (Berlin)|Olympic Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/match/64/mr.html|title=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) - FIFA.com|last=FIFA.com|website=www.fifa.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060811010105/http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/match/64/mr.html|archivedate=11 August 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*The [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Final]], held at [[Commerzbank Arena]] in [[Frankfurt]], went to a penalty shoot-out (after a 1\u20131 draw at full-time and a 2\u20132 draw after extra time) between the USA and [[Japan women's national football team|Japan]]. Japan won the game after scoring 3 penalties to 1 penalty by the USA.\n*The [[2013 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] final in [[Istanbul]] went to a penalty shoot-out after a 0\u20130 draw after extra time. France won the game after scoring 4 penalties to 1 penalty by Uruguay.\n\nGoalkeepers have been known to win shoot-outs by their kicking. For example, in a [[UEFA Euro 2004]] quarter-final match, [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] goalkeeper [[Ricardo (footballer, born 1976)|Ricardo]] saved a kick (without gloves) from [[England national football team|England's]] [[Darius Vassell]], and then scored the winning shot.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2004/3830451.stm | work=BBC News | title=Portugal break England hearts | date=24 June 2004 | accessdate=2010-05-22 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417090356/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2004/3830451.stm | archivedate=17 April 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Another example is [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]]'s [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Chilavert]] in the [[Copa Libertadores 1994]] finals (Chilavert had a reputation as a dead-ball specialist and scored 41 goals during his club career).\n\n[[Anton\u00edn Panenka]] ([[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]]) decided the penalty shoot-out at the final of the [[1976 European Football Championship]] against West Germany with a [[Panenka (penalty kick)|famous chip]] to the middle of the goal.\n\nEngland lost six (out of nine) penalty shoot-outs in major tournament finals, including losses to Germany in the semi-finals of the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 1996]] (the latter following a win over Spain by the same method in the previous round). After Euro 1996, England lost four more shoot-outs in a row in major tournament finals, losing to Argentina at the 1998 World Cup, Portugal at Euro 2004 and the 2006 World Cup and Italy at Euro 2012, before finally breaking their losing streak at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] against Colombia; this shootout also allowed England to progress into the quarter-finals for the first time in twelve years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2018/07/03/england-vs-colombia-world-cup-2018-live-score-harry-kane-latest/|title=England banish penalty curse to pass Colombia test and reach World Cup quarter-final: live reaction|last=Wallace|first=Sam|date=2018-07-03|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-07-03|last2=Tyers|first2=Alan|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe Netherlands, meanwhile, lost four consecutive shoot-outs; against Denmark in Euro 1992, France in Euro 1996, Brazil in the 1998 World Cup, and Italy in Euro 2000, before finally winning one against Sweden in Euro 2004. In Euro 2000, the Netherlands had two penalty kicks during the match and four attempts in the shootout but only managed to convert one kick against Italian keeper [[Francesco Toldo]]. [[Frank de Boer]] had both a penalty kick and shootout kick saved by Toldo, who also saved from [[Paul Bosvelt]] to give Italy a 3\u20131 shootout victory. The Netherlands' fortunes seemed to have improved during the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] when they defeated Costa Rica on penalty kicks in their quarter-final, only to lose again on penalties in their semi-final against Argentina.\n\nThe Italians have lost six shoot-outs in major championships, notably being eliminated from three consecutive World Cups (1990\u20131998, including the 1994 final) and the Euro 2016 quarter-finals on penalties. However, they have also won three shoot-outs, including the Euro 2000 semi-final against the Netherlands, the Euro 2012 quarter-final against England, and the 2006 World Cup Final against France.\n\nOn 16 November 2005, a place in the World Cup was directly determined by a penalty shoot-out for the first time. The [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL \u2013 OFC play-off)|qualifying playoff]] between [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] and [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] ended 1\u20131 on aggregate, with Uruguay winning the first leg 1\u20130 [[Estadio Centenario|at home]] and Australia winning the second leg at [[Stadium Australia|home]] by the same score. A scoreless 30 minutes of [[extra time]] was followed by a shoot-out, which Australia won 4\u20132.\n\nDuring the 2006 FIFA World Cup in Germany, [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] set an unwanted new record in the round&nbsp;of&nbsp;16 shoot-out against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] by failing to convert any of their penalties, losing 3\u20130. The goalkeeper [[Oleksandr Shovkovsky]] ([[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]) became the first not to concede a single goal in the penalty shoot-out, saving two of the Swiss attempts, with another shot hitting the crossbar. The result meant that Switzerland became the first nation to be eliminated from the World Cup without conceding any goals (and, moreover, the only nation to participate in a World Cup finals tournament without conceding a goal).\n\nThe same competition featured a shoot-out between Germany and Argentina, the two most successful teams up to that point in terms of World Cup finals penalty shoot-outs: each team had competed in 3 shoot-outs and won all of them. Germany won the shoot-out, leaving Germany alone with a 4\u20130 record in World Cup finals.\n\nOn 20 June 2007, a new UEFA record was established.<ref>{{cite web\n|work=UEFA.com\n|title=Netherlands News\n|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/news/kind=1/newsid=548583.html\n|accessdate=2007-08-21\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017163842/http://uefa.com/competitions/euro/news/kind%3D1/newsid%3D548583.html\n|archivedate=17 October 2007\n|url-status=dead\n|df=dmy-all\n}}</ref>  The semi-final of the European under-21 Championships in [[Abe Lenstra Stadion|Heerenveen]] between the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] and [[England national under-21 football team|England]] team finished 1\u20131. Thirty-two penalties had to be taken before the tie was broken. The Netherlands eventually won 13\u201312.\n\n===Domestic cups===\nIn the [[FA Cup]], penalty kicks were used in the 1972 edition of the short-lived [[FA Cup Third-fourth place matches|third-place playoff]]. They were introduced more generally in the [[1991\u201392 in English football|1991\u201392 season]] to decide matches still level after one replay and extra time. Previously there was no limit on the number of replays, which led to fixture disruption, especially disliked by the top clubs. Replays were often two or three days after the drawn match, which conflicted with the increased planning required after the [[Football Spectators Act 1989]]. The first team eliminated from the FA Cup on penalties was [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], beaten on 26 October 1991 by [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] after a first-round replay.<ref name=\"CoxRussell2002\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Cox|editor1-first=Richard William|editor2-last=Russell|editor2-first=Dave|editor3-last=Vamplew|editor3-first=Wray|first= John |last=Coyle |title=Encyclopedia of British football|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JKbb02bg6zYC&pg=PA265 |accessdate=27 June 2010|date=3 September 2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-7146-5249-8|page=265|chapter=Replays}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/cup2.sd?competitionid=58&seasonid=121|title=English FA Cup \u2013 1991/1992|publisher=soccerbase.com|accessdate=27 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504045132/http://www.soccerbase.com/cup2.sd?competitionid=58&seasonid=121|archivedate=4 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  A shoot-out was first used in the [[FA Cup Final]] in [[2005 FA Cup Final|2005]], when [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] beat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 5\u20134.<ref>[https://archive.today/20080708225448/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/04/FACF_Preview1.htm]</ref> The [[2006 FA Cup Final|following year]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] beat [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in the FA Cup Final's second ever penalty shoot-out.<ref>[https://archive.today/20080518095426/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2006/05/FACF06_MatchReport.htm]</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 2005, a new English record was established when a shoot-out between [[Tunbridge Wells F.C.|Tunbridge Wells]] and [[Littlehampton Town F.C.|Littlehampton Town]] in an FA Cup replay involved 40&nbsp;kicks being taken, with Tunbridge Wells winning 16\u201315.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/News/2005/Sep/FAC_TunbridgePenaltyRecord|title=Wells' shoot-out record|publisher=The FA|date=2 September 2005|accessdate=2013-07-01|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130203190722/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/News/2005/Sep/FAC_TunbridgePenaltyRecord|archivedate=3 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tunbridgewellsfc.co.uk/news.asp?offset=-1 |title=Latest news |publisher=Tunbridge Wells FC |accessdate=2012-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208120551/http://www.tunbridgewellsfc.co.uk/news.asp?offset=-1 |archivedate=8 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nShoot-outs have been used to settle five [[EFL Cup|Football League Cup]] finals to date.  The first was in [[2001 Football League Cup Final|2001]] when [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] beat [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] 5\u20134 on penalties after a 1\u20131 draw after extra time in the match. The second was the [[2009 Football League Cup Final|2009 final]] between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] ended goalless and was won 4\u20131 on penalties by Manchester United.  Then the [[2012 Football League Cup Final|2012 final]] between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] finished 2\u20132 after extra time, Liverpool winning 3\u20132 on penalties. The [[2016 Football League Cup Final|2016 final]] was won by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] beating Liverpool 3\u20131 on penalties, after a 1\u20131 draw. Manchester City also won the [[2019 EFL Cup Final|2019 final]] 4\u20133 on penalties after a 0\u20130 draw with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].\n\nPenalty shoot-outs have been used for many years to settle drawn games in the earlier rounds of the [[Football League Cup]], the earliest example being August 1976 when [[Doncaster Rovers]] beat [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] 3\u20132 on penalties after three drawn games in a row (1\u20131, 1\u20131, 2\u20132) in a first round match. Shoot-outs tend to be quite rare in the semi-finals due to the [[away goal rule]] applying after extra time. However, a shoot-out was used in the [[2013-14 Football League Cup|2013\u201314 semi-final]] between [[Sunderland AFC|Sunderland]] and Manchester United after both teams finished level over two legs; Sunderland won the shoot-out 2\u20131.\n\nThe [[FA Community Shield|Community Shield]] is also settled using penalties, following the normal 90 minutes of play, but no extra time. [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] have won the shield three times via a shoot-out, beating [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in [[2003 FA Community Shield|2003]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in [[2007 FA Community Shield|2007]], and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in [[2008 FA Community Shield|2008]]. Manchester United lost the [[2009 FA Community Shield|2009]] match on penalties to Chelsea.\n\nIn 2008, the Turkish Cup Final featured two clubs outside of Istanbul's Top Three for the first time in two decades, but penalty kicks decided the winner between Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi and Kayserispor, the latter having reached the final for the first time ever. After a scoreless 120 minutes, 28 penalty kicks were needed to decide the outcome, and Kayserispor, thanks  to the goal scoring and goal saving heroics of Dimitar Ivankov, won its first Turkish Cup 11\u201310.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/history/news/newsid=2075236/|title=Kayserispor triumph in 28-penalty shootout|last=FIFA.com|date=7 May 2013|website=fifa.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606181033/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/history/news/newsid=2075236/|archivedate=6 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2008\u201309 Greek Cup final AEK took a 3\u20132 lead at 89\u2019 with a goal by Scocco; however Olympiacos came back from the dead at the dying seconds of stoppage time (90\u2019+6) with a goal by Derbyshire, to force an overtime. While Olympiacos took a 4\u20133 lead in overtime with a goal by Galletti, the scorer was sent off with a second yellow card for taking his shirt off while celebrating. Later on, Avraam Papadopoulos also got a second yellow leaving Olympiacos with 9 players. AEK managed to tie the game at 4\u20134 forcing a penalty shoot out.\n\nAEK was shooting first. Both AEK and Olympiacos scored in the first 4 penalties. Majstorovic of AEK hit the horizontal crossbar in the 5th penalty giving the chance to Djordjevic (for whom it was the closing game of his career) to seal the victory for Olympiacos. However, his shot was blocked by AEK\u2019s Argentinian goalkeeper Saha. Hence, the shooting continued. Both teams scored their 6th and 7th penalties. Center-back Antzas was slotted to hit the 8th penalty for Olympiacos, but keeper Nikopolidis took the initiative and took the penalty instead tying the score to 7\u20137. Nikopolidis blocked the subsequent (9th) penalty by Georgeas for AEK but Antzas missed the penalty for Olympiacos (saved by Saha) and failed to finish the shoot-out.\n\nSince Olympiacos had only 9 players in the field, the shooters had to rotate, going back to those that shoot the very first penalties. All 7 subsequent penalty takers for both teams scored, leading to a penalty shoot out that was at 14\u201314 with 32 (!) penalty shots having been taken. However, Pelletieri of AEK had a bad penalty shot that was easily deflected by Nikopolidis, who then took the 34th penalty shot against the other goalkeeper, Saha, scoring, and ending this saga with a 15\u201314 win for Olympiacos in penalty shoot out and an overall score of 19\u201318. ([[2008\u201309 Greek Cup]]).\n\n===UEFA club competitions===\nThe first penalty shoot-out in a European Cup final occurred in the [[1984 European Cup Final]] as [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defeated [[A.S. Roma]]. The match is best known for the antics of Liverpool keeper [[Bruce Grobbelaar]]. As Roma's [[Bruno Conti]] prepared to take his kick, Grobbelaar walked towards the goal smiling confidently at the cameras lined-up behind, then proceeded to bite the back of the net, in imitation of eating spaghetti. Conti sent his spot kick over the bar. Grobbelaar then produced a similar performance before [[Francesco Graziani]] took his kick, famously wobbling his legs in mock terror. Graziani duly missed and Liverpool went on to win the shootout 4\u20132.\n\nIn the [[1986 European Cup Final]] between [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]] and [[FC Barcelona]], Steaua keeper [[Helmuth Duckadam]] saved all four of Barca's penalties, for which he was dubbed \"the hero of [[Seville]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Steaua's story |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/8184991.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 August 2009 |accessdate=7 August 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090806101018/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/8184991.stm| archivedate= 6 August 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Steaua also missed two, but still prevailed 2\u20130 in the shoot-out to become the only Romanian club side to win the title.\n\nIn the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final]] the penalty-shoot out has caused controversy among many fans as replays showed that [[Dida (goalkeeper)|Dida]] was off his goal line when saving penalties from [[David Trezeguet|Trezeguet]], [[Marcelo Zalayeta|Zalayeta]] and [[Paolo Montero|Montero]]. [[Gianluigi Buffon|Buffon]] was also off his goal line when saving penalties from [[Clarence Seedorf|Seedorf]] and [[Kakha Kaladze|Kaladze]].\n\nIn the [[2005 UEFA Champions League Final]] between [[A.C. Milan]] and [[Liverpool F.C.]], Liverpool keeper [[Jerzy Dudek]] used tactics similar to [[Bruce Grobbelaar]] in 1984 (known as the \"Dudek dance\" in 2005) to distract the Milan shootout takers which resulted in a victory for his team.\n\nThe [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final]] between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] went to penalties, when [[John Terry]] missed a penalty which would have won Chelsea the match (and the Champions League). His standing leg slipped as he took his kick, and the ball hit the post. Chelsea lost the shoot-out 6\u20135, to which Terry reacted by breaking down in tears. Terry was not originally the penalty taker, however, striker [[Didier Drogba]] had been sent off shortly before extra time ended.\n\nIn the semi-finals of the UEFA Champions League between [[Real Madrid]] and [[Bayern Munich]], [[Iker Casillas]] and [[Manuel Neuer]] each saved two spot kicks. Neuer kept out penalties from [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] (\u00a380 million) and [[Kak\u00e1]] (\u00a356 million), then the most expensive footballers in history from their transfer fees.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/9226202/Real-Madrid-2-Bayern-Munich-1-agg-3-3-Bayern-win-3-1-on-pens-match-report.html |title=Bayern Munich reach Champions League final after beating Real Madrid in dramatic penalty shoot-out |newspaper=Telegraph |date=26 April 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-19 |location=London |first=Henry |last=Winter |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425225935/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/9226202/Real-Madrid-2-Bayern-Munich-1-agg-3-3-Bayern-win-3-1-on-pens-match-report.html |archivedate=25 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2012 Chelsea defeated Bayern Munich 4\u20133 on penalties in the [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final]]. Chelsea had never previously won a shoot-out in the competition, and had lost the 2008 final and 2007 semi-final on penalties. Bayern had never lost a shoot-out in Europe; their wins included the [[2001 UEFA Champions League Final|2001 final]] against Valencia and the 2012 semi-final against Real Madrid. [[Didier Drogba]] dispatched the winning penalty, having been unable to take the fifth kick (missed by Terry) in the 2008 final due to a red card in extra time. The following day, many British newspapers made reference to the fact that an English team had finally beaten a German team on penalties.\n\nFinally, on the tenth of November 2019, Ben Grogan missed a penalty in the final of some cup that no-one really cared about anyway. Still, the memory remains in the hearts and minds of his dearest friends as a reminder of what happens when you're shit at taking pens.\n\n\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2012/may/20/chelsea-national-newspapers|title=How the papers reported Chelsea's football victory|first=Roy|last=Greenslade|date=20 May 2012|website=the Guardian|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510223748/https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2012/may/20/chelsea-national-newspapers|archivedate=10 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Records===\nOn 17 July 2011, during the [[2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] tournament in Argentina, Brazil missed 4 penalties in a row in the quarter-final, which allowed Paraguay to reach the semi-finals 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ca2011.com/jogos_tabela.php?idJ=0d3180d672e08b4c5312dcdafdf6ef36|title=CA2011.com \u2013 Brazil vs Paraguay|accessdate=17 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716052933/http://www.ca2011.com/jogos_tabela.php?idJ=0d3180d672e08b4c5312dcdafdf6ef36|archivedate=16 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe current World Record for the most penalties scored consecutively in a shoot out stands at 29, in a [[Hampshire Senior Cup]] second-round game between [[Brockenhurst F.C.|Brockenhurst]] and [[Andover Town F.C.|Andover Town]] on 9 October 2013, in which the 30th penalty was saved allowing Brockenhurst to win 15\u201314.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.andoveradvertiser.co.uk/sport/10737257.Shoot_out_world_record_confirmed/|title=Andover Town shoot-out world record confirmed|work=Andover Advertiser|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=14 October 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104214440/http://www.andoveradvertiser.co.uk/sport/10737257.Shoot_out_world_record_confirmed/|archivedate=4 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This beat the previous record of 27, in a Johnstones Paint Trophy first round match between [[Leyton Orient F.C.]] and [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.]] on 7 September 2011, in which the 28th penalty was saved allowing Dagenham to win the shootout.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\nDuring the final of the [[1992 African Cup of Nations]] played in Senegal, Ivory Coast won the penalty shootout 11\u201310. After the second set of five penalty kicks still being tied at 10\u201310, it went to sudden death, where the last penalty was missed by [[Anthony Baffoe]], the stand in Ghanaian captain. This is the most penalties in the final match of a major international tournament, and the last time a second set of 5 kicks was implemented in the rules.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} The penalty shootout was significant in that it was the first in the final of a major international tournament that every player on the pitch took a penalty.<ref name=PSO>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html#highint Highest Number of Penalties (International Matches)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706003026/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html |date=6 July 2009 }}. RSSSF</ref><ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tables/92a.html African Nations Cup 2006 Final Tournament \u2013 Final: Ivory Coast vs Ghana]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113174252/http://rsssf.com/tables/92a.html |date=13 January 2010 }}. RSSSF</ref>\n\nFourteen years later, the Ivory Coast and Cameroon needed 24 penalties to decide who would advance to the semi-finals of the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]]. The Ivory Coast advanced by winning 12\u201311 after [[Samuel Eto'o]] missed his second attempt, as his was the only miss of the penalty shootout.<ref name=PSO/><ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tables/06a-det.html African Nations Cup 2006 Final Tournament \u2013 QUARTERFINALS: Cameroon vs Ivory Coast] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022135603/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/06a-det.html |date=22 October 2008 }}. RSSSF</ref>\n\nThe current world record for the longest penalty shoot-out in a first class match is 48&nbsp;penalties during the 2005 Namibian Cup when KK Palace beat Civics 17\u201316.<ref name=\"stokkermans2009\">{{cite web\n |first       = Karel\n |last        = Stokkermans\n |author2     = Carles Lozano\n |title       = Highest Number of Penalties\n |url         = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html\n |work        = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation\n |date        = 6 February 2009\n |accessdate  = 2009-06-24\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090706003026/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html\n |archivedate = 6 July 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\nHowever, the record for the highest score in a penalty shoot out was set in the 1988 Argentine Championship, when Argeninos Juniors beat Racing Club 20\u201319 after 44 penalties.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sean Ingle|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/20/theknowledge.sport|title=Carpentier on top of the world|newspaper=Guardian|date=20 September 2001|accessdate=2012-05-19|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509234632/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/20/theknowledge.sport|archivedate=9 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 June 2015 Sunds\u00f8re IF beat Nyk\u00f8bing Mors 20\u201319 in a penalty shoot out in a preliminary round of the Danish FA Cup.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bentsen, Bo|url=http://sport.tv2.dk/fodbold/2015-06-03-vanvittig-dansk-pokalkamp-afgjort-efter-44-straffespark|title=Vanvittig dansk pokalkamp afgjort efter 44 straffespark|publisher=TV2 (Denmark)|date=2015-06-03|accessdate=2018-09-18|language=da|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn the 11 December 2012, Bradford City set the record for most consecutive penalty shootout wins. They won 9 penalty shootouts since 2009 and that included wins against Arsenal and local rivals Huddersfield Town.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n==Statistical record==\nA shoot-out is usually considered for statistical purposes to be separate from the match which preceded it.<ref>Laws of the Game 2007/2008, p.130: \"The kicks from the penalty mark are not part of the match\"</ref><ref name=\"faq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/faq/ |title=FAQ: Coefficients (associations, clubs, access list) |accessdate=2008-06-23 |date=1 July 2005 |publisher=[[UEFA]] |quote=Kicks from the penalty mark to determine which club qualifies or to determine the winners of a tie do not affect the actual result of the match. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080527082427/http://www.uefa.com/uefa/faq/ |archivedate=27 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref><ref name=\"fifarank\">{{cite web |url=http://www.futbolyou.com/en/articles/ip-590_03e_wrmedium_8787.pdf |title=The FIFA/Coca-Cola World Ranking |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=27 May 2007 |accessdate=2014-10-30 |quote=Win 3 points Draw 1 point Defeat 0 points.  To ensure that the formula is not only fair but also simple, matches that are decided by a penalty shoot-out (which are considered draws under normal rules) result in the winning team receiving two points and the losing team one point. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213092016/http://www.futbolyou.com/en/articles/ip-590_03e_wrmedium_8787.pdf |archivedate=13 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> In the case of a [[Two-legged match|two-legged fixture]], the two matches are still considered either as two draws or as one win and one loss; in the case of a single match, it is still considered as a draw. This contrasts with a fixture won in extra time, where the score at the end of normal time is superseded. Converted shoot-out penalties are not considered as goals scored by a player for the purposes of their individual records, or for \"[[Golden Boot (disambiguation)|golden boot]]\"<!--intentional link to DAB page--> competitions.\n\nThe [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] rules book, which governs most [[college soccer]] in the United States, takes a similar approach. With the exception of the national championship game, if the score of any game remains tied following the [[sudden death (sport)|sudden death overtime (or golden goal)]], the game is recorded as a tie, regardless of the result of the shoot-out tiebreaker. In a national championship game, the result of the shoot-out tiebreaker also determines the result of the game for statistical purposes.<ref name=\"NCAA 2017 Rules\">{{cite book|last= Andres|first= Ken|title= 2016 and 2017 NCAA Men's and Women's Soccer Rules|date= June 2016|publisher= [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|The National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|location= [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]|issn= 0735-0368|page= 38|url= http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/SO17.pdf}}</ref> Until 2001, all NCAA games in which the shoot-out tiebreaker was used to determine advancement or a champion were recorded as a tie.<ref name=\"NCAA 2001 Rules\">{{cite book|last= McCrath|first= C. Cliff|author-link=Cliff McCrath|title= 2001 NCAA Men's and Women's Soccer Rules|date= June 2001|publisher= [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|The National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|location= [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]|issn= 0735-0368|pages= 40, 42|url= http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/MWSR01.pdf}}</ref> In 2002, the rule was modified such that all games in which the shoot-out tiebreaker was used would also decide the winner of the game for statistical purposes.<ref name=\"NCAA 2009 Statistics Rules\">{{cite web |url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/Stats_Manuals/Soccer/2009ez.pdf#page=3 |title=Section 7: Overtime, Tiebreaker procedure |year=2009 |work=Official Soccer Statistics Rules; Approved Rulings and Interpretations |publisher=NCAA |page=3 |accessdate=25 June 2010 |quote=The only year that games decided on penalty kicks resulted in a win or loss, rather than a tie for both teams, was 2002. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628125732/http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/Stats_Manuals/Soccer/2009ez.pdf#page=3 |archivedate=28 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"NCAA 2002 Rules\">{{cite book|last= McCrath|first= C. Cliff|author-link=Cliff McCrath|title= 2002 NCAA Men's and Women's Soccer Rules|date= July 2002|publisher= [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|The National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|location= [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]|issn= 0735-0368|pages= 40, 42|url= http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/MWSR02.pdf}}</ref> The rule was again changed in 2003 to match the pre-2002 rule with the newly-added exception that a shoot-out tiebreaker in a national championship game would be decisive for all purposes, including the record.<ref name=\"NCAA 2003 Rules\">{{cite book|last= McCrath|first= C. Cliff|author-link=Cliff McCrath|title= 2003 NCAA Men's and Women's Soccer Rules|date= August 2003|publisher= [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|The National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|location= [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]|issn= 0735-0368|pages= 40\u201342|url= http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/MWSR03.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn the calculation of [[UEFA coefficient]]s, shoot-outs are ignored for club coefficients,<ref name=\"faq\" /> but not national team coefficients, where the shoot-out winner gets 20,000 points: more than the shoot-out loser, who gets 10,000 (the same as for a draw) but less than the 30,000 points for winning a match outright.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/uefa/KeyTopics/69/80/93/698093_DOWNLOAD.pdf |title=New UEFA National Team Coefficient Ranking System |date=20 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-21 |publisher=[[UEFA]] |page=\u00a73.1.3. Match points |quote=A win is worth 30,000 points and a draw 10,000 points. [...] If a match ends with a penalty shoot-out, both teams are awarded 10,000 points (as for a draw). In addition, the winning team is awarded an extra 10,000 points. The goals scored in the penalty shoot-out do not count. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080625151119/http://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/uefa/KeyTopics/69/80/93/698093_DOWNLOAD.pdf |archivedate=25 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> In the [[FIFA World Rankings]], the base value of a win is three points; a win on penalties is two; a draw and a loss on penalties are one; a loss is zero.<ref name=\"fifarank\" /> [[FIFA World Ranking system 1999-2006|The more complicated ranking system]] FIFA used from 1999 to 2006 gave a shoot-out winner the same points as for a normal win and a shoot-out loser the same points as for a draw; goals in the match proper, but not the shoot-out, were factored into the calculation.<ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA/Coca-Cola World Rankings: Overview of basic principles and method of calculation |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/mens/statistics/rank/procedures/0,2540,3,00.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050308034148/http://www.fifa.com/en/mens/statistics/rank/procedures/0%2C2540%2C3%2C00.html |archivedate=8 March 2005 |accessdate=2008-06-23 |quote=A special exception is made for matches that are decided on penalties; the winning team earns the full number of points for a win, while the losing team gets the number of points that would have been awarded for a draw. [...] In matches decided on penalties, only goals scored during regular playing time or extra time are considered in the calculation. |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\nAs a way to decide a football match, shoot-outs have been seen variously as a thrilling climax or as an unsatisfactory cop-out.\n\nPaul Doyle describes shoot-outs as \"exciting and suspense-filled\" and [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|the 2008 UEFA Champions League Final shoot-out]] as \"the perfect way to end a wonderful ... final\".<ref name=\"doyle\">{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Doyle |date=21 May 2008 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=A match worthy of champions |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/05/21/the_teams_delivered_a_match_wo.html |accessdate=2008-06-29 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080527011957/http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/05/21/the_teams_delivered_a_match_wo.html |archivedate=27 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>  Richard Williams compares the spectacle to \"a [[public flogging]] in the market square\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Williams |date=24 October 2006 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=Down with the shoot-out and let the 'games won' column decide |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2006/10/24/down_with_the_penalty_shoot-out.html |accessdate=2008-06-29 |location=London |df=dmy-all }}{{dead link|date=July 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n</ref>\n\nThe result is often seen as a [[lottery]] rather than a test of skill;<ref name=\"doyle\" /> [[manager (association football)|manager]]s [[Luiz Felipe Scolari]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Jamie |last=Jackson |date=2 July 2006 |work=[[The Observer]] |title=Players will not blame Rooney, says Gerrard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jul/02/worldcup2006.sport13 |accessdate=2008-06-29 |quote=The penalties are always a lottery. |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924232723/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jul/02/worldcup2006.sport13 |archivedate=24 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> and [[Roberto Donadoni]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Oliver |last=Kay |date=23 June 2008 |work=[[The Times]] |title=Roberto Donadoni\u2019s numbers fail to come up in lottery |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/international/euro_2008/article4194156.ece |accessdate=2008-06-29 |quote=\u201cIt is,\u201d he said grimly, \u201ca lottery.\u201d |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821145107/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/international/euro_2008/article4194156.ece |archivedate=21 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> described them as such after their teams had respectively won and lost shoot-outs. Others disagree. Mitch Phillips called it \"the ultimate test of nerve and technique\".<ref name=\"mitch\" />  Paul Doyle emphasised the psychological element.<ref name=\"doyle\" />\n\nOnly a small subset of a footballer's skills is tested by a shoot-out. Ian Thomsen likened deciding the [[1994 FIFA World Cup Final|1994 World Cup]] using a penalty shoot-out to deciding the [[Masters Tournament|Masters golf tournament]] via a [[minigolf]] game.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ian  |last=Thomsen  |date=20 July 1994 |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |title=For Soccer to Win American Hearts, It Must Create Some Heroes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/20/sports/20iht-ian_8.html?pagewanted=all |accessdate=2013-01-07 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107120245/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/20/sports/20iht-ian_8.html?pagewanted=all |archivedate=7 January 2013}}\n</ref>  The shoot-out is a test of individuals which may be considered inappropriate in a team sport; [[Sepp Blatter]] has said \"Football is a team sport and penalties is not a team, it is the individual\".<ref name=\"blatter\">{{cite news |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/09/27/sports/rules.php |title=Soccer: Blatter against shoot-out in final |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |date=27 September 2006 |accessdate=2008-06-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016091110/http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/09/27/sports/rules.php |archivedate=16 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nInferior teams are tempted to play for a scoreless draw, calculating that a shoot-out offers their best hope of victory.<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Moss |date=15 March 2007 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=In praise of the nine-day draw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/mar/15/someoftheloopiermembers |accessdate=2008-06-29 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141002225817/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/mar/15/someoftheloopiermembers |archivedate=2 October 2014 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> [[Red Star Belgrade]]'s performance beating [[Olympique Marseille]] in the [[1991 European Cup Final]] is often condemned for having \"played for penalties\" from the kick-off;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/england/2953134.stm |title=Serbia & Montenegro's new dawn |first=Nada |last=Grkinic |date=31 May 2003 |accessdate=2008-06-29 |work=[[bbc.co.uk]] |quote=Red Star Belgrade had won the European Cup in 1991 and, despite the poverty of that particular performance \u2013 they played for penalties against Marseille from kick-off \u2013 the club was rich in talent. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511141627/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/england/2953134.stm |archivedate=11 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Rookwood |author2=Matthew Cunningham |date=19 June 2003 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=Made in Britain \u2013 but successful abroad? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/jun/19/sport.comment1 |accessdate=6 July 2016 |quote=OM reached the European Cup final in 1991 but were beaten by a shameful Red Star Belgrade side who played for penalties from the start. |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826034816/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/jun/19/sport.comment1 |archivedate=26 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> a tactic coach [[Ljupko Petrovi\u0107]] freely admitted to.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob |last=Smyth |date=10 July 2007 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=The joy of six: inspired tactical switches |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2007/07/10/the_joy_of_six_inspired_tactic.html |accessdate=2008-06-29 |quote=We realised we could not really beat Marseille unless they made a mistake, so I told my players to be patient and to wait for penalties, said the manager Petrovi\u0107. |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713214900/http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2007/07/10/the_joy_of_six_inspired_tactic.html |archivedate=13 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> On the other hand, the increased opportunity for [[Upset (competition)|giant-killing]] may also be seen as an advantage, increasing the romance of a competition like the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Glenn |last=Roeder |authorlink=Glenn Roeder |date=27 February 2007 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=Big debate: should FA Cup replays be scrapped? |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2007/02/28/debate_should_fa_cup_replays_b.html |accessdate=2008-06-29 |quote=Extra-time and shoot-outs could offer smaller teams fantastic chances of extended cup runs. |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302080307/http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2007/02/28/debate_should_fa_cup_replays_b.html |archivedate=2 March 2007 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> Some teams have regarded, or been accused of regarding, a loss on penalties as an honourable result or \"no defeat at all\".<ref name=\"mitch\">{{cite news |first=Mitch |last=Phillips |date=25 June 2008 |work=[[Reuters]] |title=Mental approach holds key to penalty success |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/06/25/uk-soccer-euro-penalties-idUKL1951355120080625 |accessdate=2013-01-07 | location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107121053/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/06/25/uk-soccer-euro-penalties-idUKL1951355120080625 |archivedate=7 January 2013}}\n</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' reported on the advantage of the team kicking first usually wins and on the players aiming higher usually score a goal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=The Economist|date=|title=Football Penalties: The Lucky 12 Yards|url=|journal=The Economist|volume=June 23rd-29th, 2018|pages=68\u201369|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Advantage to team kicking first?===\n[[Ignacio Palacios-Huerta]] has suggested that the alternating kick sequence gives an unfair advantage to the team kicking first, with statistical evidence showing that the team kicking first wins in 60% of the cases, likely due to the team kicking second being under more pressure when trailing in the shoot-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sciencenordic.com/winning-shootouts-first-kick|title=Winning shootouts on the first kick|publisher=Science Nordic|date=3 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922195004/http://sciencenordic.com/winning-shootouts-first-kick|archivedate=22 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As a remedy, he proposed using the [[Thue-Morse sequence#Equitable sequencing|Thue-Morse sequence]] to determine the kicking order.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Palacios-Huerta|first=Ignacio|title=Tournaments, fairness and the prouhet-thue-morse sequence|journal=Economic Inquiry|year=2012|volume=50|issue=3|pages=848\u2013849|url=http://www.palacios-huerta.com/docs/EI-Tournaments_and_PTM_sequence.pdf|accessdate=19 February 2013|doi=10.1111/j.1465-7295.2011.00435.x|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520202649/http://www.palacios-huerta.com/docs/EI-Tournaments_and_PTM_sequence.pdf|archivedate=20 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs part of a trial to reduce this advantage, the [[International Football Association Board|IFAB]] sanctioned in March 2017 to test a different sequence of taking penalties, known as \"ABBA\", that mirrors the serving sequence in a [[Tennis score#Scoring a tiebreak game|tennis tiebreak]] (team A kicks first, team B kicks second):<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/03/03/penalty-shoot-outs-could-soon-resemble-tennis-tie-breaks/|title=Penalty shoot-outs could soon resemble tennis tie-breaks|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=3 March 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012124241/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/03/03/penalty-shoot-outs-could-soon-resemble-tennis-tie-breaks/|archivedate=12 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n;Original sequence\n:AB AB AB AB AB (sudden death starts) AB AB etc.\n;Trial sequence\n:AB BA AB BA AB (sudden death starts) BA AB etc.\n\nThe trial was initially scheduled at the [[2017 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] and the [[2017 UEFA Women's Under-17 Championship]] in May 2017 if a penalty shoot-out would be needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.org/protecting-the-game/refereeing/news/newsid=2463576.html|title=Penalty shoot-out trial at UEFA final tournaments|publisher=UEFA.org|date=1 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607211119/http://www.uefa.org/protecting-the-game/refereeing/news/newsid=2463576.html|archivedate=7 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The trial was extended in June 2017 to include the [[2017 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] and the [[2017 UEFA Women's Under-19 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Comprehensive bidding regulations approved for all finals and final tournaments|url=http://www.uefa.org/mediaservices/newsid=2474545.html|website=UEFA.org|accessdate=1 June 2017|date=1 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603223013/http://www.uefa.org/mediaservices/newsid=2474545.html|archivedate=3 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe penalty shoot-out in the Women's Under-17 Championship semi-final between Germany and Norway was the first ever to implement this new system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-uefa-penalties-idUKKBN18730W|title=New penalty system gets usual result as Germany win|work=Reuters|date=11 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514180147/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-uefa-penalties-idUKKBN18730W|archivedate=14 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was also used in the [[2017 FA Community Shield]] on 6 August 2017.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Rostance |title=Arsenal 1\u20131 Chelsea (Arsenal won 4\u20131 on pens) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40766983 |work=BBC Sport |date=6 August 2017 |accessdate=17 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814010239/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40766983 |archivedate=14 August 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the IFAB's 133rd Annual Business Meeting in [[Glasgow]], Scotland on 22 November 2018, it was agreed that due to the lack of strong support mainly because of its complexity, the ABBA option would no longer be used in future competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2018/m=11/news=ifab-s-133rd-annual-business-meeting-recommends-fine-tuning-laws-for-the-benefit.html|title=IFAB's 133rd Annual Business Meeting recommends fine-tuning Laws for the benefit of the game|publisher=FIFA.com|date=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Alternatives==\nVarious tie-break methods have been proposed, both before and since shoot-outs were introduced.\n\nHistorically, one of the first tie-breaking procedures was contained in the [[wikisource:Sheffield Rules#Rules of 1862|Sheffield Rules]] between 1862 and 1871, with the concept of the ''rouge'', scorable when the ball went narrowly wide off the goal. Rule&nbsp;14 stated \"A goal outweighs any number of rouges. Should no goals or an equal number be obtained, the match is decided by rouges\". Similarly, the [[Try (rugby)|try]] in [[rugby football]] was used from 1875 as a tie-breaker if teams were level on goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/scoring.htm |title=Scoring through the ages |last=Trueman |first=Nigel |work=Rugby football history |accessdate=2009-10-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804112452/http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/scoring.htm |archivedate=4 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nA drawn result may be allowed to stand, unless the fixture determines which team qualifies for a later round.  Before 1993 (except in [[1974 FA Charity Shield|1974]]) the [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] was shared if the match was drawn. When the [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics#Bronze Medal match|third place playoff of the 1972 Olympic tournament]] between the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviets]] and [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] ended 2\u20132 after extra time,<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=197110/matches/match=32161/report.html Olympic Football Tournament Munich 1972: Soviet Union \u2013 German Democratic Republic] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104213935/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=197110/matches/match=32161/report.html |date=4 November 2013 }} FIFA.com\n</ref> the bronze medal was shared by the two teams.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=8229/news/newsid=92858.html The Olympic Odyssey so far... (Part 2: 1968 \u2013 2000)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104213849/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=8229/news/newsid=92858.html |date=4 November 2013 }} FIFA.com 10 June 2004\n</ref>\n\nDuring the [[1962 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification process]] for the [[1962 World Cup]], Morocco and Tunisia formed a two-team group. They both won 2\u20131 at home, so they played a third match at a neutral location. When this ended in a 1\u20131 draw after extra time, Morocco advanced on a coin toss to the next round of qualification. This scenario was repeated during the [[1970 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification process]] for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]], when the same two teams were tied after three matches and extra time. Again, Morocco advanced on a coin toss. Tunisia did have better luck with the coin toss in the intervening years; during the [[1965 African Cup of Nations]], they reached the final at the expense of Senegal by winning a coin toss after three group matches had left Tunisia and Senegal tied with a win (over Ethiopia) and a draw (against each other).\n\nCurrent alternatives include replaying a match that has ended in a draw. This still occurs in the fifth (last sixteen) round and earlier rounds of the [[FA Cup|English FA Cup]]. Until 1991, any number of replays were permitted, with a record of five.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/05/48711.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20040106155319/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/05/48711.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 January 2004 |title=FA Cup Trivia |date=16 May 2003 |accessdate=2008-06-15 |publisher=[[The Football Association|FA]]}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=May 2018}} (Since then, a draw in the (first) replay has been resolved by a penalty-shoot-out.) Only once, in [[1974 European Cup Final|1974]], did the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] final go to a replay.\n\nOther suggestions have included using elements of match play such as most shots on goal, most [[corner kick]]s awarded, fewest [[Misconduct (association football)|cautions and sendings-off]], or having ongoing [[extra time]] with teams compelled to remove players at progressive intervals (similar to regular season play in the [[National Hockey League]], where players play 3-on-3 in the extra time).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.penaltyshootouts.co.uk/alternatives.html |title=Penalty Shoot-outs: alternatives |first=Jon |last=Billsberry |author2=Nathalie van Meurs |author3=Patrick Nelson |author4=Gareth Edwards |accessdate=2008-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624181210/http://www.penaltyshootouts.co.uk/alternatives.html |archivedate=24 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> These proposals have not yet been authorised by the [[International Football Association Board]]. However, after the 2006 World Cup, [[Sepp Blatter]] stated that he wants no more penalty shoot-outs in the Final of the World Cup, tentatively suggesting either a replay or \"Maybe to take players away and play [[golden goal]]\".<ref name=\"blatter\" />\n\nHenry Birtles' \"Advantage\" proposal is for the shoot-out to be held before extra-time, and only acting as a tiebreak if the game remains a draw after the full 120 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/33743/FIFA-ponder-end-to-shoot-out-woe |title=FIFA ponder end to shoot-out woe |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=4 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-20 |first=Bill |last=Bradshaw }}\n</ref> Proponents of this idea state that it would lead to a more offensive extra-time as one of the teams would know they have to score and there would never be a match in which both teams are simply waiting for penalties. Another advantage is that players who have missed would have a chance to redeem themselves in extra-time. The obvious flaw is that the team that wins the penalty shoot-out would be inclined to play defensively in extra time in the knowledge that a draw would put them through. However, this flaw is not so clear because a single goal makes the difference between winning and losing, as opposed to a team which defends a single-goal lead more comfortably because a conceded goal is the difference between winning and drawing.\n\nAnother alternative is Attacker Defender Goalkeeper (ADG), which features a series of ten contests, in which an attacker has thirty seconds to score a goal against a defender and goalkeeper. At the completion of the ten contests, the team with the most goals is the winner.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theadgalternative.com/ |title=Theadgalternative.com |publisher=Theadgalternative.com |date=5 August 2010 |accessdate=2012-05-19 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110224090150/http://www.theadgalternative.com/ |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bleacherreport.com/articles/1195909-10-alternatives-to-a-penalty-shootout |title=10 Alternatives to Penalty Shootouts |last=Tidey |first=Will |work=Bleacher Report |accessdate=2012-11-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103150137/http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1195909-10-alternatives-to-a-penalty-shootout |archivedate=3 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\n==North American experiments==\nThe [[North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984)|North American Soccer League]] (NASL) in the 1970s and 1980s, then [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) for its first four seasons (1996\u20131999) experimented with a variation of the shoot-out procedure.\n\nInstead of a straight penalty kick, the shoot-out started {{convert|35|yd|m|abbr=out|disp=or}} from the goal and having five seconds to attempt a shot. The player could make as many moves as he could in a breakaway situation in the five seconds, then attempt a shot. This procedure is similar to that used in an [[Penalty shot (ice hockey)|ice hockey penalty shot]]. As with a standard shoot-out, this variation used a best-of-five-kicks model, and if the score was still level, the tiebreaker would head to an extra round of one attempt per team.\n\nThis format rewarded player skills, as players were able to attempt to deceive goalkeepers and play the ball in an attempt to make the shot, as in a one-on-one skills contest, and goalkeepers could take on the attackers without restrictions that are normally implemented in penalty shootouts. [[Soccer Bowl '81]], the NASL's 1981 championship final, was decided by this format.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kyG1cBb-cpM|title=NASL Soccer Bowl '81|last=thecelebratedmisterk|date=13 April 2010|accessdate=3 May 2018|via=YouTube|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531020714/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kyG1cBb-cpM|archivedate=31 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFrom its inception in [[1968 North American Soccer League season|1968]], the NASL used an unconventional point system in determining the league standings. Teams were awarded six points for a win and three points for a draw. In addition, teams earned one bonus point for each goal scored in a game up to a maximum of three per game. Thus, a team that lost 5\u20133 would earn three points. However, a team that lost 1\u20130 would earn no points. Also, a team that won 5\u20134 would earn nine points (the same as a 3\u20130 win). But a team that won 2\u20130 would earn only eight points. In the league's second season ([[1969 North American Soccer League season|1969]]), the [[Kansas City Spurs]] were the league champions with 10 wins, 2 losses and 4 ties even though the [[Atlanta Chiefs]] had 11 wins, 2 losses and 3 ties, because Kansas City earned more bonus points. Starting with [[1971 North American Soccer League season|1971]] postseason playoff matches, the NASL used a [[golden goal]] rule, and every match had a winner decided from the run of play. Extra-time sessions were 15 minutes long before a brief break and change of ends. Game 1 of the 1971 NASL semifinal series between the [[Rochester Lancers (1967\u201380)|Rochester Lancers]] and the [[Dallas Tornado]] went six extra-time periods with Rochester scoring the game-winning goal in the 176th minute. Game 3 of that same series went four extra time periods with Dallas scoring in the 148th minute to win the match and the series. In [[1975 North American Soccer League season|1975]], the NASL adopted a conventional penalty-kick shootout system for all regular-season and postseason playoff matches, and there were no longer any NASL matches that ended in ties. In the standings, a team that won in regulation time was awarded six points. A team that won in a penalty-kick shootout was awarded one point. Bonus points continued to be awarded for each goal scored up to a maximum of three per game. In [[1977 North American Soccer League season|1977]], the NASL adopted the experimental North American shootout procedure described above. If a match was tied after 90 minutes, a maximum of two golden goal extra time periods of 7.5 minutes each were played. If neither team scored, the shootout was held to determine the winner of the match. In the standings, a team that won was awarded six points whether the win came in regulation time, extra time or by shootout. Bonus points continued to be awarded for each goal scored up to a maximum of three per game. No bonus points were awarded for goals scored in extra time. Postseason playoff games were decided in the same manner. In [[1981 North American Soccer League season|1981]], the number of points awarded to a team that won a game in a shootout was reduced from six to four. This remained the system until the NASL's final season in [[1984 North American Soccer League season|1984]].\n\nFrom its inception in [[1996 Major League Soccer season|1996]], MLS used the shootout system that had been used by the NASL to determine winners of matches. No regular-season or postseason playoff games ended in a tie. In general, no extra time was played; the shootout commenced immediately after 90 minutes had been played. The only exception was in the [[MLS Cup '96|MLS Cup Final]] in which a match tied after 90 minutes would be followed by a maximum of two 15-minute extra time sessions on a golden goal basis. In the regular-season standings, a team that won a match in regulation was awarded three points. A team that won a match in a shootout was awarded one point. There were no bonus points or points awarded to teams that lost whether in regulation time or a shootout. In the playoffs, the conference semifinals and conference finals were organized as best-of-three matches series. A shootout win counted as a win. Thus, a team could win two of the three matches by shootout and lose the other match in regulation and still advance to the next round. This was inconsistent with how the teams were rewarded during the regular season when the team with one win would have earned three points, and the team with two wins would have earned only two points. In [[1999 Major League Soccer season|1999]], a maximum of two 15-minute golden goal extra time periods were added for matches that were tied after 90 minutes of regulation play. If neither team scored during extra time, the match was decided by a shootout. MLS abandoned the North American style shootout starting with the [[2000 Major League Soccer season|2000 season]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Alex|last=Yannis|date=18 November 1999|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=M.L.S. is Making Changes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/18/sports/soccer-mls-is-making-changes.html|accessdate=13 July 2014|location=New York|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714180417/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/18/sports/soccer-mls-is-making-changes.html|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> If penalties are required to determine a winner during the playoffs, MLS now uses the shoot-out procedure specified by the International Football Association Board.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of FIFA World Cup penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[List of FIFA Women's World Cup penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[List of UEFA European Championship penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[List of Copa Am\u00e9rica penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[List of CONCACAF Gold Cup penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[Penalty shoot-out]]\n* [[Penalty kick (association football)|Penalty kick]]\n* [[Golden goal]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''On Penalties'' by Andrew Anthony ({{ISBN|0-224-06116-X}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Penalty shootout (association football)}}\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html Penalty Shoot-out Trivia] \u2014 [[rec.sport.soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]\n* [http://www.penaltyshoot-outs.co.uk/index.html Penalty Shoot-outs]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \u2014 by four researchers associated with the Fit Project at the [[Open University]]\n\n[[Category:Association football penalty shoot-outs| ]]\n[[Category:Laws of association football]]\n[[Category:Association football terminology]]\n[[Category:Street football games]]\n[[Category:Sports penalties]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n\nA '''penalty shoot-out''' (officially '''kicks from the penalty mark''')<ref name=\"Laws\">{{cite web|title=Laws of the Game 2016/2017|url=http://static-3eb8.kxcdn.com/documents/60/Laws%20of%20the%20Game_16-17_Digital_Eng.pdf|author=IFAB|authorlink=International Football Association Board|publisher=[[IFAB]]|location=[[Zurich]]|accessdate=27 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911032912/http://static-3eb8.kxcdn.com/documents/60/Laws%20of%20the%20Game_16-17_Digital_Eng.pdf|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a method of determining which team is awarded victory in an [[association football]] match that cannot end in a [[tie (draw)|draw]], when the score is tied after the regulation playing time as well as [[overtime (sports)|extra time]] (if used) have expired. In a penalty shoot-out, each team takes turns shooting at goal from the penalty mark, with the goal only defended by the opposing team's goalkeeper. Each team has five shots which must be taken by different kickers; the team that makes more successful kicks is declared the victor. Shoot-outs finish as soon as one team has an insurmountable lead. If scores are level after five pairs of shots, the shootout progresses into additional \"sudden-death\" rounds.<ref name=\"Laws\" /> Balls successfully kicked into the goal during a shoot-out do not count as goals for the individual kickers or the team, and are tallied separately from the goals scored during normal play (including extra time, if any). Although the procedure for each individual kick in the shoot-out resembles that of a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], there are some differences. Most notably, neither the kicker nor any player other than the [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] may play the ball again once it has been kicked.\n\nThe penalty shoot-out is one of the three methods of breaking a draw that are currently approved by the [[Laws of the Game (association football)|Laws of the Game]]; the others are extra time and, for [[two-legged tie]]s, the [[away goals rule]].<ref name=\"Laws\" /> A shoot-out is usually used only after one or more of the other methods fail to produce a winner. The method of breaking a draw for a specific match is determined beforehand by the match organizing body. In most professional level competitions, two 15-minute extra time periods are played if the score is tied at the end of regulation time, and a shoot-out is held if the score is still tied after the extra time periods.\n\nAlthough widely employed in football since the 1970s, penalty shoot-outs have been widely criticized by many followers of the game, due primarily to their perceived reliance on [[luck]] rather than skill and their dependence on individual duels between opposing players, which is arguably not in keeping with football as a [[team sport]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Wilson, M|author2=Wood, G|author3=Jordet, G.|title=The BASES Expert Statement on the Psychological Preparation for Football Penalty Shootouts|url=http://www.bases.org.uk/write/545_Expert_statement_on_Psychological_preparation_for_Football_penalty_shootouts.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106200749/http://www.bases.org.uk/write/545_Expert_statement_on_Psychological_preparation_for_Football_penalty_shootouts.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 January 2016|publisher=British Association of Sports and Exercise Sciences|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> Conversely, some believe the pressure and unpredictability involved makes it one of the most thrilling finales to any sport.<ref>{{Cite web |title=World Cup shootouts are great and here is how other sports can adopt the thrilling finale |quote=But all those things combine to make it dramatic and compulsive viewing, the ultimate element of instant unpredictability, a quick fix for both the \u201cshort attention span\u201d generation and all the ones before it, too. Shootouts provide all the things we like about sports. Heroes stepping into the spotlight with a single moment of brilliant or fortune. Sympathetic figures who your heart bleeds for. |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/columnist/martin-rogers/2018/07/01/world-cup-how-nfl-nba-mlb-get-soccer-shootout/749658002/ |work=USA Today |date=1 July 2018 |accessdate=2018-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Goalmouth Scramble: 10 'important' thoughts on the World Cup |quote=Nothing beats penalty shootouts for drama. And how great was the camera pivot to capture Manchester United legend Peter Schmeichel's reactions every time his son Kasper saved a penalty for Denmark? Truly gripping theatre. |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12081702 |work=New Zealand Herald |date=2 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nDuring a shoot-out, players other than the kicker and the goalkeepers must remain in the centre circle.<ref name=\"Laws\" /> The kicking team's goalkeeper stands at the intersection of the goal line and the line marking the penalty area ({{convert|16.5|m|yd|0|abbr=in|disp=x|/}}) near one of the assistant referees. Goals scored during the shoot-out are not commonly added to the goalscoring records of the players involved.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nA draw is a common result in football. Shoot-outs are only used in competitions that require a match-winner at the end of the game<ref name=\"Laws\" /> \u2013 this is predominantly in [[single-elimination tournament|knockout \"cup\" ties]], as opposed to [[round-robin tournament|round-robin \"leagues\"]]; they decide which team progresses to the next round of a tournament, or win it. Usually [[extra time]] has been played first, but this is not necessary;<ref name=\"Laws\" /> exceptions include the [[Copa Libertadores]], [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] (quarter-finals, semi-finals, and third-place game), [[FA Community Shield]] and the [[Football League Trophy]], all of which use shoot-outs straight after the end of normal time.\n\nThe rules of some competitions provide that a shoot-out may be used to decide placings in a round-robin group, in the unusual event that two teams who have faced each other in a final-day match finish the group with identical statistics, and no other teams has the same record. This was invoked in Group A of the [[2003 UEFA Women's Under-19 Championship]], in which Italy and Sweden held a shootout immediately after their drawn match.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eur-women-u19-03.html\n |title=European Women U-19 Championship 2002\u201303\n |last=Duret\n |first=S\u00e9bastien\n |author2=David Matishen\n |author3=Herv\u00e9 Morard\n |author4=Lars Aarhus\n |author5=Erik Garin\n |author6=Sturmius Burkert\n |date=14 February 2004\n |website=[[RSSSF]]\n |accessdate=2009-10-14\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121021024/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eur-women-u19-03.html\n |archivedate=21 January 2010\n |df=dmy\n }}\n</ref> This rule is a recent innovation, and for example did not apply in [[1990 FIFA World Cup#Group F|Group F of the 1990 World Cup]], where the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] were separated by drawing of lots immediately after drawing their final-day match.<ref>{{cite book |author=FIFA Technical Study Group |title=FIFA World Cup Italia'90: Official Report |publisher=FIFA |year=1990 |page=59 |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/techdevp/fwc_italy_1990_a_part2_277.pdf |quote=So the last two matches in Group F would decide whether teams could proceed forward by their own efforts, or make FIFA resort to drawing lots in Rome. [..] Ireland and Holland fought yet another 1\u20131 result and the draw in Rome placed Ireland in second place and Holland third. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924153727/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/techdevp/fwc_italy_1990_a_part2_277.pdf |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nSeveral leagues, such as the [[J.League]],<ref>{{cite book|author1=Hirata, T.|author2=Szymanski, S.|editor1-last=Lee|editor1-first=YH|editor2-last=Fort|editor2-first=R|title=The Sports Business in The Pacific Rim|publisher=Sports Economics, Management and Policy|chapter=The J. League and the World Cup}}</ref> have experimented with penalty shoot-outs immediately following a drawn league match, with the winner being awarded an extra [[points (association football)|point]]. In the United States and Canada, [[Major League Soccer]] initially also had a shoot-out immediately following the end of full-time, even during league matches, although these shoot-outs differed from standard penalty shoot-outs (see below).\n\nA team that loses a penalty shoot-out is eliminated from the tournament but it does not count as a defeat, while the winning team in the shoot-out advances or is crowned champion but does not get a match victory. For instance, the Netherlands are considered to have concluded the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] undefeated, despite being eliminated at the semi-final stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=7/news=van-gaal-we-can-still-make-history-2403702.html|title=Van Gaal: We can still make history|last=FIFA.com|date=11 July 2014|website=fifa.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129004925/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=7/news=van-gaal-we-can-still-make-history-2403702.html|archivedate=29 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Procedure==\n[[File:Hearts vs. Gretna Scottish Cup final.jpg|thumb|[[Steven Pressley]] scores for [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] against [[Gretna FC|Gretna]] in the [[2006 Scottish Cup Final]] shoot-out]]\n[[File:Penalty kick Lahm Cech Champions League Final 2012.jpg|thumb|[[Philipp Lahm]] is about to score in the [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final]]]]\n[[File:Didier Drogba Manuel Neuer last penalty kick Champions League Final 2012.jpg|thumb|Deciding penalty kick of [[Didier Drogba]] in the [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final]]]]\n\nThe following is a summary of the procedure for kicks from the penalty mark. The procedure is specified in Law 10 (\"Determining the Outcome of a Match\") of the IFAB's ''Laws of the Game'' document (p.&nbsp;71).<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n\n# The referee tosses a coin to decide the goal at which the kicks will be taken.  The choice of goal by the coin toss winner may only be changed by the referee for safety reasons or if the goal or playing surface becomes unusable.<ref name=\"Laws\"/>\n# The referee tosses the coin a second time to determine which team will take the first kick.\n# All players other than the kicker and the goalkeepers must remain in the [[Association football pitch|pitch]]'s centre circle (see above).\n# Each kick will be taken in the general manner of a penalty kick. Each kick will be taken from the [[Penalty area|penalty mark]], which is {{convert|11|m|yd|abbr=in}} from the goal line and equidistant from each touch line, with the goal defended only by the opposing goalkeeper. The goalkeeper must remain between the goal posts on his goal line until the ball has been kicked, although he can jump in place, wave his arms, move side to side along the goal line or otherwise try to distract the shooter.\n# Each team is responsible for selecting from the eligible players the order in which they will take the kicks.\n# Each kicker can kick the ball only once. Once kicked, the kicker may not play the ball again. The decision on a re-kick is solely at the referee's discretion.\n# No other player on either team, other than the designated kicker and goalkeeper, may touch the ball.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# A kick is successful if, having been touched once by the kicker, the ball crosses the goal line between the goal posts and under the crossbar, without touching any player, official, or outside agent other than the defending goalkeeper. The ball may touch the goalkeeper, goal posts, or crossbar any number of times before going into the goal as long as the referee believes the ball's motion is the result of the initial kick. This was clarified after an incident in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]] shoot-out between [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[France national football team|France]]. [[Bruno Bellone]]'s kick rebounded out off the post, hit goalkeeper [[Carlos Roberto Gallo|Carlos]]'s back, and subsequently bounced into the goal. Referee [[Ioan Igna]] gave the goal to France, and Brazil captain [[Edino Nazareth Filho|Edinho]] was booked for protesting that the kick should have been considered a miss as soon as it rebounded off the post. In 1987, the [[International Football Association Board]] clarified Law&nbsp;14, covering penalty kicks, to support Igna's decision.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.corshamref.org.uk/newsletter/news06jul.htm |date=July 2006 |title=The Corsham Referee Newsletter |first=Julian |last=Carosi |accessdate=2008-06-20 |number=31 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006164438/http://corshamref.org.uk/newsletter/news06jul.htm |archivedate=6 October 2008 }} and {{cite book |chapter-url=http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1987/1987app.pdf |title=Minutes of the AGM |author=IFAB |publisher=Soccer South Bay Referee Association |location=Llandudno |date=13 June 1987 |accessdate=29 November 2009 |pages=18\u201322 |chapter=III.8(a) Proposal by the Scottish Football Association: Law XIV\u2014Penalty Kick |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430130743/http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1987/1987app.pdf |archivedate=30 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n# Teams take turns to kick from the penalty mark until each has taken five kicks. However, if one side has scored more successful kicks than the other could possibly reach with all of its remaining kicks, the shoot-out immediately ends, regardless of the number of kicks remaining; this basis is called \"best-of-five kicks\". An example of this is the 2006 World Cup final, the shootout ended after Italy's [[Fabio Grosso]] had scored his team's fifth, despite the fact that France (on 3) still had one more to go.\n# If after five rounds of kicks the teams have an equal number of successful kicks, additional rounds of one kick each will be used until one team scores and the other misses. This is known as [[sudden death (sport)|sudden death]].\n# The team that scores the most successful kicks at the end of the shoot-out will be the winner of the match.\n# Only players who were on the pitch at the end of play or temporarily absent (injured, adjusting equipment etc.) will be allowed to participate in the shoot-out.<ref name=\"Laws\" /> If at the end of the match and before or during the kicks one side has more players on the pitch than the other, whether as a result of injury or red cards, then the side with more players must reduce its numbers to match the opponents; this is known as 'reduce to equate'. For example, if Team&nbsp;A has 11&nbsp;players but Team&nbsp;B only has 10, then Team&nbsp;A will choose one player who will not take part. Players excluded this way normally take no further part in the procedure, except that they can be used to replace an injured goalkeeper. The rule was introduced by the International Football Association Board in February 2000 because previously an eleventh kick would be taken by the eleventh (i.e. weakest) player of a full-strength team and the first (i.e. strongest) player of a sub-strength team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/developing/refereeing/news/newsid=74400.html |title=The Laws change and the game gets better |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=1 August 2000 |accessdate=2008-06-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514104336/http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/developing/refereeing/news/newsid%3D74400.html |archivedate=14 May 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> A rule change in 2016 eliminated the possibility of a team gaining such an advantage if a player is injured or sent off ''during'' the shoot-out.<ref name=\"changes2016\">{{cite web|last1=Hinch|first1=Will|title=Football Law Changes 2016/17|url=https://www.pitchero.com/blog/football-law-changes-201617|website=Pitchero|accessdate=14 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807040806/https://www.pitchero.com/blog/football-law-changes-201617|archivedate=7 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n# A team may replace a goalkeeper who becomes injured during the shoot-out with a substitute (provided the team has not already used the maximum number of substitutes allowed by the competition) or by a player previously excluded under the 'reduce to equate' provision.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# If a goalkeeper is sent off during the shoot-out, another player who finished the game must act as goalkeeper.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# If a player, other than the goalkeeper, becomes injured or is sent off during the shoot-out, then the shoot-out will continue with no substitution allowed. The opposing team must reduce its numbers accordingly.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# Any player remaining on the pitch may act as the goalkeeper, and it is ''not'' required for the same player to have acted as a goalkeeper during the game.\n# No player will be allowed to take a second kick until all other eligible players on their team have taken a first kick, including the goalkeeper.\n# If it becomes necessary for players to take another kick (because the score has remained equal after all eligible players have taken their first kick), players are not required to kick in the same order.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n# Kicks from the penalty mark must not be delayed for a player who leaves the field of play. The player\u2019s kick will be forfeited (not scored) if the player does not return in time to take a kick.\n# The referee must not abandon the match if, during the kicks, a team is reduced to fewer than seven players.<ref name=\"Laws\" />\n\n==Tactics==\n{{main|Penalty kick (association football)#Tactics}}\nDefending against a penalty kick is one of the most difficult tasks a goalkeeper can face. Some decide which way they will dive beforehand, giving themselves time to reach the side of the goalmouth.  A 2011 study published in the journal ''Psychological Science'' found goalkeepers dived to the right 71% of the time when their team was losing, but only 48% when ahead and 49% when tied, a phenomenon believed to be related to certain right-preferring behaviour in social mammals.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/08/02/138922339/under-pressure-soccer-goalies-tend-to-dive-right|title=Under Pressure, Soccer Goalies Tend To Dive Right|date=2 August 2011|accessdate=2011-09-03|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803010726/http://www.npr.org/2011/08/02/138922339/under-pressure-soccer-goalies-tend-to-dive-right|archivedate=3 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Others try to read the kicker's motion pattern. Kickers may attempt to feint, or delay their shot to see which way the keeper dives. Shooting high and centre, in the space that the keeper will evacuate, carries the highest risk of shooting above the bar.<ref>How to actually, seriously play soccer 2007/2008, p.130: \"Don't shoot right down the pipe\"</ref>  If a keeper blocks a penalty kick during a match, there is a danger the kicker or a teammate may score from the rebound; this is not relevant in the case of a shoot-out.\n\nSince the entire shoot-out is conducted at the same goal, the crowd behind the goal may favour one team and try to distract the other team's shooters. To forestall any potential advantage, in 2016 the Laws of the Game were modified to add a coin toss between the two teams prior to the shoot-out: the winner of the coin toss has the right to decide which goal is used for the shoot-out (previously, the decision was at the referee's discretion). The referee may change the goal only for safety reasons or if the selected goal or pitch are unusable.<ref name=\"Laws\"/>\n\nA goalkeeper may not use distracting gamesmanship such as cleaning his boots or asking the referee to see if the ball is placed properly; this risks a [[Misconduct (association football)#Cautionable offences (yellow card)|caution]] for [[unsporting conduct]]. [[Bruce Grobbelaar]]'s \"wobbly legs\" clowning distracted [[Francesco Graziani]] in the [[1984 European Cup Final]] shootout.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/football/view/258133/Euro-2012-Joe-Hart-ready-to-line-dance-for-England/|title=Euro 2012: Joe Hart will do a Bruce Grobbelaar|date=22 June 2012|work=[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]|accessdate=29 June 2012|location=London}}</ref>  The keeper is forbidden from moving off the goal line to narrow the shooter's angle; the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final]] shootout caused controversy as replays showed that both keepers got away with this, as did [[Jerzy Dudek]] in the [[2005 Champions League Final]].\n\n==History==\n===Origins===\nBefore the introduction of shoot-outs, knock-out matches level after extra time would be decided by a replay or a coin toss.\nHowever, variants of the modern shoot-out were used before then in several domestic competitions and minor tournaments.  Domestic examples include the [[Yugoslav Cup]] from 1952,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joegcupdetail.html#52 |title=Cup of Yugoslavia 1952 |first=Dinant |last=Abbink |date=6 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-07-15 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303174325/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joegcupdetail.html#52 |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> the [[Coppa Italia]] from 1958\u201359,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italcup59.html |title=Coppa Italia 1958/59 |first=Erik |last=Garin |date=28 March 2007 |accessdate=2008-07-15 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515085211/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italcup59.html |archivedate=15 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> and the Swiss inter-regional Youth Cup from 1959\u201360.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit-jugendcup.html#60 |title=Switzerland \u2013 Youth Cup 1959/60 |first=Dinant |last=Abbink |date=8 June 2000 |accessdate=2008-07-15 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915064925/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit-jugendcup.html#60 |archivedate=15 September 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>  International examples include the 1962 [[Uhrencup]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/uhren.html#62 |title=Coupe Horlog\u00e8re \u2013 Uhren Cup (Switzerland) 1962\u20132009: 1962 |first=Erik |last=Garin |date=6 November 2009 |accessdate=2011-07-14 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727042125/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesu/uhren.html#62 |archivedate=27 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (at the suggestion of its founder Kurt Weissbrodt),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grenchnertagblatt.ch/solothurn/grenchen/der-beweis-fuer-die-deutsche-frechheit-110695400 |title=Der Beweis f\u00fcr die deutsche Frechheit |first=Marco |last=Sansoni |language=German |date=13 July 2011 |accessdate=2011-07-14 |publisher=Grenchner Tagblatt |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327160559/http://www.grenchnertagblatt.ch/solothurn/grenchen/der-beweis-fuer-die-deutsche-frechheit-110695400 |archivedate=27 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nthe final of the 1962 [[Ram\u00f3n de Carranza Trophy]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/carranza.html#62 |title=Trofeo Ram\u00f3n de Carranza (C\u00e1diz-Spain) 1955\u20132007: 1962 |first=Ra\u00fal |last=Torre |date=16 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-11 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610065753/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/carranza.html#62 |archivedate=10 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> (at the suggestion of journalist Rafael Ballester),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.as.com/opinion/articulo/don-rafael-ballester-innovador/dasftb/20060818dasdaiopi_1/Tes |title=A don Rafael Ballester, innovador |first=Alfredo |last=Rela\u00f1o |date=18 August 2006 |accessdate=2008-07-16 |language=Spanish |publisher=AS.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080630033033/http://www.as.com/opinion/articulo/don-rafael-ballester-innovador/dasftb/20060818dasdaiopi_1/Tes |archivedate=30 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> and [[Football at the Bolivarian Games#V Games|a silver medal playoff match]] between amateur teams representing [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] and [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] in the [[1965 Bolivarian Games]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/bolivarianos.html\n |title=Bolivarian Games: Soccer Tournaments\n |first=Jos\u00e9 Luis\n |last=Pierrend\n |author2=Alfonzo Cornejo\n |date=3 September 2005\n |accessdate=2008-06-11\n |website=[[RSSSF]]\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425031108/http://rsssf.com/tablesb/bolivarianos.html\n |archivedate=25 April 2013\n |df=dmy\n }}\n</ref>\n\nIn major competitions, when a [[replay (sports)|replay]] or [[One-game playoff|playoff]] was not possible, ties were previously broken by drawing of lots. Examples include [[Italy national football team|Italy]]'s win over the [[USSR national football team|USSR]] in the semi-final of the [[UEFA Euro 1968|1968 European Championship]] (the final, also drawn, went to a replay).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/68e.html |title=European Championship 1968 |first=Karel |last=Stokkermans |author2=Mart\u00edn Tabeira |date=7 February 2007 |accessdate=2008-06-19 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080622211438/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/68e.html |archivedate=22 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\n[[Israel]]i Yosef Dagan is credited with originating the modern shoot-out,<ref>{{cite web |title=Israeli Behind the Goal |url=http://www.infolive.tv/en/infolive.tv-10153-israelnews-israeli-behind-goal |format=[[Adobe Flash]] |publisher=infolive.tv |accessdate=2008-06-19 |language=Hebrew, English |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422055325/http://www.infolive.tv/en/infolive.tv-10153-israelnews-israeli-behind-goal |archivedate=22 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> after watching the [[Israel national football team|Israeli team]] lose a [[Football at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Olympic quarterfinal game]] against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] by drawing of lots in [[Mexico]]. Michael Almog, later president of the [[Israel FA]], described Dagan's proposal in a letter published in ''FIFA News'' in August 1969.<ref name=\"miller\">{{cite book |title=He Always Puts It To The Right: A History Of The Penalty Kick |isbn=978-0-7528-2728-5 |first=Clark |last=Miller |publisher=Orion |year=1996 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/healwaysputsitto0000mill }}\n</ref>  Koe Ewe Teik, the [[Malaysian FA]]'s member of the [[referee (association football)|referee]]'s committee, led the move for its adoption by FIFA.<ref name=\"miller\" />  FIFA's proposal was discussed on 20 February 1970 by a working party of the [[International Football Association Board]] (IFAB), which recommended its acceptance, although \"not entirely satisfied\" with it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1970/1970wpag.pdf |title=Minutes of the Working Party |author=IFAB |publisher=Soccer South Bay Referee Association |location=London |date=20 February 1970 |accessdate=29 November 2009 |page=4, \u00a712 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430131015/http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1970/1970wpag.pdf |archivedate=30 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> It was adopted by the IFAB's annual general meeting on 27 June 1970.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1970/1970min.pdf |title=Minutes of the AGM |author=IFAB |publisher=Soccer South Bay Referee Association |location=Inverness |date=27 June 1970 |accessdate=29 November 2009 |page=\u00a75(g) |nopp=y|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430093219/http://ssbra.org/html/laws/IFABarc/pdf/1970/1970min.pdf |archivedate=30 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> In 2006, [[Deutsche Presse-Agentur]] reported a claim by former referee [[Karl Wald]] (b. 1916), from [[Frankfurt am Main]], that he had first proposed the shoot-out in 1970 to the [[Bavaria]]n FA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stern.de/sport/wm2006/news/karl-wald-der-vater-des-elfmeterschiessens-564500.html|title=Karl Wald: Der Vater des Elfmeterschie\u00dfens|last=Hollmann|first=Christian|date=30 June 2006|work=[[Stern (magazine)|Stern]]|language=German|accessdate=13 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427085811/http://www.stern.de/sport/wm2006/news/karl-wald-der-vater-des-elfmeterschiessens-564500.html|archivedate=27 April 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Development===\nIn England, the first penalty shoot-out in a professional match took place in 1970 at [[Boothferry Park]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], between [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] during the semi-final of the [[Watney Cup]], and was won by Manchester United. The first player to take a kick was [[George Best]], and the first to miss was [[Denis Law]]. [[Ian McKechnie]], who saved Law's kick, was also the first goalkeeper to take a kick; his shot hit the crossbar and deflected over, putting Hull City out of the Cup.\n\nPenalty shoot-outs were used to decide matches in UEFA's [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] and [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] in the 1970\u201371 season. On 30 September 1970, after a 4\u20134 aggregate draw in [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1970-71#First round|the first round of the Cup Winners' Cup]], [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Honv\u00e9d]] won the first shoot-out 5\u20134 against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.linguasport.com/futbol/internacional/clubes/c2/C2_71.htm |title=Cup Winners' Cup 1970\u201371 |publisher=linguasport.com |language=English |accessdate=22 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930021314/http://www.linguasport.com/futbol/internacional/clubes/c2/C2_71.htm |archivedate=30 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> when [[Jim Forrest (footballer born 1944)|Jim Forrest]]'s shot hit the bar. Five weeks later, on 4 November 1970,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197071det.html#cc |title=European Champions' Cup and Fairs' Cup 1970\u201371 \u2013 Details |authors=Antonio Zea, Marcel Haisma |date=9 January 2008 |website=RSSSF |language=English |accessdate=22 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426213400/http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197071det.html#cc |archivedate=26 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the first ever European Cup shoot out took place between [[Everton F.C.]] and [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]], with the side from England this time being the winners 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.linguasport.com/futbol/internacional/clubes/c1/C1_71.htm |title=European Cup 1970\u201371 |publisher=linguasport.com |language=English |accessdate=22 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930021454/http://www.linguasport.com/futbol/internacional/clubes/c1/C1_71.htm |archivedate=30 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the first round of the [[European Cup 1972\u201373]], the referee prematurely ended a shoot-out between [[PFC CSKA Sofia|CSKA Sofia]] and [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]], with CSKA leading 3\u20132 but Panathinaikos having taken only four kicks. Panathinaikos complained to UEFA and the match was annulled and replayed the following month,<ref>{{cite news |title=UEFA annul Cup result  |author=[[Reuters]] |date=9 Oct 1972 |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=ProQuest |page=7 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Derby could silence their critics|last=Barham |first=Albert |date=25 Oct 1972|work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=ProQuest |page=27 }}\n</ref> with CSKA winning without the need for a shoot-out.\n\nThe final of the 1973 [[Campeonato Paulista]] ended in similar circumstances. [[Santos F.C.|Santos]] were leading [[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Desportos|Portuguesa]] 2\u20130 with each team having taken three shoot-out kicks, when referee Armando Marques mistakenly (as each team still had two shots to take, and therefore Portuguesa still had a chance of leveling the scoreline) declared Santos the winners. Portuguesa manager [[Otto Gl\u00f3ria]] quickly led his team out of the stadium; this was allegedly to ensure the shoot-out could not resume once the mistake was discovered, and that instead the match would be replayed, giving Portuguesa a better chance of victory. When Santos counter-objected to a replay, Paulista&nbsp;FA president Osvaldo Teixeira Duarte annulled the original match and declared both teams joint champions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cartaovermelho.com.br/index.php?name=News&file=article&sid=35&theme=Printer |title=Decis\u00e3o do Campeonato Paulista de 1973 |author=Reportagem CV |date=26 August 2003 |publisher=cartaovermelho.com.br |language=Portuguese |accessdate=26 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706151624/http://www.cartaovermelho.com.br/index.php?name=News&file=article&sid=35&theme=Printer |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |authorlink=Pel\u00e9 |author=Pel\u00e9 |author2=Orlando Duarte |author3=Alex Bellos |author4=Daniel Hahn  |title=Pel\u00e9: the autobiography |publisher=Simon & Schuster|year=2006 |isbn=978-0-7432-7583-5}}\n</ref>\n\nThe first major international tournament to be decided by a penalty shoot-out was the [[1976 European Football Championship|1976 European Championship]] final between [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[Germany national football team|West Germany]].  UEFA had made provision for a final replay two days later,<ref>{{cite news|title=Side Lines: Thomas the send-off |last=Road |first=Alan |date=20 June 1976 |work=The Observer |page=20 |publisher=ProQuest |quote=Clive Thomas ... has been asked by the European Football Federation to stay in the country to referee a possible replay of tonight's European championship between the West Germany and the Czechs in Belgrade. }}\n</ref> but the teams decided to use a shoot-out instead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Czechs owe championship to Viktor |last=Lacey |first=David |date=21 June 1976 |work=The Guardian |publisher=ProQuest |page=17 |quote=Extra time brought no more goals and so, the countries having decided against a replay on Tuesday, the tournament had to be decided on penalties.}}\n</ref> Czechoslovakia won 5\u20133, and the deciding kick was converted by [[Anton\u00edn Panenka]] with a \"[[Panenka (penalty kick)|chip]]\" after [[Uli Hoene\u00df]] had put the previous kick over the crossbar.\n\nThe first penalty shoot-out in the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] was on 9 January 1977, in [[1978 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)#First round|the first round of African qualifying]], when [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] beat [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/fifaworldcuppreliminaryhistory_byyear__13876.pdf |author=Communications Division |title=History of the FIFA World Cup Preliminary Competition (by year) |date=27 July 2007 |work=Good to Know |publisher=[[FIFA]] |page=22 |accessdate=2009-05-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615220946/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/fifaworldcuppreliminaryhistory_byyear__13876.pdf |archivedate=15 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> The first shoot-out in the finals tournament was in [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]], when [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] beat [[France national football team|France]] in the semifinal.  If [[1982 FIFA World Cup Final|the 1982 final]] had been drawn, penalties would not have applied unless the replay was also drawn;<ref>{{cite news|title=World Cup facts and figures|date=6 June 1982|work=Chicago Tribune|page=C2}}</ref><ref name=\"Norman1986\" /> from [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]], penalties were scheduled after the final as for the earlier knockout rounds.<ref name=\"Norman1986\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y0ojAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Mc8FAAAAIBAJ&dq=final%20penalties%20world-cup&pg=3134%2C4177671|title=Soccer purists blast penalty shoootouts|last=Chad|first=Norman|date=25 June 1986|work=The Palm Beach Post|page=5C|accessdate=27 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Famous incidents==\n===National team===\nThe finals of six major [[FIFA]] competitions, including two World Cups, have gone to penalty shoot-outs:\n* The [[1991 FIFA World Youth Championship]] final between [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal]] and [[Brazil national under-20 football team|Brazil]] in [[Lisbon]] was decided on a penalty shoot-out which the Portuguese won 4\u20132, with the last shot coming from [[Rui Costa]].\n*In the [[1994 FIFA World Cup Final]] at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]], California, Brazil and [[Italy national football team|Italy]] ended extra time scoreless. Brazil went on to win the shoot-out 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/pwc/mr_3104.html|title=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) - FIFA.com|last=FIFA.com|website=www.fifa.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302011553/http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/pwc/mr_3104.html|archivedate=2 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*The [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup Final]] between the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]] and [[China women's national football team|China]], also at the Rose Bowl, was scoreless after extra time. The United States team won the shoot-out 5\u20134.\n*The [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final]] also went to a penalty shoot-out (after a 1\u20131 draw followed by a scoreless 30-mins. extra time) and was won by [[Italy national football team|Italy]] 5\u20133 against [[France national football team|France]] in [[Berlin]]'s [[Olympic Stadium (Berlin)|Olympic Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/match/64/mr.html|title=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) - FIFA.com|last=FIFA.com|website=www.fifa.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060811010105/http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/match/64/mr.html|archivedate=11 August 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*The [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Final]], held at [[Commerzbank Arena]] in [[Frankfurt]], went to a penalty shoot-out (after a 1\u20131 draw at full-time and a 2\u20132 draw after extra time) between the USA and [[Japan women's national football team|Japan]]. Japan won the game after scoring 3 penalties to 1 penalty by the USA.\n*The [[2013 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] final in [[Istanbul]] went to a penalty shoot-out after a 0\u20130 draw after extra time. France won the game after scoring 4 penalties to 1 penalty by Uruguay.\n\nGoalkeepers have been known to win shoot-outs by their kicking. For example, in a [[UEFA Euro 2004]] quarter-final match, [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] goalkeeper [[Ricardo (footballer, born 1976)|Ricardo]] saved a kick (without gloves) from [[England national football team|England's]] [[Darius Vassell]], and then scored the winning shot.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2004/3830451.stm | work=BBC News | title=Portugal break England hearts | date=24 June 2004 | accessdate=2010-05-22 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417090356/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2004/3830451.stm | archivedate=17 April 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Another example is [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]]'s [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Chilavert]] in the [[Copa Libertadores 1994]] finals (Chilavert had a reputation as a dead-ball specialist and scored 41 goals during his club career).\n\n[[Anton\u00edn Panenka]] ([[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]]) decided the penalty shoot-out at the final of the [[1976 European Football Championship]] against West Germany with a [[Panenka (penalty kick)|famous chip]] to the middle of the goal.\n\nEngland lost six (out of nine) penalty shoot-outs in major tournament finals, including losses to Germany in the semi-finals of the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 1996]] (the latter following a win over Spain by the same method in the previous round). After Euro 1996, England lost four more shoot-outs in a row in major tournament finals, losing to Argentina at the 1998 World Cup, Portugal at Euro 2004 and the 2006 World Cup and Italy at Euro 2012, before finally breaking their losing streak at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] against Colombia; this shootout also allowed England to progress into the quarter-finals for the first time in twelve years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2018/07/03/england-vs-colombia-world-cup-2018-live-score-harry-kane-latest/|title=England banish penalty curse to pass Colombia test and reach World Cup quarter-final: live reaction|last=Wallace|first=Sam|date=2018-07-03|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-07-03|last2=Tyers|first2=Alan|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe Netherlands, meanwhile, lost four consecutive shoot-outs; against Denmark in Euro 1992, France in Euro 1996, Brazil in the 1998 World Cup, and Italy in Euro 2000, before finally winning one against Sweden in Euro 2004. In Euro 2000, the Netherlands had two penalty kicks during the match and four attempts in the shootout but only managed to convert one kick against Italian keeper [[Francesco Toldo]]. [[Frank de Boer]] had both a penalty kick and shootout kick saved by Toldo, who also saved from [[Paul Bosvelt]] to give Italy a 3\u20131 shootout victory. The Netherlands' fortunes seemed to have improved during the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] when they defeated Costa Rica on penalty kicks in their quarter-final, only to lose again on penalties in their semi-final against Argentina.\n\nThe Italians have lost six shoot-outs in major championships, notably being eliminated from three consecutive World Cups (1990\u20131998, including the 1994 final) and the Euro 2016 quarter-finals on penalties. However, they have also won three shoot-outs, including the Euro 2000 semi-final against the Netherlands, the Euro 2012 quarter-final against England, and the 2006 World Cup Final against France.\n\nOn 16 November 2005, a place in the World Cup was directly determined by a penalty shoot-out for the first time. The [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL \u2013 OFC play-off)|qualifying playoff]] between [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] and [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] ended 1\u20131 on aggregate, with Uruguay winning the first leg 1\u20130 [[Estadio Centenario|at home]] and Australia winning the second leg at [[Stadium Australia|home]] by the same score. A scoreless 30 minutes of [[extra time]] was followed by a shoot-out, which Australia won 4\u20132.\n\nDuring the 2006 FIFA World Cup in Germany, [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] set an unwanted new record in the round&nbsp;of&nbsp;16 shoot-out against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] by failing to convert any of their penalties, losing 3\u20130. The goalkeeper [[Oleksandr Shovkovsky]] ([[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]) became the first not to concede a single goal in the penalty shoot-out, saving two of the Swiss attempts, with another shot hitting the crossbar. The result meant that Switzerland became the first nation to be eliminated from the World Cup without conceding any goals (and, moreover, the only nation to participate in a World Cup finals tournament without conceding a goal).\n\nThe same competition featured a shoot-out between Germany and Argentina, the two most successful teams up to that point in terms of World Cup finals penalty shoot-outs: each team had competed in 3 shoot-outs and won all of them. Germany won the shoot-out, leaving Germany alone with a 4\u20130 record in World Cup finals.\n\nOn 20 June 2007, a new UEFA record was established.<ref>{{cite web\n|work=UEFA.com\n|title=Netherlands News\n|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/news/kind=1/newsid=548583.html\n|accessdate=2007-08-21\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017163842/http://uefa.com/competitions/euro/news/kind%3D1/newsid%3D548583.html\n|archivedate=17 October 2007\n|url-status=dead\n|df=dmy-all\n}}</ref>  The semi-final of the European under-21 Championships in [[Abe Lenstra Stadion|Heerenveen]] between the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] and [[England national under-21 football team|England]] team finished 1\u20131. Thirty-two penalties had to be taken before the tie was broken. The Netherlands eventually won 13\u201312.\n\n===Domestic cups===\nIn the [[FA Cup]], penalty kicks were used in the 1972 edition of the short-lived [[FA Cup Third-fourth place matches|third-place playoff]]. They were introduced more generally in the [[1991\u201392 in English football|1991\u201392 season]] to decide matches still level after one replay and extra time. Previously there was no limit on the number of replays, which led to fixture disruption, especially disliked by the top clubs. Replays were often two or three days after the drawn match, which conflicted with the increased planning required after the [[Football Spectators Act 1989]]. The first team eliminated from the FA Cup on penalties was [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], beaten on 26 October 1991 by [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] after a first-round replay.<ref name=\"CoxRussell2002\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Cox|editor1-first=Richard William|editor2-last=Russell|editor2-first=Dave|editor3-last=Vamplew|editor3-first=Wray|first= John |last=Coyle |title=Encyclopedia of British football|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JKbb02bg6zYC&pg=PA265 |accessdate=27 June 2010|date=3 September 2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-7146-5249-8|page=265|chapter=Replays}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/cup2.sd?competitionid=58&seasonid=121|title=English FA Cup \u2013 1991/1992|publisher=soccerbase.com|accessdate=27 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504045132/http://www.soccerbase.com/cup2.sd?competitionid=58&seasonid=121|archivedate=4 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  A shoot-out was first used in the [[FA Cup Final]] in [[2005 FA Cup Final|2005]], when [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] beat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 5\u20134.<ref>[https://archive.today/20080708225448/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2005/04/FACF_Preview1.htm]</ref> The [[2006 FA Cup Final|following year]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] beat [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in the FA Cup Final's second ever penalty shoot-out.<ref>[https://archive.today/20080518095426/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2006/05/FACF06_MatchReport.htm]</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 2005, a new English record was established when a shoot-out between [[Tunbridge Wells F.C.|Tunbridge Wells]] and [[Littlehampton Town F.C.|Littlehampton Town]] in an FA Cup replay involved 40&nbsp;kicks being taken, with Tunbridge Wells winning 16\u201315.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/News/2005/Sep/FAC_TunbridgePenaltyRecord|title=Wells' shoot-out record|publisher=The FA|date=2 September 2005|accessdate=2013-07-01|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130203190722/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/News/2005/Sep/FAC_TunbridgePenaltyRecord|archivedate=3 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tunbridgewellsfc.co.uk/news.asp?offset=-1 |title=Latest news |publisher=Tunbridge Wells FC |accessdate=2012-05-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208120551/http://www.tunbridgewellsfc.co.uk/news.asp?offset=-1 |archivedate=8 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nShoot-outs have been used to settle five [[EFL Cup|Football League Cup]] finals to date.  The first was in [[2001 Football League Cup Final|2001]] when [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] beat [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] 5\u20134 on penalties after a 1\u20131 draw after extra time in the match. The second was the [[2009 Football League Cup Final|2009 final]] between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] ended goalless and was won 4\u20131 on penalties by Manchester United.  Then the [[2012 Football League Cup Final|2012 final]] between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] finished 2\u20132 after extra time, Liverpool winning 3\u20132 on penalties. The [[2016 Football League Cup Final|2016 final]] was won by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] beating Liverpool 3\u20131 on penalties, after a 1\u20131 draw. Manchester City also won the [[2019 EFL Cup Final|2019 final]] 4\u20133 on penalties after a 0\u20130 draw with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].\n\nPenalty shoot-outs have been used for many years to settle drawn games in the earlier rounds of the [[Football League Cup]], the earliest example being August 1976 when [[Doncaster Rovers]] beat [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] 3\u20132 on penalties after three drawn games in a row (1\u20131, 1\u20131, 2\u20132) in a first round match. Shoot-outs tend to be quite rare in the semi-finals due to the [[away goal rule]] applying after extra time. However, a shoot-out was used in the [[2013-14 Football League Cup|2013\u201314 semi-final]] between [[Sunderland AFC|Sunderland]] and Manchester United after both teams finished level over two legs; Sunderland won the shoot-out 2\u20131.\n\nThe [[FA Community Shield|Community Shield]] is also settled using penalties, following the normal 90 minutes of play, but no extra time. [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] have won the shield three times via a shoot-out, beating [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in [[2003 FA Community Shield|2003]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in [[2007 FA Community Shield|2007]], and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in [[2008 FA Community Shield|2008]]. Manchester United lost the [[2009 FA Community Shield|2009]] match on penalties to Chelsea.\n\nIn 2008, the Turkish Cup Final featured two clubs outside of Istanbul's Top Three for the first time in two decades, but penalty kicks decided the winner between Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi and Kayserispor, the latter having reached the final for the first time ever. After a scoreless 120 minutes, 28 penalty kicks were needed to decide the outcome, and Kayserispor, thanks  to the goal scoring and goal saving heroics of Dimitar Ivankov, won its first Turkish Cup 11\u201310.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/history/news/newsid=2075236/|title=Kayserispor triumph in 28-penalty shootout|last=FIFA.com|date=7 May 2013|website=fifa.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606181033/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/history/news/newsid=2075236/|archivedate=6 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2008\u201309 Greek Cup final AEK took a 3\u20132 lead at 89\u2019 with a goal by Scocco; however Olympiacos came back from the dead at the dying seconds of stoppage time (90\u2019+6) with a goal by Derbyshire, to force an overtime. While Olympiacos took a 4\u20133 lead in overtime with a goal by Galletti, the scorer was sent off with a second yellow card for taking his shirt off while celebrating. Later on, Avraam Papadopoulos also got a second yellow leaving Olympiacos with 9 players. AEK managed to tie the game at 4\u20134 forcing a penalty shoot out.\n\nAEK was shooting first. Both AEK and Olympiacos scored in the first 4 penalties. Majstorovic of AEK hit the horizontal crossbar in the 5th penalty giving the chance to Djordjevic (for whom it was the closing game of his career) to seal the victory for Olympiacos. However, his shot was blocked by AEK\u2019s Argentinian goalkeeper Saha. Hence, the shooting continued. Both teams scored their 6th and 7th penalties. Center-back Antzas was slotted to hit the 8th penalty for Olympiacos, but keeper Nikopolidis took the initiative and took the penalty instead tying the score to 7\u20137. Nikopolidis blocked the subsequent (9th) penalty by Georgeas for AEK but Antzas missed the penalty for Olympiacos (saved by Saha) and failed to finish the shoot-out.\n\nSince Olympiacos had only 9 players in the field, the shooters had to rotate, going back to those that shoot the very first penalties. All 7 subsequent penalty takers for both teams scored, leading to a penalty shoot out that was at 14\u201314 with 32 (!) penalty shots having been taken. However, Pelletieri of AEK had a bad penalty shot that was easily deflected by Nikopolidis, who then took the 34th penalty shot against the other goalkeeper, Saha, scoring, and ending this saga with a 15\u201314 win for Olympiacos in penalty shoot out and an overall score of 19\u201318. ([[2008\u201309 Greek Cup]]).\n\n===UEFA club competitions===\nThe first penalty shoot-out in a European Cup final occurred in the [[1984 European Cup Final]] as [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] defeated [[A.S. Roma]]. The match is best known for the antics of Liverpool keeper [[Bruce Grobbelaar]]. As Roma's [[Bruno Conti]] prepared to take his kick, Grobbelaar walked towards the goal smiling confidently at the cameras lined-up behind, then proceeded to bite the back of the net, in imitation of eating spaghetti. Conti sent his spot kick over the bar. Grobbelaar then produced a similar performance before [[Francesco Graziani]] took his kick, famously wobbling his legs in mock terror. Graziani duly missed and Liverpool went on to win the shootout 4\u20132.\n\nIn the [[1986 European Cup Final]] between [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]] and [[FC Barcelona]], Steaua keeper [[Helmuth Duckadam]] saved all four of Barca's penalties, for which he was dubbed \"the hero of [[Seville]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Steaua's story |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/8184991.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 August 2009 |accessdate=7 August 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090806101018/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/8184991.stm| archivedate= 6 August 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Steaua also missed two, but still prevailed 2\u20130 in the shoot-out to become the only Romanian club side to win the title.\n\nIn the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final]] the penalty-shoot out has caused controversy among many fans as replays showed that [[Dida (goalkeeper)|Dida]] was off his goal line when saving penalties from [[David Trezeguet|Trezeguet]], [[Marcelo Zalayeta|Zalayeta]] and [[Paolo Montero|Montero]]. [[Gianluigi Buffon|Buffon]] was also off his goal line when saving penalties from [[Clarence Seedorf|Seedorf]] and [[Kakha Kaladze|Kaladze]].\n\nIn the [[2005 UEFA Champions League Final]] between [[A.C. Milan]] and [[Liverpool F.C.]], Liverpool keeper [[Jerzy Dudek]] used tactics similar to [[Bruce Grobbelaar]] in 1984 (known as the \"Dudek dance\" in 2005) to distract the Milan shootout takers which resulted in a victory for his team.\n\nThe [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final]] between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] went to penalties, when [[John Terry]] missed a penalty which would have won Chelsea the match (and the Champions League). His standing leg slipped as he took his kick, and the ball hit the post. Chelsea lost the shoot-out 6\u20135, to which Terry reacted by breaking down in tears. Terry was not originally the penalty taker, however, striker [[Didier Drogba]] had been sent off shortly before extra time ended.\n\nIn the semi-finals of the UEFA Champions League between [[Real Madrid]] and [[Bayern Munich]], [[Iker Casillas]] and [[Manuel Neuer]] each saved two spot kicks. Neuer kept out penalties from [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] (\u00a380 million) and [[Kak\u00e1]] (\u00a356 million), then the most expensive footballers in history from their transfer fees.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/9226202/Real-Madrid-2-Bayern-Munich-1-agg-3-3-Bayern-win-3-1-on-pens-match-report.html |title=Bayern Munich reach Champions League final after beating Real Madrid in dramatic penalty shoot-out |newspaper=Telegraph |date=26 April 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-19 |location=London |first=Henry |last=Winter |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425225935/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/9226202/Real-Madrid-2-Bayern-Munich-1-agg-3-3-Bayern-win-3-1-on-pens-match-report.html |archivedate=25 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2012 Chelsea defeated Bayern Munich 4\u20133 on penalties in the [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final]]. Chelsea had never previously won a shoot-out in the competition, and had lost the 2008 final and 2007 semi-final on penalties. Bayern had never lost a shoot-out in Europe; their wins included the [[2001 UEFA Champions League Final|2001 final]] against Valencia and the 2012 semi-final against Real Madrid. [[Didier Drogba]] dispatched the winning penalty, having been unable to take the fifth kick (missed by Terry) in the 2008 final due to a red card in extra time. The following day, many British newspapers made reference to the fact that an English team had finally beaten a German team on penalties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2012/may/20/chelsea-national-newspapers|title=How the papers reported Chelsea's football victory|first=Roy|last=Greenslade|date=20 May 2012|website=the Guardian|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510223748/https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2012/may/20/chelsea-national-newspapers|archivedate=10 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Records===\nOn 17 July 2011, during the [[2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] tournament in Argentina, Brazil missed 4 penalties in a row in the quarter-final, which allowed Paraguay to reach the semi-finals 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ca2011.com/jogos_tabela.php?idJ=0d3180d672e08b4c5312dcdafdf6ef36|title=CA2011.com \u2013 Brazil vs Paraguay|accessdate=17 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120716052933/http://www.ca2011.com/jogos_tabela.php?idJ=0d3180d672e08b4c5312dcdafdf6ef36|archivedate=16 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe current World Record for the most penalties scored consecutively in a shoot out stands at 29, in a [[Hampshire Senior Cup]] second-round game between [[Brockenhurst F.C.|Brockenhurst]] and [[Andover Town F.C.|Andover Town]] on 9 October 2013, in which the 30th penalty was saved allowing Brockenhurst to win 15\u201314.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.andoveradvertiser.co.uk/sport/10737257.Shoot_out_world_record_confirmed/|title=Andover Town shoot-out world record confirmed|work=Andover Advertiser|date=14 October 2013|accessdate=14 October 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104214440/http://www.andoveradvertiser.co.uk/sport/10737257.Shoot_out_world_record_confirmed/|archivedate=4 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This beat the previous record of 27, in a Johnstones Paint Trophy first round match between [[Leyton Orient F.C.]] and [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.]] on 7 September 2011, in which the 28th penalty was saved allowing Dagenham to win the shootout.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\nDuring the final of the [[1992 African Cup of Nations]] played in Senegal, Ivory Coast won the penalty shootout 11\u201310. After the second set of five penalty kicks still being tied at 10\u201310, it went to sudden death, where the last penalty was missed by [[Anthony Baffoe]], the stand in Ghanaian captain. This is the most penalties in the final match of a major international tournament, and the last time a second set of 5 kicks was implemented in the rules.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} The penalty shootout was significant in that it was the first in the final of a major international tournament that every player on the pitch took a penalty.<ref name=PSO>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html#highint Highest Number of Penalties (International Matches)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706003026/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html |date=6 July 2009 }}. RSSSF</ref><ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tables/92a.html African Nations Cup 2006 Final Tournament \u2013 Final: Ivory Coast vs Ghana]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113174252/http://rsssf.com/tables/92a.html |date=13 January 2010 }}. RSSSF</ref>\n\nFourteen years later, the Ivory Coast and Cameroon needed 24 penalties to decide who would advance to the semi-finals of the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]]. The Ivory Coast advanced by winning 12\u201311 after [[Samuel Eto'o]] missed his second attempt, as his was the only miss of the penalty shootout.<ref name=PSO/><ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tables/06a-det.html African Nations Cup 2006 Final Tournament \u2013 QUARTERFINALS: Cameroon vs Ivory Coast] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022135603/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/06a-det.html |date=22 October 2008 }}. RSSSF</ref>\n\nThe current world record for the longest penalty shoot-out in a first class match is 48&nbsp;penalties during the 2005 Namibian Cup when KK Palace beat Civics 17\u201316.<ref name=\"stokkermans2009\">{{cite web\n |first       = Karel\n |last        = Stokkermans\n |author2     = Carles Lozano\n |title       = Highest Number of Penalties\n |url         = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html\n |work        = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation\n |date        = 6 February 2009\n |accessdate  = 2009-06-24\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090706003026/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html\n |archivedate = 6 July 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\nHowever, the record for the highest score in a penalty shoot out was set in the 1988 Argentine Championship, when Argeninos Juniors beat Racing Club 20\u201319 after 44 penalties.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sean Ingle|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/20/theknowledge.sport|title=Carpentier on top of the world|newspaper=Guardian|date=20 September 2001|accessdate=2012-05-19|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509234632/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/sep/20/theknowledge.sport|archivedate=9 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 June 2015 Sunds\u00f8re IF beat Nyk\u00f8bing Mors 20\u201319 in a penalty shoot out in a preliminary round of the Danish FA Cup.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bentsen, Bo|url=http://sport.tv2.dk/fodbold/2015-06-03-vanvittig-dansk-pokalkamp-afgjort-efter-44-straffespark|title=Vanvittig dansk pokalkamp afgjort efter 44 straffespark|publisher=TV2 (Denmark)|date=2015-06-03|accessdate=2018-09-18|language=da|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn the 11 December 2012, Bradford City set the record for most consecutive penalty shootout wins. They won 9 penalty shootouts since 2009 and that included wins against Arsenal and local rivals Huddersfield Town.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\n==Statistical record==\nA shoot-out is usually considered for statistical purposes to be separate from the match which preceded it.<ref>Laws of the Game 2007/2008, p.130: \"The kicks from the penalty mark are not part of the match\"</ref><ref name=\"faq\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/faq/ |title=FAQ: Coefficients (associations, clubs, access list) |accessdate=2008-06-23 |date=1 July 2005 |publisher=[[UEFA]] |quote=Kicks from the penalty mark to determine which club qualifies or to determine the winners of a tie do not affect the actual result of the match. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080527082427/http://www.uefa.com/uefa/faq/ |archivedate=27 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref><ref name=\"fifarank\">{{cite web |url=http://www.futbolyou.com/en/articles/ip-590_03e_wrmedium_8787.pdf |title=The FIFA/Coca-Cola World Ranking |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=27 May 2007 |accessdate=2014-10-30 |quote=Win 3 points Draw 1 point Defeat 0 points.  To ensure that the formula is not only fair but also simple, matches that are decided by a penalty shoot-out (which are considered draws under normal rules) result in the winning team receiving two points and the losing team one point. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213092016/http://www.futbolyou.com/en/articles/ip-590_03e_wrmedium_8787.pdf |archivedate=13 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> In the case of a [[Two-legged match|two-legged fixture]], the two matches are still considered either as two draws or as one win and one loss; in the case of a single match, it is still considered as a draw. This contrasts with a fixture won in extra time, where the score at the end of normal time is superseded. Converted shoot-out penalties are not considered as goals scored by a player for the purposes of their individual records, or for \"[[Golden Boot (disambiguation)|golden boot]]\"<!--intentional link to DAB page--> competitions.\n\nThe [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] rules book, which governs most [[college soccer]] in the United States, takes a similar approach. With the exception of the national championship game, if the score of any game remains tied following the [[sudden death (sport)|sudden death overtime (or golden goal)]], the game is recorded as a tie, regardless of the result of the shoot-out tiebreaker. In a national championship game, the result of the shoot-out tiebreaker also determines the result of the game for statistical purposes.<ref name=\"NCAA 2017 Rules\">{{cite book|last= Andres|first= Ken|title= 2016 and 2017 NCAA Men's and Women's Soccer Rules|date= June 2016|publisher= [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|The National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|location= [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]|issn= 0735-0368|page= 38|url= http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/SO17.pdf}}</ref> Until 2001, all NCAA games in which the shoot-out tiebreaker was used to determine advancement or a champion were recorded as a tie.<ref name=\"NCAA 2001 Rules\">{{cite book|last= McCrath|first= C. Cliff|author-link=Cliff McCrath|title= 2001 NCAA Men's and Women's Soccer Rules|date= June 2001|publisher= [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|The National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|location= [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]|issn= 0735-0368|pages= 40, 42|url= http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/MWSR01.pdf}}</ref> In 2002, the rule was modified such that all games in which the shoot-out tiebreaker was used would also decide the winner of the game for statistical purposes.<ref name=\"NCAA 2009 Statistics Rules\">{{cite web |url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/Stats_Manuals/Soccer/2009ez.pdf#page=3 |title=Section 7: Overtime, Tiebreaker procedure |year=2009 |work=Official Soccer Statistics Rules; Approved Rulings and Interpretations |publisher=NCAA |page=3 |accessdate=25 June 2010 |quote=The only year that games decided on penalty kicks resulted in a win or loss, rather than a tie for both teams, was 2002. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628125732/http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/Stats_Manuals/Soccer/2009ez.pdf#page=3 |archivedate=28 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"NCAA 2002 Rules\">{{cite book|last= McCrath|first= C. Cliff|author-link=Cliff McCrath|title= 2002 NCAA Men's and Women's Soccer Rules|date= July 2002|publisher= [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|The National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|location= [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]|issn= 0735-0368|pages= 40, 42|url= http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/MWSR02.pdf}}</ref> The rule was again changed in 2003 to match the pre-2002 rule with the newly-added exception that a shoot-out tiebreaker in a national championship game would be decisive for all purposes, including the record.<ref name=\"NCAA 2003 Rules\">{{cite book|last= McCrath|first= C. Cliff|author-link=Cliff McCrath|title= 2003 NCAA Men's and Women's Soccer Rules|date= August 2003|publisher= [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|The National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|location= [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]|issn= 0735-0368|pages= 40\u201342|url= http://www.ncaapublications.com/productdownloads/MWSR03.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIn the calculation of [[UEFA coefficient]]s, shoot-outs are ignored for club coefficients,<ref name=\"faq\" /> but not national team coefficients, where the shoot-out winner gets 20,000 points: more than the shoot-out loser, who gets 10,000 (the same as for a draw) but less than the 30,000 points for winning a match outright.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/uefa/KeyTopics/69/80/93/698093_DOWNLOAD.pdf |title=New UEFA National Team Coefficient Ranking System |date=20 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-21 |publisher=[[UEFA]] |page=\u00a73.1.3. Match points |quote=A win is worth 30,000 points and a draw 10,000 points. [...] If a match ends with a penalty shoot-out, both teams are awarded 10,000 points (as for a draw). In addition, the winning team is awarded an extra 10,000 points. The goals scored in the penalty shoot-out do not count. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080625151119/http://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/uefa/KeyTopics/69/80/93/698093_DOWNLOAD.pdf |archivedate=25 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> In the [[FIFA World Rankings]], the base value of a win is three points; a win on penalties is two; a draw and a loss on penalties are one; a loss is zero.<ref name=\"fifarank\" /> [[FIFA World Ranking system 1999-2006|The more complicated ranking system]] FIFA used from 1999 to 2006 gave a shoot-out winner the same points as for a normal win and a shoot-out loser the same points as for a draw; goals in the match proper, but not the shoot-out, were factored into the calculation.<ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA/Coca-Cola World Rankings: Overview of basic principles and method of calculation |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/mens/statistics/rank/procedures/0,2540,3,00.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050308034148/http://www.fifa.com/en/mens/statistics/rank/procedures/0%2C2540%2C3%2C00.html |archivedate=8 March 2005 |accessdate=2008-06-23 |quote=A special exception is made for matches that are decided on penalties; the winning team earns the full number of points for a win, while the losing team gets the number of points that would have been awarded for a draw. [...] In matches decided on penalties, only goals scored during regular playing time or extra time are considered in the calculation. |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\nAs a way to decide a football match, shoot-outs have been seen variously as a thrilling climax or as an unsatisfactory cop-out.\n\nPaul Doyle describes shoot-outs as \"exciting and suspense-filled\" and [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|the 2008 UEFA Champions League Final shoot-out]] as \"the perfect way to end a wonderful ... final\".<ref name=\"doyle\">{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Doyle |date=21 May 2008 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=A match worthy of champions |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/05/21/the_teams_delivered_a_match_wo.html |accessdate=2008-06-29 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080527011957/http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/05/21/the_teams_delivered_a_match_wo.html |archivedate=27 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>  Richard Williams compares the spectacle to \"a [[public flogging]] in the market square\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Williams |date=24 October 2006 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=Down with the shoot-out and let the 'games won' column decide |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2006/10/24/down_with_the_penalty_shoot-out.html |accessdate=2008-06-29 |location=London |df=dmy-all }}{{dead link|date=July 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n</ref>\n\nThe result is often seen as a [[lottery]] rather than a test of skill;<ref name=\"doyle\" /> [[manager (association football)|manager]]s [[Luiz Felipe Scolari]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Jamie |last=Jackson |date=2 July 2006 |work=[[The Observer]] |title=Players will not blame Rooney, says Gerrard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jul/02/worldcup2006.sport13 |accessdate=2008-06-29 |quote=The penalties are always a lottery. |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924232723/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jul/02/worldcup2006.sport13 |archivedate=24 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> and [[Roberto Donadoni]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Oliver |last=Kay |date=23 June 2008 |work=[[The Times]] |title=Roberto Donadoni\u2019s numbers fail to come up in lottery |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/international/euro_2008/article4194156.ece |accessdate=2008-06-29 |quote=\u201cIt is,\u201d he said grimly, \u201ca lottery.\u201d |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821145107/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/international/euro_2008/article4194156.ece |archivedate=21 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> described them as such after their teams had respectively won and lost shoot-outs. Others disagree. Mitch Phillips called it \"the ultimate test of nerve and technique\".<ref name=\"mitch\" />  Paul Doyle emphasised the psychological element.<ref name=\"doyle\" />\n\nOnly a small subset of a footballer's skills is tested by a shoot-out. Ian Thomsen likened deciding the [[1994 FIFA World Cup Final|1994 World Cup]] using a penalty shoot-out to deciding the [[Masters Tournament|Masters golf tournament]] via a [[minigolf]] game.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ian  |last=Thomsen  |date=20 July 1994 |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |title=For Soccer to Win American Hearts, It Must Create Some Heroes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/20/sports/20iht-ian_8.html?pagewanted=all |accessdate=2013-01-07 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107120245/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/20/sports/20iht-ian_8.html?pagewanted=all |archivedate=7 January 2013}}\n</ref>  The shoot-out is a test of individuals which may be considered inappropriate in a team sport; [[Sepp Blatter]] has said \"Football is a team sport and penalties is not a team, it is the individual\".<ref name=\"blatter\">{{cite news |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/09/27/sports/rules.php |title=Soccer: Blatter against shoot-out in final |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |date=27 September 2006 |accessdate=2008-06-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016091110/http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/09/27/sports/rules.php |archivedate=16 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nInferior teams are tempted to play for a scoreless draw, calculating that a shoot-out offers their best hope of victory.<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Moss |date=15 March 2007 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=In praise of the nine-day draw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/mar/15/someoftheloopiermembers |accessdate=2008-06-29 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141002225817/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/mar/15/someoftheloopiermembers |archivedate=2 October 2014 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> [[Red Star Belgrade]]'s performance beating [[Olympique Marseille]] in the [[1991 European Cup Final]] is often condemned for having \"played for penalties\" from the kick-off;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/england/2953134.stm |title=Serbia & Montenegro's new dawn |first=Nada |last=Grkinic |date=31 May 2003 |accessdate=2008-06-29 |work=[[bbc.co.uk]] |quote=Red Star Belgrade had won the European Cup in 1991 and, despite the poverty of that particular performance \u2013 they played for penalties against Marseille from kick-off \u2013 the club was rich in talent. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511141627/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/england/2953134.stm |archivedate=11 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Rookwood |author2=Matthew Cunningham |date=19 June 2003 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=Made in Britain \u2013 but successful abroad? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/jun/19/sport.comment1 |accessdate=6 July 2016 |quote=OM reached the European Cup final in 1991 but were beaten by a shameful Red Star Belgrade side who played for penalties from the start. |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826034816/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/jun/19/sport.comment1 |archivedate=26 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> a tactic coach [[Ljupko Petrovi\u0107]] freely admitted to.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob |last=Smyth |date=10 July 2007 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=The joy of six: inspired tactical switches |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2007/07/10/the_joy_of_six_inspired_tactic.html |accessdate=2008-06-29 |quote=We realised we could not really beat Marseille unless they made a mistake, so I told my players to be patient and to wait for penalties, said the manager Petrovi\u0107. |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713214900/http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2007/07/10/the_joy_of_six_inspired_tactic.html |archivedate=13 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> On the other hand, the increased opportunity for [[Upset (competition)|giant-killing]] may also be seen as an advantage, increasing the romance of a competition like the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Glenn |last=Roeder |authorlink=Glenn Roeder |date=27 February 2007 |work=[[The Guardian]] |title=Big debate: should FA Cup replays be scrapped? |url=http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2007/02/28/debate_should_fa_cup_replays_b.html |accessdate=2008-06-29 |quote=Extra-time and shoot-outs could offer smaller teams fantastic chances of extended cup runs. |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302080307/http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2007/02/28/debate_should_fa_cup_replays_b.html |archivedate=2 March 2007 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> Some teams have regarded, or been accused of regarding, a loss on penalties as an honourable result or \"no defeat at all\".<ref name=\"mitch\">{{cite news |first=Mitch |last=Phillips |date=25 June 2008 |work=[[Reuters]] |title=Mental approach holds key to penalty success |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/06/25/uk-soccer-euro-penalties-idUKL1951355120080625 |accessdate=2013-01-07 | location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107121053/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2008/06/25/uk-soccer-euro-penalties-idUKL1951355120080625 |archivedate=7 January 2013}}\n</ref>\n\n''The Economist'' reported on the advantage of the team kicking first usually wins and on the players aiming higher usually score a goal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=The Economist|date=|title=Football Penalties: The Lucky 12 Yards|url=|journal=The Economist|volume=June 23rd-29th, 2018|pages=68\u201369|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Advantage to team kicking first?===\n[[Ignacio Palacios-Huerta]] has suggested that the alternating kick sequence gives an unfair advantage to the team kicking first, with statistical evidence showing that the team kicking first wins in 60% of the cases, likely due to the team kicking second being under more pressure when trailing in the shoot-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sciencenordic.com/winning-shootouts-first-kick|title=Winning shootouts on the first kick|publisher=Science Nordic|date=3 December 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922195004/http://sciencenordic.com/winning-shootouts-first-kick|archivedate=22 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As a remedy, he proposed using the [[Thue-Morse sequence#Equitable sequencing|Thue-Morse sequence]] to determine the kicking order.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Palacios-Huerta|first=Ignacio|title=Tournaments, fairness and the prouhet-thue-morse sequence|journal=Economic Inquiry|year=2012|volume=50|issue=3|pages=848\u2013849|url=http://www.palacios-huerta.com/docs/EI-Tournaments_and_PTM_sequence.pdf|accessdate=19 February 2013|doi=10.1111/j.1465-7295.2011.00435.x|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520202649/http://www.palacios-huerta.com/docs/EI-Tournaments_and_PTM_sequence.pdf|archivedate=20 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs part of a trial to reduce this advantage, the [[International Football Association Board|IFAB]] sanctioned in March 2017 to test a different sequence of taking penalties, known as \"ABBA\", that mirrors the serving sequence in a [[Tennis score#Scoring a tiebreak game|tennis tiebreak]] (team A kicks first, team B kicks second):<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/03/03/penalty-shoot-outs-could-soon-resemble-tennis-tie-breaks/|title=Penalty shoot-outs could soon resemble tennis tie-breaks|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=3 March 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012124241/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/03/03/penalty-shoot-outs-could-soon-resemble-tennis-tie-breaks/|archivedate=12 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n;Original sequence\n:AB AB AB AB AB (sudden death starts) AB AB etc.\n;Trial sequence\n:AB BA AB BA AB (sudden death starts) BA AB etc.\n\nThe trial was initially scheduled at the [[2017 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] and the [[2017 UEFA Women's Under-17 Championship]] in May 2017 if a penalty shoot-out would be needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.org/protecting-the-game/refereeing/news/newsid=2463576.html|title=Penalty shoot-out trial at UEFA final tournaments|publisher=UEFA.org|date=1 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607211119/http://www.uefa.org/protecting-the-game/refereeing/news/newsid=2463576.html|archivedate=7 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The trial was extended in June 2017 to include the [[2017 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] and the [[2017 UEFA Women's Under-19 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Comprehensive bidding regulations approved for all finals and final tournaments|url=http://www.uefa.org/mediaservices/newsid=2474545.html|website=UEFA.org|accessdate=1 June 2017|date=1 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603223013/http://www.uefa.org/mediaservices/newsid=2474545.html|archivedate=3 June 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe penalty shoot-out in the Women's Under-17 Championship semi-final between Germany and Norway was the first ever to implement this new system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-uefa-penalties-idUKKBN18730W|title=New penalty system gets usual result as Germany win|work=Reuters|date=11 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514180147/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-uefa-penalties-idUKKBN18730W|archivedate=14 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was also used in the [[2017 FA Community Shield]] on 6 August 2017.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Rostance |title=Arsenal 1\u20131 Chelsea (Arsenal won 4\u20131 on pens) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40766983 |work=BBC Sport |date=6 August 2017 |accessdate=17 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814010239/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40766983 |archivedate=14 August 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the IFAB's 133rd Annual Business Meeting in [[Glasgow]], Scotland on 22 November 2018, it was agreed that due to the lack of strong support mainly because of its complexity, the ABBA option would no longer be used in future competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2018/m=11/news=ifab-s-133rd-annual-business-meeting-recommends-fine-tuning-laws-for-the-benefit.html|title=IFAB's 133rd Annual Business Meeting recommends fine-tuning Laws for the benefit of the game|publisher=FIFA.com|date=22 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Alternatives==\nVarious tie-break methods have been proposed, both before and since shoot-outs were introduced.\n\nHistorically, one of the first tie-breaking procedures was contained in the [[wikisource:Sheffield Rules#Rules of 1862|Sheffield Rules]] between 1862 and 1871, with the concept of the ''rouge'', scorable when the ball went narrowly wide off the goal. Rule&nbsp;14 stated \"A goal outweighs any number of rouges. Should no goals or an equal number be obtained, the match is decided by rouges\". Similarly, the [[Try (rugby)|try]] in [[rugby football]] was used from 1875 as a tie-breaker if teams were level on goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/scoring.htm |title=Scoring through the ages |last=Trueman |first=Nigel |work=Rugby football history |accessdate=2009-10-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804112452/http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/scoring.htm |archivedate=4 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\nA drawn result may be allowed to stand, unless the fixture determines which team qualifies for a later round.  Before 1993 (except in [[1974 FA Charity Shield|1974]]) the [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] was shared if the match was drawn. When the [[Football at the 1972 Summer Olympics#Bronze Medal match|third place playoff of the 1972 Olympic tournament]] between the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviets]] and [[East Germany national football team|East Germany]] ended 2\u20132 after extra time,<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=197110/matches/match=32161/report.html Olympic Football Tournament Munich 1972: Soviet Union \u2013 German Democratic Republic] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104213935/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=197110/matches/match=32161/report.html |date=4 November 2013 }} FIFA.com\n</ref> the bronze medal was shared by the two teams.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=8229/news/newsid=92858.html The Olympic Odyssey so far... (Part 2: 1968 \u2013 2000)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104213849/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=8229/news/newsid=92858.html |date=4 November 2013 }} FIFA.com 10 June 2004\n</ref>\n\nDuring the [[1962 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification process]] for the [[1962 World Cup]], Morocco and Tunisia formed a two-team group. They both won 2\u20131 at home, so they played a third match at a neutral location. When this ended in a 1\u20131 draw after extra time, Morocco advanced on a coin toss to the next round of qualification. This scenario was repeated during the [[1970 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification process]] for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]], when the same two teams were tied after three matches and extra time. Again, Morocco advanced on a coin toss. Tunisia did have better luck with the coin toss in the intervening years; during the [[1965 African Cup of Nations]], they reached the final at the expense of Senegal by winning a coin toss after three group matches had left Tunisia and Senegal tied with a win (over Ethiopia) and a draw (against each other).\n\nCurrent alternatives include replaying a match that has ended in a draw. This still occurs in the fifth (last sixteen) round and earlier rounds of the [[FA Cup|English FA Cup]]. Until 1991, any number of replays were permitted, with a record of five.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/05/48711.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20040106155319/http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/TheFACup/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2003/05/48711.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 January 2004 |title=FA Cup Trivia |date=16 May 2003 |accessdate=2008-06-15 |publisher=[[The Football Association|FA]]}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=May 2018}} (Since then, a draw in the (first) replay has been resolved by a penalty-shoot-out.) Only once, in [[1974 European Cup Final|1974]], did the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] final go to a replay.\n\nOther suggestions have included using elements of match play such as most shots on goal, most [[corner kick]]s awarded, fewest [[Misconduct (association football)|cautions and sendings-off]], or having ongoing [[extra time]] with teams compelled to remove players at progressive intervals (similar to regular season play in the [[National Hockey League]], where players play 3-on-3 in the extra time).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.penaltyshootouts.co.uk/alternatives.html |title=Penalty Shoot-outs: alternatives |first=Jon |last=Billsberry |author2=Nathalie van Meurs |author3=Patrick Nelson |author4=Gareth Edwards |accessdate=2008-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624181210/http://www.penaltyshootouts.co.uk/alternatives.html |archivedate=24 June 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> These proposals have not yet been authorised by the [[International Football Association Board]]. However, after the 2006 World Cup, [[Sepp Blatter]] stated that he wants no more penalty shoot-outs in the Final of the World Cup, tentatively suggesting either a replay or \"Maybe to take players away and play [[golden goal]]\".<ref name=\"blatter\" />\n\nHenry Birtles' \"Advantage\" proposal is for the shoot-out to be held before extra-time, and only acting as a tiebreak if the game remains a draw after the full 120 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/33743/FIFA-ponder-end-to-shoot-out-woe |title=FIFA ponder end to shoot-out woe |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=4 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-20 |first=Bill |last=Bradshaw }}\n</ref> Proponents of this idea state that it would lead to a more offensive extra-time as one of the teams would know they have to score and there would never be a match in which both teams are simply waiting for penalties. Another advantage is that players who have missed would have a chance to redeem themselves in extra-time. The obvious flaw is that the team that wins the penalty shoot-out would be inclined to play defensively in extra time in the knowledge that a draw would put them through. However, this flaw is not so clear because a single goal makes the difference between winning and losing, as opposed to a team which defends a single-goal lead more comfortably because a conceded goal is the difference between winning and drawing.\n\nAnother alternative is Attacker Defender Goalkeeper (ADG), which features a series of ten contests, in which an attacker has thirty seconds to score a goal against a defender and goalkeeper. At the completion of the ten contests, the team with the most goals is the winner.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theadgalternative.com/ |title=Theadgalternative.com |publisher=Theadgalternative.com |date=5 August 2010 |accessdate=2012-05-19 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110224090150/http://www.theadgalternative.com/ |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bleacherreport.com/articles/1195909-10-alternatives-to-a-penalty-shootout |title=10 Alternatives to Penalty Shootouts |last=Tidey |first=Will |work=Bleacher Report |accessdate=2012-11-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103150137/http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1195909-10-alternatives-to-a-penalty-shootout |archivedate=3 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>\n\n==North American experiments==\nThe [[North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984)|North American Soccer League]] (NASL) in the 1970s and 1980s, then [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) for its first four seasons (1996\u20131999) experimented with a variation of the shoot-out procedure.\n\nInstead of a straight penalty kick, the shoot-out started {{convert|35|yd|m|abbr=out|disp=or}} from the goal and having five seconds to attempt a shot. The player could make as many moves as he could in a breakaway situation in the five seconds, then attempt a shot. This procedure is similar to that used in an [[Penalty shot (ice hockey)|ice hockey penalty shot]]. As with a standard shoot-out, this variation used a best-of-five-kicks model, and if the score was still level, the tiebreaker would head to an extra round of one attempt per team.\n\nThis format rewarded player skills, as players were able to attempt to deceive goalkeepers and play the ball in an attempt to make the shot, as in a one-on-one skills contest, and goalkeepers could take on the attackers without restrictions that are normally implemented in penalty shootouts. [[Soccer Bowl '81]], the NASL's 1981 championship final, was decided by this format.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kyG1cBb-cpM|title=NASL Soccer Bowl '81|last=thecelebratedmisterk|date=13 April 2010|accessdate=3 May 2018|via=YouTube|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531020714/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kyG1cBb-cpM|archivedate=31 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFrom its inception in [[1968 North American Soccer League season|1968]], the NASL used an unconventional point system in determining the league standings. Teams were awarded six points for a win and three points for a draw. In addition, teams earned one bonus point for each goal scored in a game up to a maximum of three per game. Thus, a team that lost 5\u20133 would earn three points. However, a team that lost 1\u20130 would earn no points. Also, a team that won 5\u20134 would earn nine points (the same as a 3\u20130 win). But a team that won 2\u20130 would earn only eight points. In the league's second season ([[1969 North American Soccer League season|1969]]), the [[Kansas City Spurs]] were the league champions with 10 wins, 2 losses and 4 ties even though the [[Atlanta Chiefs]] had 11 wins, 2 losses and 3 ties, because Kansas City earned more bonus points. Starting with [[1971 North American Soccer League season|1971]] postseason playoff matches, the NASL used a [[golden goal]] rule, and every match had a winner decided from the run of play. Extra-time sessions were 15 minutes long before a brief break and change of ends. Game 1 of the 1971 NASL semifinal series between the [[Rochester Lancers (1967\u201380)|Rochester Lancers]] and the [[Dallas Tornado]] went six extra-time periods with Rochester scoring the game-winning goal in the 176th minute. Game 3 of that same series went four extra time periods with Dallas scoring in the 148th minute to win the match and the series. In [[1975 North American Soccer League season|1975]], the NASL adopted a conventional penalty-kick shootout system for all regular-season and postseason playoff matches, and there were no longer any NASL matches that ended in ties. In the standings, a team that won in regulation time was awarded six points. A team that won in a penalty-kick shootout was awarded one point. Bonus points continued to be awarded for each goal scored up to a maximum of three per game. In [[1977 North American Soccer League season|1977]], the NASL adopted the experimental North American shootout procedure described above. If a match was tied after 90 minutes, a maximum of two golden goal extra time periods of 7.5 minutes each were played. If neither team scored, the shootout was held to determine the winner of the match. In the standings, a team that won was awarded six points whether the win came in regulation time, extra time or by shootout. Bonus points continued to be awarded for each goal scored up to a maximum of three per game. No bonus points were awarded for goals scored in extra time. Postseason playoff games were decided in the same manner. In [[1981 North American Soccer League season|1981]], the number of points awarded to a team that won a game in a shootout was reduced from six to four. This remained the system until the NASL's final season in [[1984 North American Soccer League season|1984]].\n\nFrom its inception in [[1996 Major League Soccer season|1996]], MLS used the shootout system that had been used by the NASL to determine winners of matches. No regular-season or postseason playoff games ended in a tie. In general, no extra time was played; the shootout commenced immediately after 90 minutes had been played. The only exception was in the [[MLS Cup '96|MLS Cup Final]] in which a match tied after 90 minutes would be followed by a maximum of two 15-minute extra time sessions on a golden goal basis. In the regular-season standings, a team that won a match in regulation was awarded three points. A team that won a match in a shootout was awarded one point. There were no bonus points or points awarded to teams that lost whether in regulation time or a shootout. In the playoffs, the conference semifinals and conference finals were organized as best-of-three matches series. A shootout win counted as a win. Thus, a team could win two of the three matches by shootout and lose the other match in regulation and still advance to the next round. This was inconsistent with how the teams were rewarded during the regular season when the team with one win would have earned three points, and the team with two wins would have earned only two points. In [[1999 Major League Soccer season|1999]], a maximum of two 15-minute golden goal extra time periods were added for matches that were tied after 90 minutes of regulation play. If neither team scored during extra time, the match was decided by a shootout. MLS abandoned the North American style shootout starting with the [[2000 Major League Soccer season|2000 season]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Alex|last=Yannis|date=18 November 1999|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=M.L.S. is Making Changes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/18/sports/soccer-mls-is-making-changes.html|accessdate=13 July 2014|location=New York|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714180417/http://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/18/sports/soccer-mls-is-making-changes.html|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> If penalties are required to determine a winner during the playoffs, MLS now uses the shoot-out procedure specified by the International Football Association Board.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of FIFA World Cup penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[List of FIFA Women's World Cup penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[List of UEFA European Championship penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[List of Copa Am\u00e9rica penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[List of CONCACAF Gold Cup penalty shoot-outs]]\n* [[Penalty shoot-out]]\n* [[Penalty kick (association football)|Penalty kick]]\n* [[Golden goal]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''On Penalties'' by Andrew Anthony ({{ISBN|0-224-06116-X}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Penalty shootout (association football)}}\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/penalties.html Penalty Shoot-out Trivia] \u2014 [[rec.sport.soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]\n* [http://www.penaltyshoot-outs.co.uk/index.html Penalty Shoot-outs]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \u2014 by four researchers associated with the Fit Project at the [[Open University]]\n\n[[Category:Association football penalty shoot-outs| ]]\n[[Category:Laws of association football]]\n[[Category:Association football terminology]]\n[[Category:Street football games]]\n[[Category:Sports penalties]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c6:6286:3100:bc1e:a591:58b9:acbb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eUEFA club competitions)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penalty_shoot-out_(association_football)"}
{"title_page": "Los Angeles Dragons (American football)", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Los Angeles Dragons (American football)|timestamp=20200425171831|year=2020|month=April|day=25|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Los Angeles Dragons (American football)|date=25 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{USFootball team\n|logo           = Los_Angeles_Dragons_logo.png\n|pixels         =\n|founded        = 2000\n|folded         = 2000\n|league         = [[Spring Football League]]\n|history        =\n|stadium        = [[Los Angeles Memorial coliseum]]\n|city           = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n|colors         = \n|owner          =\n|coach          = Doug Cosbie\n|championships  = \n|titles         =\n}}\n\nThe '''Los Angeles Dragons''' were a [[Professional sports|professional]] [[American football]] team based in [[Los Angeles, California]] that played in the [[Spring Football League]] in 2000.<ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/rememberthesfl/news Associated Press story on SFL]</ref> The Dragons [[Head Coach]] was [[Doug Cosbie]], who played for the [[Dallas Cowboys]]. The Dragons played their home games at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]. \n\nDragons players of note:\n\n*[[Craig Walendy]] - (UCLA, New York Giants)\n*[[Saladin McCullough]] - (Oregon, San Francisco 49ers)\n*[[Chris Sailer]] - (UCLA, San Francisco 49ers)\n*Greg Ainsworth - (Oregon State. Cincinnati Bengals)\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{stub}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Los Angeles Dragons (American football)|timestamp=20200425171831|year=2020|month=April|day=25|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Los Angeles Dragons (American football)|date=25 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{USFootball team\n|logo           = Los_Angeles_Dragons_logo.png\n|pixels         =\n|founded        = 2000\n|folded         = 2000\n|league         = [[Spring Football League]]\n|history        =\n|stadium        = [[Los Angeles Memorial coliseum]]\n|city           = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n|colors         = \n|owner          =\n|coach          = Doug Cosbie\n|championships  = \n|titles         =\n}}\n\nThe '''Los Angeles Dragons''' were a [[Professional sports|professional]] [[American football]] team based in [[Los Angeles, California]] that played in the [[Spring Football League]] in 2000.<ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/rememberthesfl/news Associated Press story on SFL]</ref> The Dragons [[Head Coach]] was [[Doug Cosbie]], who played for the [[Dallas Cowboys]]. The Dragons played their home games at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]. \n\nDragons players of note:\n\n*[[Craig Walendy]] - (UCLA, New York Giants)\n*[[Saladin McCullough]] - (Oregon, San Francisco 49ers)\n*[[Chris Sailor]] - (UCLA, San Francisco 49ers)\n*Greg Ainsworth - (Oregon State. Cincinnati Bengals)\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{stub}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_Angeles_Dragons_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "Age discrimination in the United States", "text_new": "In the United States, all states have passed laws that restrict [[age discrimination]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Discrimination \u2013 Employment Laws |url=https://www.ncsl.org/research/labor-and-employment/discrimination-employment.aspx |website=National Conference of State Legislatures |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=27 July 2015}}</ref> and federal law prohibits age discrimination against persons over the age of forty.<ref>{{cite web |title=Age Discrimination |url=https://www.eeoc.gov/laws/types/age.cfm |website=U.S. Equal Opportunity Commission |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable U.S. law regarding age discrimination==\nThe  [[Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967]] (ADEA) is a law that provides certain employment protections to workers who are over the age of forty, who work for an employer who has twenty or more employees. For protected workers, the ADEA prohibits discrimination at all levels of employment, from recruitment and hiring, through the employment relationship, and through decisions for layoffs or termination of the employment relationship.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Larson|first1=Aaron|title=Age Discrimination Law|url=https://www.expertlaw.com/library/employment/age_discrimination.html|website=ExpertLaw|accessdate=28 September 2017|date=25 July 2016}}</ref> An age limit may only be legally specified in the circumstance where age has been shown to be a \"[[bona fide occupational qualification]] [BFOQ] reasonably necessary to the normal operation of the particular business\" (see {{usc|29|623(f)(1)}}). In practice, BFOQs for age are limited to the obvious (hiring a young actor to play a young character in a movie) or when public safety is at stake (for example, in the case of age limits for pilots and bus drivers). The ADEA does not stop an employer from favoring an older employee over a younger one, even when the younger one is over 40 years old.<ref>{{ussc|name=General Dynamics Land Sys., Inc. v. Cline|link=|volume=540|page=581|pin=|year=2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, the [[EEOC]] declared age restrictions on flight attendants' employment to be illegal sex discrimination under [[Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref>{{cite web|author=K Barry |url=http://femininityinflight.com/activism.html |title=Timeline of Discrimination |publisher=Femininity in Flight |accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Older Americans Amendments of 1975]] ({{USPL|94|135}}) is an Act of the 94th U.S. Congress amending the Older Americans Act of 1965. It prohibits discrimination based on age in programs or activities that receive federal financial assistance, for instance, financial assistance to schools and colleges, provided by the [[U.S. Department of Education]].<ref>{{cite web|title=United States \u2013 Older Americans Amendments of 1975. Public Law 94-134 (H.R. 3922).|url=http://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/natlex4.detail?p_lang=en&p_isn=18760&p_classification=08.02|website=www.ilo.org|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Older Americans Amendments of 1975 (A Compilation of Public Law 94-135, Accompanying Reports, and Related Acts) V. 1|url=http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.leghis/olderaa0001&div=1&src=home|website=heinonline.org|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 1986, the [[Fair Labor Standards Act]] was amended to allow the [[United States Secretary of Labor]] to provide special certificates to allow an employer to pay less than the minimum wage to individuals whose earning or productive capacity is impaired by age, physical or mental deficiency, or injury.<ref name= s2884>\"[https://www.congress.gov/bill/99th-congress/senate-bill/2884?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22%5C%22fair+labor+standards%5C%22%22%5D%7D&r=1 S.2884 \u2014 99th Congress (1985\u20131986)]\". ''United States Congress''. October 16, 1986.</ref> These employees must still be paid wages that are related to the individual's productivity and commensurate with those paid to similarly located and employed nonhandicapped workers.<ref name= s2884/>\n\n[[Mandatory retirement]] due to age is generally unlawful in the United States, except in certain industries and occupations that are regulated by law, and are often part of the government (such as military service and federal police agencies, such as the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]). [[Minnesota]] has statutorily established mandatory retirement for all judges at age 70 (more precisely, at the end of the month a judge reaches that age). The [[Minnesota Legislature]] has had the constitutional right to set judicial retirement ages since 1956, but did not do so until 1973, setting the age at 70.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/politics/ci_28448632/rachel-stassen-berger-minnesota-judges-arent-making-fuss |title=Minnesota judges aren't making a fuss about retirement rule |first=Rachel E. |last=Stassen-Berger |newspaper=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press|Pioneer Press]] |location=[[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul, MN]] |date=July 7, 2015 |accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> The Federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act, which became law in 1986, ended mandatory age-related retirement at age 70 for many jobs, not including the Minnesota judiciary;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/politics/ci_28448632/rachel-stassen-berger-minnesota-judges-arent-making-fuss |title=Minnesota judges aren't making a fuss about retirement rule |first=Rachel E. |last=Stassen-Berger |newspaper=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press|Pioneer Press]] |location=[[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul, MN]] |date=July 7, 2015 |accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> another exception was all postsecondary institutions (colleges, etc.) This exception ended on December 31, 1993.<ref> https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.3102/0013189X13497993</ref><ref> Sanjek, Roger (2009). Gray Panthers. Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 185.</ref> The Fair Treatment for Experienced Pilots Act (Public Law 110-135) went into effect on December 13, 2007, raising the mandatory retirement age for pilots to 65 from the previous 60.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.faa.gov/news/press_releases/news_story.cfm?newsId=10072 |title=FAA Statement on Pilot Retirement Age |date=14 December 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States federal [[minimum wage]] laws allow for employers to pay lower wages to young workers. Many state and local minimum wage laws mirror such an age-based, tiered minimum wage.<ref>[http://www.dol.gov/esa/minwage/q-a.htm Questions and Answers About the Minimum Wage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403074514/http://www.dol.gov/esa/minwage/q-a.htm |date=3 April 2007 }}, US Department of Labor</ref>\n\nIn the United States, a person must generally be at least 14 years old to seek a job, and workers face additional restrictions on their work activities until they reach age 16.<ref>[http://www.dol.gov/dol/topic/youthlabor/agerequirements.htm Youth & Labor \u2013 Age Requirements], US Department of Labor</ref> Many companies refuse to hire workers younger than 18.\n\nSome U.S. political offices have qualifications that discriminate on the basis of age. For example, the President of the United States must be at least 35 years old; a [[United States Senator]] must be at least 30; and a [[United States Congress]] member must be at least 25. \n\nThe [[District of Columbia]] and twelve states ([[California]], [[Florida]], [[Iowa]], [[Hawaii]], [[Kansas]], [[Louisiana]], [[Maine]], [[Minnesota]], [[Nebraska]], [[New Mexico]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Vermont]]) define age as a specific motivation for hate crimes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.adl.org/learn/hate_crimes_laws/State_Hate_Crime_Statutory_Provisions_chart.pdf |title= Anti-Defamation League State Hate Crime Statutory Provisions (2005) |access-date= 22 May 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110629085842/http://www.adl.org/learn/hate_crimes_laws/State_Hate_Crime_Statutory_Provisions_chart.pdf |archive-date= 29 June 2011 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}&nbsp;{{small|(23.8&nbsp;KB)}} (See page 1, section \"Other\", note 2) Retrieved on 21 May 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/discrimination/pdf/everyday-fears-080805.pdf |title= Everyday Fears \u2013 A Survey of Violent Hate Crimes in Europe and North America |access-date= 22 May 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060112034643/http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/discrimination/pdf/everyday-fears-080805.pdf |archive-date= 12 January 2006 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}&nbsp;{{small|(1.96&nbsp;MB)}} McClintock, Michael (See pages 84 and 122, Appendix 10, \"Others\", note 2) Retrieved on 21 May 2009</ref>\n\n===Notable U.S. court cases regarding age discrimination===\nIn ''[[Western Air Lines, Inc v Criswell]]'' 472 US 400 (1985) the United States Supreme Court held it was lawful to require airline pilots to retire at 60, because the Federal Aviation Authority forbid using pilots over 60 in aviation. But the Court held that refusing to employ flight engineers over that age was unjustified as there were no such FAA requirements. (Note that The Fair Treatment for Experienced Pilots Act (Public Law 110-135) went into effect on December 13, 2007, raising the mandatory retirement age for pilots to 65 from the previous 60.)<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.faa.gov/news/press_releases/news_story.cfm?newsId=10072 |title=FAA Statement on Pilot Retirement Age |date=14 December 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n''[[DeMarco v. Holy Cross High School]]'' 4 F.3d 166 (2nd Cir. 1993) was an employment discrimination case brought under the ADEA ([[Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967]]). The appellant, Guy DeMarco, was released from employment prior to his eligibility for tenure at the age of forty-nine. Holy Cross High School argued that it was not subject to ADEA laws, and if it were that this case against it was in violation of the [[Free Exercise Clause]] and the [[Establishment Clause]] of the [[First Amendment]]. The defendant also argued that the plaintiff failed to utilize the administrative remedies available. The court noted that other anti-discrimination statutes were held to be applicable to religious organizations, with the exception of statutes that prohibited discrimination based on religious belief. Since statutes prohibiting discrimination by race, gender and national origin were already found applicable to religious organizations, it was logical (and a reasonable interpretation of the legislative history) to extend the prohibition against age discrimination to religious organizations as well.<ref>Id. Paragraph 24</ref> The decision of the district court was reversed and the case remanded for further proceedings.<ref>Id. Paragraph 25</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Kimel v. Florida Bd. of Regents]]'', 528 U.S. 62 (2000), the United States Supreme Court held that state employees cannot sue states for monetary damages under the [[Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967]] in federal court.<ref>{{ussc|name=Kimel v. Florida Board of Regents|link=|volume=528|page=62|pin=|year=2000}}</ref> The [[EEOC]] may still enforce the ADEA against states, and state employees may still sue state officials for [[declaratory relief|declaratory]] and [[injunctive relief]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Feder |first=Jody |title=The Age Discrimination in Employment Act  (ADEA): A Legal Overview |url=http://aging.senate.gov/crs/aging21.pdf |publisher=Congressional Research Service, June 23, 2010, p. 2 |accessdate=3 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705135926/http://aging.senate.gov/crs/aging21.pdf |archivedate=5 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Gomez-Perez v. Potter]]'' (2008), the United States Supreme Court allowed federal workers who experience retaliation as a result of reporting age discrimination under the law to sue for damages.<ref>{{ussc|name=Gomez-Perez v. Potter|link=|volume=553|page=474|pin=|year=2008}}</ref>\n\nThe United States Supreme Court, in [[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 554|''Meacham v. Knolls Atomic Power Lab'']], 554 U.S. 84 (2008), held that the employer, not the employee, bears the burden of proving that a layoff or other action that hurts older workers more than others was based not on age but on some other \u201creasonable factor.\u201d<ref name=NYTimes01>{{cite news|last=Greenhouse|first=Linda|title=A Supreme Court Victory for Older Workers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/20/washington/20scotus.html|accessdate=March 1, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 20, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the United States Supreme Court issued its opinion on ''[[Gross v. FBL Financial Services, Inc.]]''. In a 5\u20134 opinion, the Court ruled that private-sector plaintiffs must prove that age was the \"but for\" cause of the adverse employment action they are suing over. <ref name= Preview>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotusblog.com/2020/01/argument-preview-what-counts-as-discrimination-based-on-age|title=Argument preview: What counts as discrimination \u201cbased on\u201d age?|last=Garden|first=Charlotte|date=2020-01-08|website=SCOTUSBlog|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref name= LawDaily/> That is, the plaintiff must prove that age discrimination was the determining reason for the adverse employment action (e.g. the action would not have been taken 'but for' the plaintiff's age).<ref name= Forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/patriciagbarnes/2019/10/04/high-court-to-address-the-muddled-mess-of-the-age-discrimination-in-employment-act/#72d6e76615a8|title=High Court To Address The Muddled Mess Of The Age Discrimination In Employment Act|last=Barnes|first=Patricia|date=2019-10-04|website=Forbes|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> However, the Supreme Court's opinion did not explicitly mention public-sector workers.<ref name= Newsweek>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/what-wednesdays-supreme-court-case-could-mean-age-discrimination-workplace-1480157|title=WHAT WEDNESDAY'S SUPREME COURT CASE COULD MEAN FOR AGE DISCRIMINATION IN THE WORKPLACE|last=Moyler|first=Hunter|date=2020-01-14|website=Newsweek|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> A later opinion, ''[[University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center v. Nassar]]'' (2013) applied the same 'but for' standard to [[Workplace retaliation|retaliation claims]].\n\n''[[Babb v. Wilkie]]'', No. 18-882, , 589 U.S. ___ (2020), is a case of the United States Supreme Court in which the justices considered the scope of protections for federal employees in the [[Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967]]. Specifically, the Court ruled that plaintiffs only need to prove that age was a [[Mixed motive discrimination|motivating factor]] in the decision in order to sue.<ref name=BabbSCOTUS>{{ussc|name=Babb v. Wilkie|volume=589|year=2020|docket=18-882}}</ref> However, establishing [[Sine qua non#\"But-for\" causation in law|but for]] causation is still necessary in determining the appropriate remedy. If a plaintiff can establish that the age was the determinining factor in the employment outcome, they may be entitled to compensatory damages or other relief relating to the end result of the employment decision.<ref name= LawDaily>{{cite web|url=http://www.employmentlawdaily.com/index.php/news/supreme-court-to-determine-whether-but-for-causation-required-in-federal-sector-adea-claims/|title=Supreme Court to determine whether \u2018but-for\u2019 causation required in federal-sector ADEA claims\n|date=2019-07-02|website=Employment Law Daily|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/employment/articles/1260655/breaking-federal-workers-can-sue-over-any-age-bias-justices-rule|title=BREAKING: Federal Workers Can Sue Over 'Any' Age Bias, Justices Rule|date=2020-04-06|website=Law360|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Notable activism against age discrimination in the United States==\nThe [[Newsboys Strike of 1899]] fought ageist employment practices targeted against youth by large newspaper syndicates in the Northeast. The strikers demonstrated across the city for several days, effectively stopping circulation of the two papers, along with the news distribution for many [[New England]] cities. The [[Strike action|strike]] lasted two weeks, causing Pulitzer's ''[[New York World]]'' to decrease its circulation from 360,000 papers sold per day to 125,000.<ref>Nasaw, David. (1999) \"Ch. 3: Youse an' yer noble scrap: On strike with the Newsboy Legion in 1899.\" in ''Big Town, Big Time.'' New York: New York Daily News. p. 9.</ref> Although the price of papers was not lowered, the strike was successful in forcing the ''World'' and ''Journal'' to offer full buybacks to their sellers, thus increasing the amount of money that newsies received for their work.<ref>Mott, F.L. (2000) ''American Journalism''. New York: Routledge. p. 598.</ref>\n\nThe [[American Youth Congress]], or AYC, was formed in 1935 to advocate for [[youth rights]] in U.S. politics.<ref>Black, A., Hopkins, J. ''et al.'' (2003) [http://www.nps.gov/archive/elro/glossary/american-youth-congress.htm \"American Youth Congress,\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019032029/http://www.nps.gov/archive/elro/glossary/american-youth-congress.htm |date=October 19, 2007 }} ''The Eleanor Roosevelt Papers.'' Teaching Eleanor Roosevelt. Hyde Park, New York: Eleanor Roosevelt National Historic Site. Retrieved 7/30/07.</ref>\nIt ended in 1940.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://newdeal.feri.org/er/er26.htm |title=Eleanor Roosevelt, \"Why I Still Believe in the Youth Congress,\" in New Deal Network: Selected Writings of Eleanor Roosevelt, originally published in ''Liberty'', (April 1940): 30\u201332. |access-date=2005-07-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006022108/http://newdeal.feri.org/er/er26.htm |archive-date=2016-10-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[AARP]] was founded in 1958 by [[Ethel Percy Andrus]] (a retired educator from California) and Leonard Davis (later the founder of the [[Colonial Penn Life Insurance Company|Colonial Penn Group]] of insurance companies).<ref>{{cite news|work=Los Angeles Times|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/jan/23/local/me-15772|date=January 23, 2001|title=Local: Obituary}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.usc.edu/6078/Obituary-AARP-founder-philanthropist-Leonard-Davis-76/|work=USC News|title=AARP Founder: Philanthropist Leonard Davis, 76}}</ref> Its stated mission is \"to empower people to choose how they live as they age\".<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aarp.org/about-aarp/|title=About AARP|last=|first=|date=|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> It is an influential [[lobbying]] group in the United States focusing largely on issues affecting the elderly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenonprofittimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/8-1-15_Top50PI.pdf|title=The 2015 Power & Influence Top 50|last=|first=|date=August 31, 2015|website=The NonProfit Times|publisher=The NonProfit Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/top-lobbyists/258317-top-lobbyists-2015-grassroots|title=Top Lobbyists 2015: Grassroots|last=Dickson|first=Rebecca|date=October 28, 2015|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref>  \n\nThe [[Gray Panthers]] was formed in 1970 by [[Maggie Kuhn]], with a goal of eliminating [[mandatory retirement]]; they now work on many [[social justice]] issues including eliminating ageism.<ref>Kuhn, M., Long, C. and Quinn, L. (1991) ''No Stone Unturned: the Life and Times of Maggie Kuhn.'' Ballantine Books.</ref><ref>https://www.aarp.org/politics-society/history/champions-of-aging-photos/older-american-maggie-kuhn-gray-panthers/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.graypanthersnyc.org/about_us/ |title=About Us |publisher=Gray Panthers Nyc |date=2018-08-27 |accessdate=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Youth Liberation of Ann Arbor]] started in 1970 to promote youth and fight ageism.\n\n[[Three O'Clock Lobby]] formed in 1976 to promote [[youth participation]] throughout traditionally ageist government structures in Michigan.\n\nOld Lesbians Organizing for Change was founded in 1987 in response to the combination of ageism and sexism affecting older lesbians. Their initial meeting was inspired by the publication of the book ''[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781883523404 Look Me in the Eye: Old Women, Aging and Ageism]'' by [[Barbara Macdonald]] and Cynthia Rich in 1983.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite web\n | url=http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss547_bioghist.html\n | title=Old Lesbians Organizing for Change Records\n | accessdate=27 March 2015\n}}</ref> The mission of the organization is to \"eliminate the oppression of ageism and to stand in solidarity against all oppressions\" through \u201c[the] cooperative community of Old Lesbian feminist activists from many backgrounds working for justice and the well-being of all old lesbians.\u201d<ref>[https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/c8z89fjx/  Old Lesbians Organizing for Change records 1986\u20131992 (Box 1) housed in the UCLA Library Special Collections]</ref>  \n\n[[Americans for a Society Free from Age Restrictions]] formed in 1996 to advance the civil and human rights of young people through eliminating ageist laws targeted against young people, and to help youth counter ageism in America.<ref>{{cite web|work=ASFAR |year=2006 |url=http://www.asfar.org/articles.php |title=Americans for a Society Free from Age Restrictions Articles of Incorporation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609192032/http://www.asfar.org/articles.php |archive-date=9 June 2007}}</ref> \n\nThe [[National Youth Rights Association]] started in 1998 to promote awareness of the legal and human rights of young people in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|work=National Youth Rights Association|year=2001|url=http://www.youthrights.org/docs/nyraarticlesofinc.pdf|title=National Youth Rights Association Articles of Incorporation (Partial)}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Freechild Project]] was formed in 2001 to identify, unify and promote diverse opportunities for youth engagement in social change by fighting ageism. In 2002 the Freechild Project created an information and training initiative to provide resources to youth organizations and schools focused on youth rights.<ref>(n.d.) [http://www.freechild.org/SNAYR/index.htm Survey of North American Youth Rights] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206100316/http://www.freechild.org/SNAYR/index.htm |date=6 February 2007 }} The Freechild Project website.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ageism]]\n*[[Elder law]]\n*[[History of youth rights in the United States]]\n*[[Nursing home residents' rights]]\n*[[Youth rights]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* Axon, K. (n.d.) [https://web.archive.org/web/20080215235519/http://www.asfar.org/zine/1st/Pedophobia.html ''The Anti-Child Bias of Children's Advocacy Groups''] Chicago, IL: [[Americans for a Society Free from Age Restrictions]].\n* Butler, T., & Berret, B. (2011). A generation lost:  the reality of age discrimination in today's hiring practices.  ''Journal of Management and Marketing Research'', 9, 1\u201311. Academic Search Complete. Web. 21 Sept. 2013.\n* {{Cite book|title =Why Survive? Being Old In America  |last = Butler|first = Robert|author-link= Robert N. Butler| publisher =Harper & Row  | year =1975  | location =  | pages =496 pages  | url =https://books.google.com/?id=_EJpAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Why+Survive%22&dq=%22Why+Survive%22  | doi =  | isbn=0-06-010591-7}}\n* ''The Children's Rights Movement: Overcoming the Oppression of Young People'', edited by Beatrice and Ronald Gross (Garden City, NY: Anchor Press/Doubleday, 1977.\n* Kuhn, M., Long, C. and Quinn, L. (1991) ''No Stone Unturned: the Life and Times of [[Maggie Kuhn]]''. Ballantine Books.\n* [[John Holt (educator)|Holt, J.]] (1974). ''[[Escape from Childhood]]: The Needs and Rights of Children''. Boston: E. P. Dutton.\n* {{Cite book|title = Look Me in the Eye: Old Women, Aging and Ageism|last = Macdonald|first = Barbara|author-link = Barbara Macdonald| publisher = Spinsters Ink Books|year = 1983|isbn = 978-1883523404|location = |pages = |last2 = Rich|first2 = Cynthia|url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781883523404}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:Ageism]]\n[[Category:Discrimination in the United States]]\n[[Category:Old age in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "In the United States, all states have passed laws that restrict [[age discrimination]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Discrimination - Employment Laws |url=https://www.ncsl.org/research/labor-and-employment/discrimination-employment.aspx |website=National Conference of State Legislatures |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=27 July 2015}}</ref> and federal law prohibits age discrimination against persons over the age of forty.<ref>{{cite web |title=Age Discrimination |url=https://www.eeoc.gov/laws/types/age.cfm |website=U.S. Equal Opportunity Commission |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable U.S. law regarding age discrimination==\nThe  [[Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967]] (ADEA) is a law that provides certain employment protections to workers who are over the age of forty, who work for an employer who has twenty or more employees. For protected workers, the ADEA prohibits discrimination at all levels of employment, from recruitment and hiring, through the employment relationship, and through decisions for layoffs or termination of the employment relationship.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Larson|first1=Aaron|title=Age Discrimination Law|url=https://www.expertlaw.com/library/employment/age_discrimination.html|website=ExpertLaw|accessdate=28 September 2017|date=25 July 2016}}</ref> An age limit may only be legally specified in the circumstance where age has been shown to be a \"[[bona fide occupational qualification]] [BFOQ] reasonably necessary to the normal operation of the particular business\" (see {{usc|29|623(f)(1)}}). In practice, BFOQs for age are limited to the obvious (hiring a young actor to play a young character in a movie) or when public safety is at stake (for example, in the case of age limits for pilots and bus drivers). The ADEA does not stop an employer from favoring an older employee over a younger one, even when the younger one is over 40 years old.<ref>{{ussc|name=General Dynamics Land Sys., Inc. v. Cline|link=|volume=540|page=581|pin=|year=2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, the [[EEOC]] declared age restrictions on flight attendants' employment to be illegal sex discrimination under [[Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964]].<ref>{{cite web|author=K Barry |url=http://femininityinflight.com/activism.html |title=Timeline of Discrimination |publisher=Femininity in Flight |accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Older Americans Amendments of 1975]] ({{USPL|94|135}}) is an Act of the 94th U.S. Congress amending the Older Americans Act of 1965. It prohibits discrimination based on age in programs or activities that receive federal financial assistance, for instance, financial assistance to schools and colleges, provided by the [[U.S. Department of Education]].<ref>{{cite web|title=United States - Older Americans Amendments of 1975. Public Law 94-134 (H.R. 3922).|url=http://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/natlex4.detail?p_lang=en&p_isn=18760&p_classification=08.02|website=www.ilo.org|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Older Americans Amendments of 1975 (A Compilation of Public Law 94-135, Accompanying Reports, and Related Acts) V. 1|url=http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.leghis/olderaa0001&div=1&src=home|website=heinonline.org|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 1986, the [[Fair Labor Standards Act]] was amended to allow the [[United States Secretary of Labor]] to provide special certificates to allow an employer to pay less than the minimum wage to individuals whose earning or productive capacity is impaired by age, physical or mental deficiency, or injury.<ref name= s2884>\"[https://www.congress.gov/bill/99th-congress/senate-bill/2884?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22%5C%22fair+labor+standards%5C%22%22%5D%7D&r=1 S.2884 \u2014 99th Congress (1985-1986)]\". ''United States Congress''. October 16, 1986.</ref> These employees must still be paid wages that are related to the individual's productivity and commensurate with those paid to similarly located and employed nonhandicapped workers.<ref name= s2884/>\n\n[[Mandatory retirement]] due to age is generally unlawful in the United States, except in certain industries and occupations that are regulated by law, and are often part of the government (such as military service and federal police agencies, such as the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]). [[Minnesota]] has statutorily established mandatory retirement for all judges at age 70 (more precisely, at the end of the month a judge reaches that age). The [[Minnesota Legislature]] has had the constitutional right to set judicial retirement ages since 1956, but did not do so until 1973, setting the age at 70.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/politics/ci_28448632/rachel-stassen-berger-minnesota-judges-arent-making-fuss |title=Minnesota judges aren't making a fuss about retirement rule |first=Rachel E. |last=Stassen-Berger |newspaper=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press|Pioneer Press]] |location=[[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul, MN]] |date=July 7, 2015 |accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> The Federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act, which became law in 1986, ended mandatory age-related retirement at age 70 for many jobs, not including the Minnesota judiciary;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/politics/ci_28448632/rachel-stassen-berger-minnesota-judges-arent-making-fuss |title=Minnesota judges aren't making a fuss about retirement rule |first=Rachel E. |last=Stassen-Berger |newspaper=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press|Pioneer Press]] |location=[[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul, MN]] |date=July 7, 2015 |accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> another exception was all postsecondary institutions (colleges, etc.) This exception ended on December 31, 1993.<ref> https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.3102/0013189X13497993</ref><ref> Sanjek, Roger (2009). Gray Panthers. Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 185.</ref> The Fair Treatment for Experienced Pilots Act (Public Law 110-135) went into effect on December 13, 2007, raising the mandatory retirement age for pilots to 65 from the previous 60.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.faa.gov/news/press_releases/news_story.cfm?newsId=10072 |title=FAA Statement on Pilot Retirement Age |date=14 December 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States federal [[minimum wage]] laws allow for employers to pay lower wages to young workers. Many state and local minimum wage laws mirror such an age-based, tiered minimum wage.<ref>[http://www.dol.gov/esa/minwage/q-a.htm Questions and Answers About the Minimum Wage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403074514/http://www.dol.gov/esa/minwage/q-a.htm |date=3 April 2007 }}, US Department of Labor</ref>\n\nIn the United States, a person must generally be at least 14 years old to seek a job, and workers face additional restrictions on their work activities until they reach age 16.<ref>[http://www.dol.gov/dol/topic/youthlabor/agerequirements.htm Youth & Labor \u2013 Age Requirements], US Department of Labor</ref> Many companies refuse to hire workers younger than 18.\n\nSome U.S. political offices have qualifications that discriminate on the basis of age. For example, the President of the United States must be at least 35 years old; a [[United States Senator]] must be at least 30; and a [[United States Congress]] member must be at least 25. \n\nThe [[District of Columbia]] and twelve states ([[California]], [[Florida]], [[Iowa]], [[Hawaii]], [[Kansas]], [[Louisiana]], [[Maine]], [[Minnesota]], [[Nebraska]], [[New Mexico]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Vermont]]) define age as a specific motivation for hate crimes.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.adl.org/learn/hate_crimes_laws/State_Hate_Crime_Statutory_Provisions_chart.pdf |title= Anti-Defamation League State Hate Crime Statutory Provisions (2005) |access-date= 22 May 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110629085842/http://www.adl.org/learn/hate_crimes_laws/State_Hate_Crime_Statutory_Provisions_chart.pdf |archive-date= 29 June 2011 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}&nbsp;{{small|(23.8&nbsp;KB)}} (See page 1, section \"Other\", note 2) Retrieved on 21 May 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/discrimination/pdf/everyday-fears-080805.pdf |title= Everyday Fears \u2013 A Survey of Violent Hate Crimes in Europe and North America |access-date= 22 May 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060112034643/http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/discrimination/pdf/everyday-fears-080805.pdf |archive-date= 12 January 2006 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}&nbsp;{{small|(1.96&nbsp;MB)}} McClintock, Michael (See pages 84 and 122, Appendix 10, \"Others\", note 2) Retrieved on 21 May 2009</ref>\n\n===Notable U.S. court cases regarding age discrimination===\nIn ''[[Western Air Lines, Inc v Criswell]]'' 472 US 400 (1985) the United States Supreme Court held it was lawful to require airline pilots to retire at 60, because the Federal Aviation Authority forbid using pilots over 60 in aviation. But the Court held that refusing to employ flight engineers over that age was unjustified as there were no such FAA requirements. (Note that The Fair Treatment for Experienced Pilots Act (Public Law 110-135) went into effect on December 13, 2007, raising the mandatory retirement age for pilots to 65 from the previous 60.)<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.faa.gov/news/press_releases/news_story.cfm?newsId=10072 |title=FAA Statement on Pilot Retirement Age |date=14 December 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n''[[DeMarco v. Holy Cross High School]]'' 4 F.3d 166 (2nd Cir. 1993) was an employment discrimination case brought under the ADEA ([[Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967]]). The appellant, Guy DeMarco, was released from employment prior to his eligibility for tenure at the age of forty-nine. Holy Cross High School argued that it was not subject to ADEA laws, and if it were that this case against it was in violation of the [[Free Exercise Clause]] and the [[Establishment Clause]] of the [[First Amendment]]. The defendant also argued that the plaintiff failed to utilize the administrative remedies available. The court noted that other anti-discrimination statutes were held to be applicable to religious organizations, with the exception of statutes that prohibited discrimination based on religious belief. Since statutes prohibiting discrimination by race, gender and national origin were already found applicable to religious organizations, it was logical (and a reasonable interpretation of the legislative history) to extend the prohibition against age discrimination to religious organizations as well.<ref>Id. Paragraph 24</ref> The decision of the district court was reversed and the case remanded for further proceedings.<ref>Id. Paragraph 25</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Kimel v. Florida Bd. of Regents]]'', 528 U.S. 62 (2000), the United States Supreme Court held that state employees cannot sue states for monetary damages under the [[Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967]] in federal court.<ref>{{ussc|name=Kimel v. Florida Board of Regents|link=|volume=528|page=62|pin=|year=2000}}</ref> The [[EEOC]] may still enforce the ADEA against states, and state employees may still sue state officials for [[declaratory relief|declaratory]] and [[injunctive relief]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Feder |first=Jody |title=The Age Discrimination in Employment Act  (ADEA): A Legal Overview |url=http://aging.senate.gov/crs/aging21.pdf |publisher=Congressional Research Service, June 23, 2010, p. 2 |accessdate=3 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110705135926/http://aging.senate.gov/crs/aging21.pdf |archivedate=5 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Gomez-Perez v. Potter]]'' (2008), the United States Supreme Court allowed federal workers who experience retaliation as a result of reporting age discrimination under the law to sue for damages.<ref>{{ussc|name=Gomez-Perez v. Potter|link=|volume=553|page=474|pin=|year=2008}}</ref>\n\nThe United States Supreme Court, in [[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 554|''Meacham v. Knolls Atomic Power Lab'']], 554 U.S. 84 (2008), held that the employer, not the employee, bears the burden of proving that a layoff or other action that hurts older workers more than others was based not on age but on some other \u201creasonable factor.\u201d<ref name=NYTimes01>{{cite news|last=Greenhouse|first=Linda|title=A Supreme Court Victory for Older Workers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/20/washington/20scotus.html|accessdate=March 1, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 20, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the United States Supreme Court issued its opinion on ''[[Gross v. FBL Financial Services, Inc.]]''. In a 5-4 opinion, the Court ruled that private-sector plaintiffs must prove that age was the \"but for\" cause of the adverse employment action they are suing over. <ref name= Preview>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotusblog.com/2020/01/argument-preview-what-counts-as-discrimination-based-on-age|title=Argument preview: What counts as discrimination \u201cbased on\u201d age?|last=Garden|first=Charlotte|date=2020-01-08|website=SCOTUSBlog|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref name= LawDaily/> That is, the plaintiff must prove that age discrimination was the determining reason for the adverse employment action (e.g. the action would not have been taken 'but for' the plaintiff's age).<ref name= Forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/patriciagbarnes/2019/10/04/high-court-to-address-the-muddled-mess-of-the-age-discrimination-in-employment-act/#72d6e76615a8|title=High Court To Address The Muddled Mess Of The Age Discrimination In Employment Act|last=Barnes|first=Patricia|date=2019-10-04|website=Forbes|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> However, the Supreme Court's opinion did not explicitly mention public-sector workers.<ref name= Newsweek>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/what-wednesdays-supreme-court-case-could-mean-age-discrimination-workplace-1480157|title=WHAT WEDNESDAY'S SUPREME COURT CASE COULD MEAN FOR AGE DISCRIMINATION IN THE WORKPLACE|last=Moyler|first=Hunter|date=2020-01-14|website=Newsweek|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> A later opinion, ''[[University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center v. Nassar]]'' (2013) applied the same 'but for' standard to [[Workplace retaliation|retaliation claims]].\n\n''[[Babb v. Wilkie]]'', No. 18-882, , 589 U.S. ___ (2020), is a case of the United States Supreme Court in which the justices considered the scope of protections for federal employees in the [[Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967]]. Specifically, the Court ruled that plaintiffs only need to prove that age was a [[Mixed motive discrimination|motivating factor]] in the decision in order to sue.<ref name=BabbSCOTUS>{{ussc|name=Babb v. Wilkie|volume=589|year=2020|docket=18-882}}</ref> However, establishing [[Sine qua non#\"But-for\" causation in law|but for]] causation is still necessary in determining the appropriate remedy. If a plaintiff can establish that the age was the determinining factor in the employment outcome, they may be entitled to compensatory damages or other relief relating to the end result of the employment decision.<ref name= LawDaily>{{cite web|url=http://www.employmentlawdaily.com/index.php/news/supreme-court-to-determine-whether-but-for-causation-required-in-federal-sector-adea-claims/|title=Supreme Court to determine whether \u2018but-for\u2019 causation required in federal-sector ADEA claims\n|date=2019-07-02|website=Employment Law Daily|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/employment/articles/1260655/breaking-federal-workers-can-sue-over-any-age-bias-justices-rule|title=BREAKING: Federal Workers Can Sue Over 'Any' Age Bias, Justices Rule|date=2020-04-06|website=Law360|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Notable activism against age discrimination in the United States==\nThe [[Newsboys Strike of 1899]] fought ageist employment practices targeted against youth by large newspaper syndicates in the Northeast. The strikers demonstrated across the city for several days, effectively stopping circulation of the two papers, along with the news distribution for many [[New England]] cities. The [[Strike action|strike]] lasted two weeks, causing Pulitzer's ''[[New York World]]'' to decrease its circulation from 360,000 papers sold per day to 125,000.<ref>Nasaw, David. (1999) \"Ch. 3: Youse an' yer noble scrap: On strike with the Newsboy Legion in 1899.\" in ''Big Town, Big Time.'' New York: New York Daily News. p. 9.</ref> Although the price of papers was not lowered, the strike was successful in forcing the ''World'' and ''Journal'' to offer full buybacks to their sellers, thus increasing the amount of money that newsies received for their work.<ref>Mott, F.L. (2000) ''American Journalism''. New York: Routledge. p. 598.</ref>\n\nThe [[American Youth Congress]], or AYC, was formed in 1935 to advocate for [[youth rights]] in U.S. politics.<ref>Black, A., Hopkins, J. ''et al.'' (2003) [http://www.nps.gov/archive/elro/glossary/american-youth-congress.htm \"American Youth Congress,\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019032029/http://www.nps.gov/archive/elro/glossary/american-youth-congress.htm |date=October 19, 2007 }} ''The Eleanor Roosevelt Papers.'' Teaching Eleanor Roosevelt. Hyde Park, New York: Eleanor Roosevelt National Historic Site. Retrieved 7/30/07.</ref>\nIt ended in 1940.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://newdeal.feri.org/er/er26.htm |title=Eleanor Roosevelt, \"Why I Still Believe in the Youth Congress,\" in New Deal Network: Selected Writings of Eleanor Roosevelt, originally published in ''Liberty'', (April 1940): 30-32. |access-date=2005-07-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006022108/http://newdeal.feri.org/er/er26.htm |archive-date=2016-10-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[AARP]] was founded in 1958 by [[Ethel Percy Andrus]] (a retired educator from California) and Leonard Davis (later the founder of the [[Colonial Penn Life Insurance Company|Colonial Penn Group]] of insurance companies).<ref>{{cite news|work=Los Angeles Times|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/jan/23/local/me-15772|date=January 23, 2001|title=Local: Obituary}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.usc.edu/6078/Obituary-AARP-founder-philanthropist-Leonard-Davis-76/|work=USC News|title=AARP Founder: Philanthropist Leonard Davis, 76}}</ref> Its stated mission is \"to empower people to choose how they live as they age\".<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aarp.org/about-aarp/|title=About AARP|last=|first=|date=|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> It is an influential [[lobbying]] group in the United States focusing largely on issues affecting the elderly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thenonprofittimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/8-1-15_Top50PI.pdf|title=The 2015 Power & Influence Top 50|last=|first=|date=August 31, 2015|website=The NonProfit Times|publisher=The NonProfit Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/top-lobbyists/258317-top-lobbyists-2015-grassroots|title=Top Lobbyists 2015: Grassroots|last=Dickson|first=Rebecca|date=October 28, 2015|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref>  \n\nThe [[Gray Panthers]] was formed in 1970 by [[Maggie Kuhn]], with a goal of eliminating [[mandatory retirement]]; they now work on many [[social justice]] issues including eliminating ageism.<ref>Kuhn, M., Long, C. and Quinn, L. (1991) ''No Stone Unturned: the Life and Times of Maggie Kuhn.'' Ballantine Books.</ref><ref>https://www.aarp.org/politics-society/history/champions-of-aging-photos/older-american-maggie-kuhn-gray-panthers/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.graypanthersnyc.org/about_us/ |title=About Us |publisher=Gray Panthers Nyc |date=2018-08-27 |accessdate=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Youth Liberation of Ann Arbor]] started in 1970 to promote youth and fight ageism.\n\n[[Three O'Clock Lobby]] formed in 1976 to promote [[youth participation]] throughout traditionally ageist government structures in Michigan.\n\nOld Lesbians Organizing for Change was founded in 1987 in response to the combination of ageism and sexism affecting older lesbians. Their initial meeting was inspired by the publication of the book ''[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781883523404 Look Me in the Eye: Old Women, Aging and Ageism]'' by [[Barbara Macdonald]] and Cynthia Rich in 1983.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite web\n | url=http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss547_bioghist.html\n | title=Old Lesbians Organizing for Change Records\n | accessdate=27 March 2015\n}}</ref> The mission of the organization is to \"eliminate the oppression of ageism and to stand in solidarity against all oppressions\" through \u201c[the] cooperative community of Old Lesbian feminist activists from many backgrounds working for justice and the well-being of all old lesbians.\u201d<ref>[https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/c8z89fjx/  Old Lesbians Organizing for Change records 1986-1992 (Box 1) housed in the UCLA Library Special Collections]</ref>  \n\n[[Americans for a Society Free from Age Restrictions]] formed in 1996 to advance the civil and human rights of young people through eliminating ageist laws targeted against young people, and to help youth counter ageism in America.<ref>{{cite web|work=ASFAR |year=2006 |url=http://www.asfar.org/articles.php |title=Americans for a Society Free from Age Restrictions Articles of Incorporation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609192032/http://www.asfar.org/articles.php |archive-date=9 June 2007}}</ref> \n\nThe [[National Youth Rights Association]] started in 1998 to promote awareness of the legal and human rights of young people in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|work=National Youth Rights Association|year=2001|url=http://www.youthrights.org/docs/nyraarticlesofinc.pdf|title=National Youth Rights Association Articles of Incorporation (Partial)}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Freechild Project]] was formed in 2001 to identify, unify and promote diverse opportunities for youth engagement in social change by fighting ageism. In 2002 the Freechild Project created an information and training initiative to provide resources to youth organizations and schools focused on youth rights.<ref>(n.d.) [http://www.freechild.org/SNAYR/index.htm Survey of North American Youth Rights] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206100316/http://www.freechild.org/SNAYR/index.htm |date=6 February 2007 }} The Freechild Project website.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ageism]]\n*[[Elder law]]\n*[[History of youth rights in the United States]]\n*[[Nursing home residents' rights]]\n*[[Youth rights]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* Axon, K. (n.d.) [https://web.archive.org/web/20080215235519/http://www.asfar.org/zine/1st/Pedophobia.html ''The Anti-Child Bias of Children's Advocacy Groups''] Chicago, IL: [[Americans for a Society Free from Age Restrictions]].\n* Butler, T., & Berret, B. (2011). A generation lost:  the reality of age discrimination in today's hiring practices.  ''Journal of Management and Marketing Research'', 9, 1-11. Academic Search Complete. Web. 21 Sept. 2013.\n* {{Cite book|title =Why Survive? Being Old In America  |last = Butler|first = Robert|author-link= Robert N. Butler| publisher =Harper & Row  | year =1975  | location =  | pages =496 pages  | url =https://books.google.com/?id=_EJpAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Why+Survive%22&dq=%22Why+Survive%22  | doi =  | isbn=0-06-010591-7}}\n* ''The Children's Rights Movement: Overcoming the Oppression of Young People'', edited by Beatrice and Ronald Gross (Garden City, NY: Anchor Press/Doubleday, 1977.\n* Kuhn, M., Long, C. and Quinn, L. (1991) ''No Stone Unturned: the Life and Times of [[Maggie Kuhn]]''. Ballantine Books.\n* [[John Holt (educator)|Holt, J.]] (1974). ''[[Escape from Childhood]]: The Needs and Rights of Children''. Boston: E. P. Dutton.\n* {{Cite book|title = Look Me in the Eye: Old Women, Aging and Ageism|last = Macdonald|first = Barbara|author-link = Barbara Macdonald| publisher = Spinsters Ink Books|year = 1983|isbn = 978-1883523404|location = |pages = |last2 = Rich|first2 = Cynthia|url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781883523404}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:Ageism]]\n[[Category:Discrimination in the United States]]\n[[Category:Old age in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Diannaa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Attribution: text was copied fromMandatory retirementandAge Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967on April 25, 2020. Please see the history of those pages for full attribution.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Age_discrimination_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Bahujan Samaj Party", "text_new": "{{For|the Nepalese party|Bahujan Samaj Party, punjab hi this is me }}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox Indian Political Party\n |name            = Bahujan Samaj Party\n |logo            = [[File:Elephant Bahujan Samaj Party.svg|200px|Bahujan Samaj Party Flag]]\n |abbreviation    = BSP\n |colorcode       = {{Bahujan Samaj Party/meta/color}}\n |alliance        = \n |president       = [[Mayawati]]<ref>{{cite web |author=livemint |title=Mayawati says she will remain BSP president for next 20 years|website=livemint.com|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/PTjTr92SwEcPJ0ItjL4YuL/BSP-should-be-ready-to-fight-polls-solo-says-Mayawati.html|accessdate=2018-05-26}}</ref>\n |secretary       = \n* [[Satish Chandra Mishra]]\n* [[R S Kushwaha]]\n* [[Munquad Ali]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bsp-munquad-ali-up-party-chief-danish-ali-shyam-singh-yadav-party-leader-lok-sabha-1578345-2019-08-07|title=BSP appoints Munquad Ali as UP party chief, Danish Ali removed as leader in LS|last=LucknowAugust 7|first=India Today Web Desk|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>\n* Ram Achal Rajbhar\n* Mewalal Gautam<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/ex-bjp-leader-dayashankar-released-from-mau-jail/articleshow/53584371.cms |title=EX-BJP leader Dayashankar released from Mau jail|date=2016-08-07|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n* [[R Sridhar]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Maya's personal aide is named party's new general secretary |work=Indian Express |date=13 December 2016 |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/mayawati-replaces-personal-aide-with-another-as-bsp-general-secretary-prasad-maurya-manoj-kumar-4424113/lite/ |accessdate=2016-03-13}}</ref>\n |foundation       = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|p=y|1984|04|14}}\n |founder          = [[Kanshi Ram]]\n|rajyasabha_leader = [[Satish Chandra Mishra]]\n|loksabha_leader = [[Kunwar Danish Ali]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/bsp-reappoints-danish-ali-as-its-ls-leader/article29902155.ece|title=BSP reappoints Danish Ali as its LS leader|date=2019-11-06|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-12-26|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n |predecessor      = [[Dalit Shoshit Samaj Sangharsh Samiti|DSSSS]]\n |headquarters     = 12, Gurudwara Rakabganj Road, [[New Delhi]], [[India]]-110001\n |publication      = Bahujan Samaj Bulletin \n |wing4_title      = Volunteer's wing\n |wing4            = [[Bahujan Volunteer Force]]\n |eci              = [[List of political parties in India|National Party]]\n |membership       = \n |ideology         = [[Social equality]]<ref>{{cite news |work=Deccan Herald |title=BSP stands for social equality |date=11 February 2008 |url=http://archive.deccanherald.com/DeccanHerald.com/Content/Feb122008/district2008021151743.asp |accessdate=2016-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314114540/http://archive.deccanherald.com/DeccanHerald.com/Content/Feb122008/district2008021151743.asp |archive-date=14 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br />[[Social justice]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Cong damaged cause of social justice: Mayawati |work=Hindustan Times |date=10 April 2009 |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/cong-damaged-cause-of-social-justice-mayawati/story-4brhIxzP1pQeE3FJlOC7KP.html |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref><br />[[Self-Respect Movement|Self respect]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Ms. Mayawati said she would devote her life for the self-respect movement.|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/a-chamar-will-be-my-successor-mayawati/article3097137.ece |work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n |position         = [[Centre-left politics|Centre-left]]<ref name=\"elections.in\">{{cite web|work=Elections.in|title=Bahujan Samaj Party (BSP)|url=http://www.elections.in/political-parties-in-india/bahujan-samaj-party.html|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>  \n |colours          = {{Color box|{{Bahujan Samaj Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Blue]]\n |loksabha_seats   = {{Composition bar|10|543|hex={{Bahujan Samaj Party/meta/color}}}}\n |rajyasabha_seats = {{Composition bar|4|245|hex=#0000FF}}\n |no_states         = {{Composition bar|0|31|hex={{Bahujan Samaj Party/meta/color}}}}\n| state_seats_name =[[Vidhan Sabha]] & [[Vidhan Parishad]]\n| state_seats      = {{hidden\n|Indian states \n|headerstyle=background:#ccccff\n|style=text-align:center; |{{Composition bar|18|403|hex={{Bahujan Samaj Party/meta/color}}}}([[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]])\n<br />{{Composition bar|8|100||hex={{Bahujan Samaj Party/meta/color}}}}([[Uttar Pradesh Vidhan Parishad]])<br/>{{Composition bar|2|230||hex={{Bahujan Samaj Party/meta/color}}}}([[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]])<br/>{{Composition bar|2|90||hex={{Bahujan Samaj Party/meta/color}}}}([[Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly]])}}\n |website          = {{URL|http://bspindia.org/}} \n |symbol           =[[File:Indian Election Symbol Elephant.png|150px|center|Elephant]]\n}} \n\nThe '''Bahujan Samaj Party''' ('''BSP''') is a [[List of political parties in India#National parties|national level]] political party in India that was formed to represent Bahujans (literally means \"people in majority\"), referring to [[Scheduled Castes]], [[Scheduled Tribes]],  and [[Other Backward Castes]] (OBC), along with religious minorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/bahujan-samaj-party|title=BAHUJAN SAMAJ PARTY - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> According to [[Kanshi Ram]], when he founded the party in 1984, the Bahujans comprised 85 percent of India's population, but were divided into 6,000 different castes.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-rMW03l_gx0C&pg=PA390&lpg=PA390&dq=85%25+bahujan#v=onepage&q=85%25%20bahujan&f=false|title=India's Silent Revolution: The Rise of the Lower Castes in North India|last=Jaffrelot|first=Christophe|date=2003|publisher=Hurst|isbn=9781850653981|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://countercurrents.org/2017/04/28/the-contradictory-bahujan-of-the-bsp/|title=The Contradictory Bahujan of the BSP \u2013 Countercurrents|date=2017-04-28|work=Countercurrents|access-date=2018-03-09|language=en-US}}</ref> The party claims to be inspired by the philosophy of [[Gautama Buddha]], [[B. R. Ambedkar]], [[Mahatma Jyotiba Phule]], [[Narayana Guru]], [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy]] and [[Shahu of Kolhapur|Chhatrapati Shahuji Maharaj]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The ground flanked by giant-sized cut-outs of BSP's icons -- Babasaheb Ambedkar, Shahuji Maharaj, Jyotiba Phule, Narain Guru, Periyar, and Mayawati herself.|url=http://specials.rediff.com/news/2007/mar/01maya.htm}}</ref> [[Kanshi Ram]] named his prot\u00e9g\u00e9e, [[Mayawati]], as his successor in 2001. The BSP has its main base in the Indian state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] where it was the second-largest party in the [[2019 Indian general election]] with 19.3% of votes<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/elections/lok-sabha/uttar-pradesh/indian-politics-has-undergone-a-tremendous-change-uttar-pradesh-results-the-proof/articleshow/69498432.cms|title=Indian politics has undergone a tremendous change. Uttar Pradesh results the proof|date=2019-05-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-10-07}}</ref> and in the [[2017 Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|2017 Uttar Pradesh elections]] with over 22% of votes.<ref>{{cite web | author=IANS | title=Assembly Elections Results 2017: Political parties with lesser seats get more vote share | website=The Financial Express | date=12 March 2017 | url=http://www.financialexpress.com/elections/assembly-elections-results-2017-political-parties-with-lesser-seats-get-more-vote-share/585280/ | language=la | accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref> Its [[election symbol]] is an elephant.\n\n== {{anchor|Bahujan}} Etymology ==\n\"Bahujan\" is a Pali term frequently found in Buddhist texts, and literally refers to \"the many\", or \"the majority. It appears in the dictum \"[[Bahujana sukhaya bahujana hitaya cha|Bahujana Hitaya Bahujana Sukhaya]]\", or \"The benefit and prosperity of the many\", articulated by [[Gautama Buddha]].<ref name=\"Gurusamy2019\">{{cite book|first=S. |last=Gurusamy|title=Dalit Empowerment in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nqmcDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA98|year= 2013|publisher=MJP Publisher|page=98|id=GGKEY:SW8XELLJGLC}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Madan|first=Gurmukh Ram|title=Buddhism: Its Various Manifestations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LqhhR-hY7VQC&pg=PA47|year=1999|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-7099-728-3|page=47}}</ref><ref name=\"Roy2015\">{{cite encyclopedia|editor-first1=Uday|editor-last1=Chandra|editor-first2=Geir|editor-last2=Heierstad|editor-first3=Kenneth Bo|editor-last3=Nielsen|encyclopedia=The Politics of Caste in West Bengal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7qXbCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA177|title=Transformative politics: The imaginary of the Mulnibasi in West Bengal|first=Indrajit|last=Roy|pages=169\u2013192|year=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-41477-3}}</ref> In his writing, [[B. R. Ambedkar]] used the term to refer to the majority of people in Hindu society that experienced discrimination and oppression on the basis of caste. [[Jotirao Phule]] used the term in a similar context, and compared the lower castes of India to [[Slavery in the United States|slaves in the United States]]. [[Dalit]] and lower-caste writers have suggested this proportion was 85 percent of the population.<ref name=\"Roy2015\"/><ref name=\"Jaffrelot2003\">{{cite book|first=Christophe|last=Jaffrelot|title=India's Silent Revolution: The Rise of the Lower Castes in North India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qJZp5tDuY-gC|year=2003|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-12786-8|page=153}}</ref> Lower-caste people are sometimes collectively referred to as \"bahujan samaj\", or the majority community.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pai |first1=Sudha |title=New Social Engineering Agenda of the Bahujan Samaj Party: Implications for State and National Politics |journal=South Asia: Journal of South Asian Studies |date=2009 |volume=29 |issue=3 |page=339 |doi=10.1080/00856400903374277}}</ref><ref name=Guha>{{cite journal |last1=Guha |first1=Sohini |title=From Ethnic to Multiethnic: The Transformation of the Bahujan Samaj Party in North India |journal=Ethnopolitics |date=2013 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20132 |doi=10.1080/17449057.2011.601850}}</ref> The term has also been translated as \"[[Subaltern (postcolonialism)|subaltern]]\".<ref name=Guha/> The precise set of caste groups described as \"Bahujan\" has varied with context; in the state of [[Maharashtra]], for example, the term has often excluded Dalits. However, it always refers to non-''[[Dvija]]'', or twice-born, castes, and thus does not include [[Brahmin]]s, [[Kshatriya]]s, or [[Vaishya]]s.<ref name=\"VoraPalshikar2003\">{{cite book|first1=Rajendra|last1=Vora|first2=Suhas|last2=Palshikar|title=Indian Democracy: Meanings and Practices|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rLWICwAAQBAJ&pg=PT249|year=2003|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-93-5150-019-3|pages=249\u2013250}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/topic/dvija|title=Dvija|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|year=2014|accessdate=9 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kumar |first1=Pradeep |title=Dalits and the BSP in Uttar Pradesh: Issues and Challenges |journal=Economic and Political Weekly |date=9 April 1999 |volume=34 |issue=14|pages=822\u2013826|jstor=4407820}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation and structure==\nThe BSP has no separate youth wing; however, youth representation is over 50%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/maya-bsp-has-no-other-outfit-social-media-accounts/articleshow/65113287.cms|title=Maya: BSP has no other outfit, social media accounts - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> BSP has no social media accounts or website.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/lucknow/bsp-has-no-youth-wing-or-official-website-says-mayawati-5272529/|title=BSP has no youth wing or official website, says Mayawati|date=2018-07-24|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en-US}}</ref> Sudhindra Bhadoria, a senior party leader, is the only official spokesperson of the BSP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/opinion/bahujan-samaj-party-has-no-official-facebook-or-twitter-accounts-mayawati-118072400022_1.html|title=Bahujan Samaj Party has no official Facebook or Twitter accounts: Mayawati|last=Standard|first=Business|date=2018-07-24|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology and political positions ==\n=== Ideology ===\nIts self-proclaimed ideology is \"Social Transformation and Economic Emancipation\" of the \"Bahujan Samaj\". The \"Bahujan Samaj\", to them, consists of the lower-caste groups in India like the Scheduled Castes (SC), the Scheduled Tribes (ST) and the Other Backward Classes (OBC). It also includes religious minorities like Sikhs, Muslims, Christians, Parsis, and Buddhists. They see these groups as victims of the \"Manuwadi\" system for millennia, a system which benefited upper-caste Hindus only. [[B. R. Ambedkar]], a champion of lower-caste rights, is an important ideological inspiration. The party claims not to be prejudiced against upper-caste Hindus. In 2008, while addressing the audience, Mayawati said: \"Our policies and ideology are not against any particular caste or religion. If we were anti-upper caste, we would not have given tickets to candidates from upper castes to contest elections\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi/bsp-is-not-anti-upper-caste-mayawati/story-klNh0237WyQ4xVrIDiZtKI.html|title=BSP is not anti-upper caste: Mayawati|date=2008-11-26|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2019-05-19}}</ref> [[Satish Chandra Mishra]], a BSP senior leader, is upper caste. The party also believe in egalitarianism and hold a strong emphasis on social justice.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Strategy ===\nThe Bahujan Samaj Party was founded on the birth anniversary of [[B. R. Ambedkar]], 14 April 1984, by Kanshi Ram,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Singh|first1=Pitam|title=Women legislators in Indian politics|date=2003|publisher=Concept Pub. Co.|location=New Delhi|isbn=8180690199|pages=101|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ldhazU_vvQcC&pg=PA101&lpg=PA101&dq=14th+april+1984+bsp#v=onepage&q=14th%20april%201984%20bsp&f=false}}</ref> who named former schoolteacher, Mayawati, as his successor of BSP in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kanshi Ram declares Mayawati as his successor|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2001/dec/15bsp.htm|agency=Rediff News |date=15 December 2001 |first=Sharat |last=Pradhan}}</ref>\n\n Lesser-known figures from the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]] have been used as [[Dalit]] icons by the BSP, such as [[Avantibai]], [[Uda Devi]], Mahaviri Devi,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/interviews/BSP-used-Dalit-viranganas-to-build-Mayas-image/articleshow/2090111.cms|title=BSP used Dalit viranganas to build Maya's image - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref> [[Jhalkaribai]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2016may15/1463298298.html|title=Book review: Kanshiram: Leader of the Dalits {{!}} TwoCircles.net|last=TwoCircles.net|website=twocircles.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref> [[Matadin Bhangi]], Ballu Mehtar, Vira Pasi, [[Banke Chamar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2005/nov/10revolt.htm|title=Dalits took part in 1857 revolt: Study|website=rediff.com|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref> and [[Chetram Jatav]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/1040901/asp/opinion/story_3675790.asp|title=The Telegraph - Calcutta : Opinion|website=telegraphindia.com|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref> the social scientist Badri Narayan Tiwari has noted that {{quote|Dalit intellectuals supported by BSP, which is trying to mobilize grassroot Dalits using local heroes, histories, myths and legends found a wealth of resources in the oral history of the regions of [Uttar Pradesh] centering around the 1857 rebellion. The political strategy of the party is to tell and retell the stories of these heroes, build memorials and organize celebrations around their stories repeatedly to build a collective memory in the psyche of the people. The stories are narrated in such a manner that the Dalits imagine the story of the making of a nation in which they played a significant role.<ref name=\"conference\">{{cite paper |url=http://www.csas.ed.ac.uk/mutiny/confpapers/Tiwari-Paper.pdf |pages=13, 27, 33 |title=Identity and Narratives: Dalits and memories of 1857 |first=Badri Narayan |last=Tiwari |publisher=University of Edinburgh: Mutiny at the Margins Conference |year=2007}}</ref>}}\n\n== History ==\nThe party's power grew quickly with seats in the [[Legislative Assembly of Uttar Pradesh]] and the [[Lok Sabha]], the [[lower house]] of the [[Parliament of India]]. In 1993, following the assembly elections, Mayawati formed a coalition with [[Samajwadi Party]] president [[Mulayam Singh Yadav]] as [[Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh|Chief Minister]]. On 2 June 1995, she withdrew support from his government, which led to a major incident where Yadav was accused of sending his goons to keep her party legislators hostage at a [[Lucknow]] guest house and shout casteist abuses at her.<ref>{{cite news |title=Report indicting Mulayam Singh Yadav comes handy for BJP |work=India Today |date=15 August 1996 |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/report-indicting-mulayam-singh-yadav-comes-handy-for-bjp/1/282144.html |accessdate=2016-05-12}}</ref> Since this event, they have regarded each other publicly as chief rivals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ghildiyal|first1=Subodh|title=Why Mayawati cannot stand Mulayam|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Why-Mayawati-cannot-stand-Mulayam/articleshow/1387716.cms}}</ref>\n\nMayawati then obtained support from the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) to become Chief Minister on 3 June 1995. In October 1995, the BJP withdrew their support and fresh elections were called after a period of [[President's Rule]]. In 2003, Mayawati resigned from her own government to prove that she was not \"hungry for power\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Uttar Pradesh chief quits |work=BBC News |date=26 August 2003 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3181313.stm |accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref> and asked the BJP-run [[Government of India]] to remove [[Ministry of Tourism (India)|Union Tourism and Culture Minister]], [[Jagmohan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayawati offers to resign |work=The Times of India |date=25 August 2003 |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2003-08-25/news/27544146_1_heritage-corridor-scam-bjp-ministers-bsp-leader |accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref> In 2007, she began leading a BSP-formed government with an absolute majority for a full five-year term.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayawati rules Uttar Pradesh |work=India Today |date=21 May 2007 |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/bsp-pride-mayawati/1/155789.html |accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bahujan Samaj Party Ekla chalo re.jpg|right|thumb|Bahujan Samaj Party claims to represent the low and lowly. A man carrying the BSP flag.]]\n\n=== Silver jubilee ===\nBahujan Samaj Party on 14 April 2009 celebrated its silver jubilee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/JHmKf3eHPRj2ff2foE5KxL/BSP-celebrates-silver-jubilee-with-golden-hopes.html|title=BSP celebrates silver jubilee with golden hopes|last=Mathew|first=Liz|date=2009-04-14|website=Live Mint|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref> ''Manywar Shri Kanshi Ramji Shahri Garib Awas Yojna'', housing scheme for poor was launched by Lucknow Development Authority (LDA).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/LDA-ready-with-its-gift-for-BSP-silver-jubilee/articleshow/5649184.cms|title=LDA ready with its gift for BSP silver jubilee|last=Shah|first=Pankaj|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref> Role of Mayawati was discussed in BSP's success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/BfUgIQbCr0xrgTr6cdHfjK/25-years-on-what8217s-next-for-Mayawati.html|title=25 years on, what's next for Mayawati?|last=Singh|first=Pallavi|date=2009-11-18|website=Live Mint|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref> Mass rally was organised in [[Lucknow]] with 10000 police personnel on duty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sify.com/news/bsp-supporters-congregate-in-lucknow-to-celebrate-party-s-25-years-news-national-kdpqOgccghbsi.html|title=BSP supporters congregate in Lucknow to celebrate party's 25 years|website=Sify|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref> It was 305th and largest rally of BSP since 1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2010/mar/15/lucknow-braces-for-mega-bsp-rally-today-139473.html|title=Lucknow braces for mega BSP rally today|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref> As per [[Observer Research Foundation]], within 25 years BSP became third largest political party of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orfonline.org/research/bsps-25-year-journey-what-next/|title=BSP's 25-year Journey: What Next?|last=Misra|first=Satish|website=ORF|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Success in 2007 ===\nThe results of the May 2007 [[2007 Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|Uttar Pradesh state assembly election]] saw the BSP emerge as a sole majority party, the first to do so since 1991. Mayawati began her fourth term as [[Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]] and took her oath of office along with 50 ministers of cabinet and state rank on 13 May 2007, at Rajbhawan in the state capital of [[Lucknow]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mayawati takes oath as UP CM|url=http://www.ndtv.com/video/player/news/mayawati-takes-oath-as-up-cm/13607|work=NDTV}}</ref> Most importantly, the majority achieved in large part was due to the party's ability to take away majority of upper castes votes from their traditional party, the BJP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|title=Upper castes played crucial role in bsp victory in up assembly elections|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-upper-castes-played-crucial-role-in-bsp-victory-in-up-assembly-elections-1096355}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Flags of \"Bahujan Samaj Party\" at Shivaji Park.png|thumb|Flags of \"Bahujan Samaj Party\" at [[Shivaji Park]], [[Mumbai]].]]\n\nThe party could manage only 80 seats in 2012 as against 206 in 2007 assembly elections. BSP government was the first in the history of Uttar Pradesh to complete its full five-year term.<ref>http://eciresults.nic.in/PartyWiseResult.htm</ref> On 26 May 2018, Ram Achal Rajbhar was replaced by [[R S Kushwaha]] as the president of UP unit.<ref>https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/mayawati-effects-major-reshuffle-in-bsp-rs-kushwaha-appointed-state-president-in-up/1182038/</ref>\n\n=== 2014 Lok Sabha Elections ===\nThe 2014 national Lok Sabha elections saw the BSP become the third-largest national party of India in terms of vote percentage, having 4.2% of the vote across the country but gaining no seats.<ref>{{cite news|title=BSP gets third-largest vote share, but no seat|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/elections-2014/bsp-gets-third-largest-vote-share-but-no-seat-114051700178_1.html|work=Business Standard}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 Lok Sabha Elections ''Mahagathbandhan''===\nPrior to the 2019 Lok Sabha elections, BSP formed a ''[[Mahagathbandhan]].'' The ''Mahagathbandhan'' (or Grand Alliance), or simply the ''Gathbandhan'' (Alliance),<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/sp-bsp-rld-thagbandhan-wont-cross-double-digits/article26837237.ece 'SP-BSP-RLD thagbandhan won't cross double digits'], The Hindu (April 14, 2019) {{verify source |date=August 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/895646183]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/895469470]] cite #3 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/politics/110419/we-can-become-kingmakers-bsp-chief-mayawati-eggs-on-party-workers.html|title=We can become kingmakers: BSP chief Mayawati eggs on party workers|last=p|first=shilpa|date=2019-04-11|website=Deccan Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2019-04-13}} {{verify source |date=August 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/895646183]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/895469470]] cite #4 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> is an anti-[[Indian National Congress|Congress]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/elections/lok-sabha-2019/bsp-will-play-a-role-in-balance-of-power-at-centre-mayawati/article26799236.ece|title=BSP will play a role in \u2018balance of power\u2019 at Centre: Mayawati|date=2019-04-10|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-04-13|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}} {{verify source |date=August 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/895646183]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/895469470]] cite #5 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> anti-[[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/lok-sabha-elections/lok-sabha-election-2019-mayawati-should-be-pm-says-pawan-kalyan-after-poll-pact-with-bsp-she-nods/story-3ft4F47Wc22UiZaE32ZgFJ.html|title=Mayawati should be PM, says Pawan Kalyan after poll pact with BSP. She nods|date=2019-03-15|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}} {{verify source |date=August 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/895646183]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/895469470]] cite #6 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> Indian political alliance formed in the run-up to the [[2019 Indian general election|2019 general election]] under the leadership of two former Chief Ministers of Uttar Pradesh, [[Akhilesh Yadav]] of the [[Samajwadi Party]] and [[Mayawati]] of the Bahujan Samaj Party, along with [[Ajit Singh (politician)|Ajit Singh]]\u2019s [[Rashtriya Lok Dal]] and several other political parties, contesting in different states of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/2019-lok-sabha-election-akhilesh-yadav-on-mayawati-as-pm-candidate-will-be-very-happy-1976766|title=Will Be Very Happy, Says Akhilesh Yadav On Mayawati As PM Candidate|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2019-03-20}} {{verify source |date=August 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/895646183]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/895469470]] cite #7 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/akhilesh-hints--at-supporting--maya-as-pm.html|title=Akhilesh hints at supporting Maya as PM|last=Pioneer|first=The|website=The Pioneer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}} {{verify source |date=August 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/895646183]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/895469470]] cite #8 - please veri